\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 POLICY \highlight\uc2  SYNERGY TO SUPPORT NATIONAL  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  RECOVERY: AMRO REPORT\b0\par\par\uc2 1,432 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 February 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The economyof Indonesia remains resilient amid the COVID-19 pandemic, according to the 2020 Annual Consultation Report on Indonesia, published by the ASEAN+3 Macroeconomic Research Office (AMRO) and received here on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 A prompt recalibration of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mix and the enactment of large \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures have provided timely support to affected households, businesses, and the financial sector, as well as safeguarded macroeconomic and financial stability, the report stated.\par \par \uc2 The report was produced based on AMRO\u8217\'20\'19s virtual 2020 annual consultation visit to Indonesia and data and information available as of December 31, 2020.\par \par \uc2 Recent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments\par \par \uc2 According to AMRO\u8217\'20\'19s report on recent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments in Indonesia, the country"s national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity has gradually turned around from a sharp contraction that was triggered by the imposition of large-scale social restrictions in the second quarter of 2020.\par \par \uc2 According to Statistics Indonesia data released on February 5 this year, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the whole of 2020 is expected to contract by 2.1 percent, which is modest relative to regional peers.\par \par \uc2 However, continued supportive \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy, together with the widespread availability of COVID-19 vaccines, are expected to underpin a rebound in growth to 4.9 percent in 2021.\par \par \uc2 An improvement in the current account balance and resumption of capital inflows have buttressed the external position and supported the rupiah. While imports have remained weak in the backdrop of muted domestic demand, exports have picked up due to a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rebound and a recovery in commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, improved investor sentiment and rebalancing of global portfolios have sustained inflows into the government bond market in recent months, supporting the external position.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, strong capital buffers supported by regulatory forbearance have underpinned overall banking system resilience, although the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn has affected banks\u8217\'20\'19 asset quality to some extent.\par \par \uc2 To assist businesses affected by the pandemic, including micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs), loan quality assessment and restructuring criteria have been relaxed to allow banks to maintain their lending to the business sector.\par \par \uc2 Extraordinary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 has actively recalibrated its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mix to maintain stability and support recovery.\par \par \uc2 The measures it has employed include providing substantial liquidity support through quantitative easing and conducting triple interventions in the foreign exchange spot, domestic non-deliverable forward, and secondary government bond markets to provide a cushion against volatility shocks while maintaining rupiah flexibility.\par \par \uc2 In light of subdued inflation, the BI has lowered its benchmark rate, the seven-day reverse repo rate, by 125 basis points to 3.75 percent as of end-2020.\par \par \uc2 Macroprudential measures have also been eased to stimulate financing to priority sectors while maintaining financial system resilience to support national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 The total amount of liquidity injected into the money market and banking system, notably through lowering the statutory reserve requirements, term repos, foreign exchange swaps, as well as purchase of government bonds in the secondary market, is estimated at Rp727 trillion, or 4.7 percent of the GDP (Gross Domestic Product), as of end-2020.\par \par \uc2 BI has also accelerated the implementation of the 2025 Payment System Blueprint initiatives to aid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial digitalization.\par \par \uc2 Besides, sizable \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  packages have been rolled out to support affected households and businesses.\par \par \uc2 The 2020 revised \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  introduced \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  packages totaling Rp695 trillion, or about 4.4 percent of the GDP, to cover COVID-19 healthcare \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social assistance to affected households, sectoral and regional aid (known as the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods package), and support to businesses, including both MSMEs and bigger firms (non-\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods package).\par \par \uc2 As of the end of December last year, about 84.3 percent of the packages have been disbursed. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  packages have also been approved for the 2021 \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to ensure continued support to the healthcare sector, affected households and communities, and strengthen structural reforms for a sustainable recovery.\par \par \uc2 A forward-looking \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Perppu 1/2020 (converted into Law 2/2020), has been issued to suspend the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  ceiling of 3 percent of the GDP between 2020 and 2022.\par \par \uc2 It also allows BI to purchase government bonds in the primary market, guided by prudent principles. BI has purchased government bonds through market-based mechanisms, in line with a joint decree between the Finance Minister and BI Governor dated April, 2020.\par \par \uc2 Under a one-off burden sharing agreement in July, 2020, BI has also agreed to finance the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods package through private placements and absorb the entire interest cost of this package, as well as share part of the interest cost of the non-\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods package related to corporate support.\par \par \uc2 Last but not least, the recent passage of the Omnibus Law on Job Creation is expected to be a major breakthrough in improving the investment climate and facilitating job creation.\par \par \uc2 Risks, vulnerabilities, challenges\par \par \uc2 With rapid vaccine development lifting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook in 2021, downside risks stem mainly from ongoing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the pandemic trajectory in the short-term, the AMRO report stated.\par \par \uc2 While \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is expected to gain further momentum under continued supportive monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, the pace of the rebound may be weighed down by current elevated infection rates and tightened social restrictions, it added.\par \par \uc2 Against the backdrop of recent progress in vaccine development, possible delays in inoculation or weaker-than-expected vaccine efficacy could trigger renewed lockdowns in major economies and cast a shadow on global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects, which would in turn affect Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exports and growth outlook.\par \par \uc2 On the upside, a swift and effective vaccination program conducted on a large-scale will enable a stronger recovery for Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 The government\u8217\'20\'19s gross financing needs rose sharply in 2020, and will remain elevated in 2021, due to the allocation of sizable \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  packages to support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 An increase in precautionary savings, weaker demand for credit, and BI financing under the burden sharing scheme have allowed the higher \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be financed without pushing up bond yields in 2020.\par \par \uc2 In addition, improved investor sentiment and rebalancing of global portfolios have sustained inflows to the government bond market in recent months. That said, financing pressure may tighten when savings behavior and credit demand normalizes in tandem with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, the report stated.\par \par \uc2 The pandemic has underscored the importance of rebuilding \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  space in the medium term. The implementation of a consistently sound monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework has enabled Indonesia to build up \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  space over the years and gain credibility in the markets.\par \par \uc2 However, with the implementation of large \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  packages in 2020 and 2021, the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  space is estimated to have shrunk against the backdrop of rising debt levels. This could be further aggravated by a decline in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue due to a planned reduction in the corporate income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate.\par \par \uc2 Future \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  considerations\par \par \uc2 Effective implementation of the current \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mix, on both monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  fronts, is expected to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in 2021.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy is aimed at achieving a smooth exit from the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures. The phasing out of BI\u8217\'20\'19s exceptional \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  financing should be done in conjunction with the implementation of a credible \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation plan, the AMRO report said.\par \par \uc2 In that regard, the government\u8217\'20\'19s commitment to restore the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  rules from 2023 onwards will help to anchor market confidence. The authorities should consider consolidating the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position through raising \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue and enhancing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  efficiency, the AMRO report stated.\par \par \uc2 The pace and timing of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s exit from extraordinary \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures should also be calibrated within the broader context of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments in advanced economies, in particular the US, it added.\par \par \uc2 In the longer run, efforts on financial deepening, in particular, broadening the domestic investor base, will increase the resilience of the bond market against capital flow volatility shocks, the report said.\par \par \uc2 In addition, recent initiatives such as the Blueprint for Money Market Development 2025 that aim to build a conducive ecosystem for foreign exchange and money markets, are expected to accelerate financial market developments in the years ahead.\par \par \uc2 Continued reforms in the areas of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  diversification, investment climate, infrastructure and human capital development, and digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , would also increase Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s resilience against future shocks, the report said.\par \par \uc2 *) The ASEAN+3 Macroeconomic Research Office (AMRO) is an international organization established to contribute towards securing macroeconomic and financial stability of the ASEAN+3 region, which includes 10 members of the \uc2 Association of Southeast Asian Nations\uc2  (ASEAN) and China; Hong Kong, China; Japan; and, Korea.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/A/H-SHT/H-SHT) 18-02-2021 20:38:38\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020210218eh2i00105\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
