\par\par \b \uc2 Luxury car  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  cut may be 'off target'\b0\par\par\uc2 Norman Harsono, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 916 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 February 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The government's plan to cut the luxury goods sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PPnBM) on new cars might not automatically lead to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, say experts, as job losses, business closures and mobility restrictions amid the prolonged COVID-19 health emergency continue to limit consumer demand.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  announced in a statement on Feb. 11 that the luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut would apply to sedans and two-wheel drive vehicles with engines of 1,500 cc and below starting on March 1.\par \par \uc2 Under the new scheme, a 100 percent luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut applies for the first three months and a 50 percent luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut applies for the succeeding three months. The government expects the scheme to significantly lower the price of new cars, which are currently subject to a luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  that ranges from 10 percent to 200 percent of a good's sales price in accordance with Law No. 42/2009.\par \par \uc2 "This program does not offer anything to improve [consumer] purchasing power, even though the price [will be] lower," research director Piter Abdullah of the Center of Reform on Economics (CORE) Indonesia told a virtual press briefing on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Piter criticized the luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentive for new car purchases as "off target", as lower-middle income consumers had received "the hardest blow to their purchasing power" compared with other income classes. Many workers in the lower-middle income group, both formal and informal, had lost their sources of income last year through job losses or business closures during the coronavirus-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crunch.\par \par \uc2 "Lowering vehicle \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not restore their purchasing power," he stressed.\par \par \uc2 More broadly, the government expects the luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut to stimulate consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a key driver of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that contributes more than 50 percent to gross domestic product (GDP).\par \par \uc2 Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  fell 2.63 percent year-on-year (yoy) in 2020, led by a decline in retail sales, goods imports and wholesale car sales, according to Statistics Indonesia (BPS).\par \par \uc2 The latest BPS data also showed that, compared with other manufacturing sectors, the automotive industry booked the sharpest fourth-quarter decline of 18.98 percent yoy as automakers slowed car and motorcycle production.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shrank 2.07 percent in 2020, the first annual contraction since the 1998 Asian financial crisis. Meanwhile, the unemployment rate reached 7.07 percent in August 2020 compared with 5.23 percent in August 2019 as businesses either laid off employees or shut down operations.\par \par \uc2 The government decided to introduce the luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut in March in an attempt to encourage some growth in the first quarter of 2021, which would in turn create positive sentiment for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery this year. The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut also aimed to capitalize on the Idul Fitri holiday in May, one of the country's biggest shopping seasons.\par \par \uc2 The Office of the Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister also expected the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK) \uc2 to support the luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut by revising its \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  to allow zero percent down payment for car purchases.\par \par \uc2 Domestic car sales slumped 50 percent on an annual basis in 2020 to 532,407 vehicles from 1.03 million vehicles in 2019, according to Association of Indonesian Automotive Manufacturers (Gaikindo). Its data also showed that sales in January amounted to just 52,910 cars, down 34.2 percent from 80,435 cars in January 2020.\par \par \uc2 Economist Bhima Yudhistira of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) said the ongoing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM) imposed on the densely populated islands of Java and Bali had also reduced the demand for new cars. Meanwhile, consumers still largely prioritized the purchase of everyday goods, he added.\par \par \uc2 "Buying motor vehicles is not a main priority. It remains a tertiary priority, even among the middle classes," Bhima said by text message.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, chairman Jongkie Sugiarto of Gaikindo toldThe Jakarta Poston Tuesdaythat automakers expected the new luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  scheme to help push up sales by roughly 40 percent in March, April and May.\par \par \uc2 "Automakers will be competing to win over consumers [looking] to buy new cars. They need to sign deals and prepare financing schemes. Everything will run again," said Jongkie.\par \par \uc2 Continuing, he said automakers expected average monthly sales of between 60,000 and 70,000 cars this year, higher than the 2020 monthly average of 50,000 cars sold but lower than the 85,000 to 90,000 cars sold monthly before Indonesia's coronavirus outbreak emerged in March 2020.\par \par \uc2 Jongkie expressed optimism for potential sales once the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut was enacted this March: "We've asked [Gaikindo] members to immediately calculate new prices. There is nothing we can do about sales lost in the next two weeks, but starting March 1, ta-da!"\par \par \uc2 In a December 2020 commentary, \uc2 Fitch Ratings\uc2  estimated that Indonesian automotive sales would reach 700,000 cars this year as a result of limited demand due to high unemployment and COVID-19 mobility restrictions.\par \par \uc2 The credit rating agency's sales projection is higher than 2020 sales figures but lower than 2019 figures.\par \par \uc2 "Despite improvements since June 2020, fundamental demand remains muted. Extended \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the pandemic will see consumers curbing discretionary \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including car purchases," Fitch noted.\par \par \uc2 Separately, Toyota-Astra Motor deputy president director Henry Tanoto and Honda Prospect Motor sales and marketing director Yusak Billy told Kontan.co.id that the two companies were still waiting for the government to issue a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the PPnBM cut for new cars.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210218eh2i00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
