\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA'S BOP POSTED A SURPLUS OF US$2.6 BILLION IN 2020\b0\par\par\uc2 363 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 February 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Indonesia"s balance of payment (BOP) recorded a surplus of US$2.6 billion last year, continuing its surplus of US$4.7 billion a year earlier and reinforcing external resilience amid the COVID-19 pandemic, according to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The development was fueled by a decline in the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the capital and financial account surpluses," Executive Director of the BI Communication Department Erwin Haryono noted in a written statement released on Friday.\par \par \uc2 The BOP posted a low \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of US$0.2 billion in the fourth quarter of 2020, driven by a current account surplus amid the low capital and financial account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Consequently, foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the end of 2020 increased to US$135.9 billion, equivalent to 9.8 months of imports and the government\u8217\'20\'19s foreign debt repayments. The foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are above the international adequacy standard.\par \par \uc2 The current account surplus continued in the fourth quarter of 2020, supported by an increase in the goods trade balance surplus. In the fourth quarter of 2020, the current account posted another surplus of US$0.8 billion, or 0.3 percent of the national gross domestic product (GDP), continuing the surplus of US$1 billion in a quarter earlier, or 0.4 percent of the GDP.\par \par \uc2 Haryono remarked that the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2020 stood at US$4.7 billion, constituting 0.4 percent of the GDP. The current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  plunged sharply as compared to US$30.3 billion, or 2.7 percent of the GDP in 2019.\par \par \uc2 The declining \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was in line with the limited performance of the country"s exports due to low demand in partner countries during the COVID-19 pandemic, coupled with declining imports due to low domestic demand.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the capital and financial accounts in 2020 continued to post a surplus of US$7.9 billion owing to investors" optimism about domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and abating \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in global financial markets, especially in the second semester of 2020.\par \par \uc2 (T.H-SHT/A/S022/S022) 19-02-2021 18:20:47\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020210219eh2j000b5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
