\par\par \b \uc2 Between livelihoods and health concerns: Are we ready for the return of live concerts?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,254 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 March 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 12\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Raka Ibrahim, Contributor, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 "We're all in survival mode now," Wendi Putranto said. "And the government doesn't care that we're dying."\par \par \uc2 After a year of lost opportunities, the 43-year old has a reason to be cynical. M-Bloc, the Jakarta-based venue he serves as program director, has lost more than Rp 2.5 billion (US$173,587) in less than a year and has had to fire at least 12 staff members.\par \par \uc2 It is far from alone in an industry suffering hardship. Since restrictions were imposed on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities across the country last year, Indonesia's previously bustling live concert ecosystem has ground to an abrupt halt. In an economically volatile industry long reliant on revenue from live concerts, this is a catastrophe.\par \par \uc2 "Thousands of people are adrift without government help," Wendi revealed.\par \par \uc2 "Many musicians, crews and event workers have been forced to sell off equipment for food and work as day laborers; [some] defaulted on mortgages and even became homeless."\par \par \uc2 Along with major concert promoters, musicians and event organizers, Wendi has been calling for a return of live concerts in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Through an open letter published on March 3 in anticipation of National Music Day, they have urged the government to provide clarity on the status of live music and pleaded for the involvement of event workers and venues in its current vaccination efforts.\par \par \uc2 Taken at face value, their demands make sense. The music industry, Wendi said, had fallen victim to inconsistent, lopsided regulations.\par \par \uc2 "Why won't they allow concerts to take place with health protocols when they allowed thousands of people to gather without social distancing in last year's regional elections?" he asked. "Why are movie theaters open but indoor concerts banned? What's the difference?"\par \par \uc2 Their message is clear: Live concerts must return, otherwise the music industry will collapse into a black hole with no way of escaping.\par \par \uc2 "For us, live concerts are the only solution that makes business sense," opined Dewi Gontha, president director of Java Festival Production.\par \par \uc2 "The music industry can only be revived by bringing it back."\par \par \uc2 These calls, though, have been met with skepticism and concern. Music industry insiders are hardly optimistic, with some pointing out that Indonesia is still barely managing to contain the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 Cholil Mahmud, the frontman of prominent rock band Efek Rumah Kaca, understands the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  concerns but feels that musicians should have the courage to ask bigger questions and hold the government accountable. "The fact is, it's extremely risky to bring back concerts," the 44-year old said.\par \par \uc2 "But the real question is, why are we still in this position, even though we have followed every rule and curtailed concerts? After a year of seeing the government focus on saving the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  instead of lives, why are we still concerned about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  survival? This means something is fundamentally wrong."\par \par \uc2 Bayu Fajri, CEO of event equipment provider company Bayusvara, agrees with this sentiment. "\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  regulations play a part, but the industry is dying mainly because of the pandemic," the 30-year old said.\par \par \uc2 "People live differently now. Even if you magically allow all live concerts, it won't be the same. Right now, it's simply not feasible to return to the way things were."\par \par \uc2 Others are decidedly less diplomatic. "The idea of bringing back concerts right now is borderline offensive to frontline workers," Argia Adhidhanendra, founder of independent concert promoter Noisewhore, said.\par \par \uc2 "Why would you even think of having a potentially superspreader event when, as it is, we're overwhelmed by the pandemic?"\par \par \uc2 Despite agreeing that a return of live concerts would be a welcome boost for music workers like him, Bayu is also aware of the obvious risk.\par \par \uc2 "We can't control how the virus would spread after we reopen live concerts, no matter the protocol," he said. "If live concerts ended up exacerbating the pandemic, we would find ourselves in an even worse position than before."\par \par \uc2 "If you're rash and the disease spreads from this, people are going to stay away from concerts in the future," Argia said. "Should that happen, the market crash will be even worse." Indonesia, he said, would see a deluge of music festivals with barely anyone attending - a disastrous outcome for all parties.\par \par \uc2 Despite the bleak situation, Cholil thinks musicians and organizers can band together to find creative alternatives. "We've seen promoters attempting online and pre-recorded concerts. Though it has its limitations, it also provides opportunity," he said. "It forced us to break a glass ceiling we never thought existed. We had to adapt, and it's important to carry this on."\par \par \uc2 For Argia, the pandemic has shown that independent promoters and mid-scale vendors are more adaptable to the industry's peaks and troughs. Noisewhore, once a byword for edgy independent concerts, announced the launch of The Storefront, a fan-run online music store, late last year.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Bayusvara temporarily dropped their mantle as music equipment moguls and launched Segarsvara, a grocery delivery service. They have also gradually invested in new equipment, and retrained their staff to support live streaming.\par \par \uc2 "Instead of fighting for permits, big promoters should dedicate their time to pivoting online," Argia said.\par \par \uc2 In the past year, independent organizers have organized live shows through virtual reality, live streaming and even a virtual concert through the game Minecraft.\par \par \uc2 "If they can do it, then surely big promoters can do better," the 23-year old said. "Big promoters should stop bitching. They have all the money in the world to pivot."\par \par \uc2 However, Wendi thinks it's not that simple. Live concerts - albeit in a vastly changed form - is still the best way forward. He proposes a pilot project: a concert with tight health protocols and limited indoor seating.\par \par \uc2 "M-Bloc plans to work together with the Pertamina Central Hospital [RSPP] to provide antigen swab tests for the audience," Wendi revealed. "They will be socially distanced and must stay in their seats during the entire performance."\par \par \uc2 On March 9, the government seemed to heed these calls. The tourism and creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister, Sandiaga Uno, announced that after talks with National Police Chief Gen. Listyo Sigit Prabowo, he would permit live concerts in so-called "green zones", albeit with tight health protocols.\par \par \uc2 In typical Indonesian fashion, though, a few days later (on March 13), National Police spokesman Argo Yuwono said the police had yet to formulate a formal \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for implementing these plans.\par \par \uc2 Bayu thinks that, either way, the music industry would have to fundamentally rethink the way it organizes live concerts.\par \par \uc2 "In late 2019, there was an explosion of concerts and festivals. But that was the culmination of years of progress and rising demand within the music industry," he said. "After the pandemic, all this has gone out the window. Everything has changed."\par \par \uc2 Organizers must take slow, painful steps in educating musicians, crews and especially the audience. "How does the crew work within the constraints of a health protocol? How do we ensure these concerts won't increase COVID-19 cases?" Bayu asks.\par \par \uc2 "Concertgoers must tolerate any inconvenient health protocols. This is not a celebration, this is essentially a science experiment."\par \par \uc2 Whether the experiment is even worth the attempt is still up for debate. "The fact that we're even having this conversation is reckless and selfish," Argia criticized. "You're gambling with people's lives.\par \par \uc2 No matter how you spin it, COVID fatigue is still better than COVID deaths."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210315eh3f00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
