\par\par \b \uc2 Feminine leadership urgent for post-pandemic future\b0\par\par\uc2 958 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 March 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Ariza A. Ramadani and Citra Handayani Nasruddin , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 It is more than a year since the COVID-19 pandemic emerged. The virus has since affected our social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, lives and livelihoods profoundly, and caused health and social crises. As leaders worldwide navigated the calamity, some of them, mostly women, responded better than others.\par \par \uc2 Evidently, we need more of the feminine leadership style that emphasizes compassion and resilience amid this adversity and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . A serious attempt must therefore be made to promote gender equality in alignment with recovery efforts to pave the way toward a better world.\par \par \uc2 From the macro level of heads of state and government to the micro level of organization and community leaders and even matriarchs, we have seen women providing strong and effective leadership.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, last year's study by Supriya Garikipati and Uma Kambhampati found that countries led by women were proactive and decisive, and led to lower COVID-19 fatality rates. This finding was consistent with Jack Zenger and \uc2 Joe Folkman\uc2 's research, which suggested that women were not only more effective leaders in general, but also better leaders during crises.\par \par \uc2 The driving force behind the effectiveness of female leaders derives from their behavior, traits and characteristics, which are crucial during a crisis. They showed more compassion for the feelings of others and concern for wellbeing, but were also confident in their plans. They also demonstrated essential skills such as communication, collaboration and flexibility.\par \par \uc2 As Garikipati and Kambhampati indicated in their study, women tended to be risk-averse when it comes to human life, but they are risk takers when it comes to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardships. As for men, some studies argued that when gambling was framed as potential loss, they tended to be more risk-averse than women.\par \par \uc2 Ultimately, women's risk appetite, or acceptable level of risk, may explain why female leaders were likely to accept the potential \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs of early lockdowns to save human lives.\par \par \uc2 These findings may also shine a light on the double burden that women at the micro level have borne during the pandemic, juggling care for their family's health and safety while making ends met.\par \par \uc2 According to the \uc2 International Labor Organization\uc2 , women performed 76.2 percent on average in total hours of unpaid care work in 2018. In addition, they also managed family expenses more tightly, given the volatility of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation that could lead to reduced incomes.\par \par \uc2 Data from the \uc2 United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women\uc2  (\uc2 UN Women\uc2 ) show that Indonesian women, who draw their primary income from family businesses, lost more than 80 percent of their earnings. Meanwhile, those who depended on \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and other government support saw losses of 24 percent.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, they survived by starting small retail businesses selling products like foods, cookies, plants and handicrafts, or by taking any job available to put food on the table. In doing so, they demonstrated effective crisis leadership for their nuclear families.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, compassion and resilience alone are insufficient to save the entire nation from this catastrophe. Rational, structured and management skills, traits primarily associated with male leadership, are also imperative for dealing with the health and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conundrums. However, evidence indicates that gender stereotypes are connected to leadership style.\par \par \uc2 Many female leaders, for instance, also embrace an evidence-based approach in decision-making. Some are widely renowned for their clear, decisive communication without neglecting to express solicitude, such as German Chancellor \uc2 Angela Merkel\uc2 , New Zealand Prime Minister \uc2 Jacinda Ardern\uc2  and our own finance minister, Sri Mulyani Indrawati. This is the manner in which female leaders adopt a more democratic and participatory style, as opposed to the autocratic and directive leadership style that has been mostly adopted by male leaders.\par \par \uc2 These female leaders have shown that balancing skills and behavior has proven effective in making the best of an unideal situation.\par \par \uc2 Effective results are critical in this difficult time. As the crisis continues and intensifies in many places, all leaders should strive to meet this need. Irrespective of gender, anyone can adopt a feminine leadership style to solve difficult problems in any context.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, a challenging future awaits after the pandemic. Problems such as climate change, epidemics, natural resource depletion, talent shortages and technological advancements call for a new style of leadership that is more participatory, resilient and inclusive rather than commanding and controlling.\par \par \uc2 However, accommodating this leadership style is impossible without efforts to drive gender equality. We therefore need to diversify our leadership and provide more opportunities for women to take leadership roles on both the macro and micro levels, whatever they aspire to be.\par \par \uc2 Government intervention can play a major role in gender equality and inclusion. First, structural barriers, such as sticky floors and glass ceilings as well as barriers and bias that hinder women from realizing their potentials must be addressed.\par \par \uc2 Paid parental leave, for example, can be distributed more equally between men and women. Other incentives can also be given to encourage the equal participation of men in care work at home, such as flexible WFH hours for parents during final school examinations.\par \par \uc2 Second, support should be expanded for women to survive and thrive through targeted policies, such as direct cash assistance to complement the Family Hope Program (PKH), the ration card program and the Village Funds.\par \par \uc2 Finally, serious and prompt efforts must be made to encourage girls to pursue higher education, especially in science, technology, engineering and mathematics. Only by prioritizing gender equality can a new leadership style emerge toward building a more resilient world.\par \par \uc2 _______________________\par \par \uc2 The writers are cocreators of EcoMOMics, an education platform for women to share and discuss everyday economics, stemming from their backgrounds in education, economics, communications and \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210317eh3h00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
