\par\par \b \uc2 World Bank\uc2  holds Indonesia's GDP growth forecast for 2021\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 747 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 March 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has maintained its forecast for Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) growth this year as the country lags behind some other Asian economies in both containing COVID-19 and trading manufactured goods.\par \par \uc2 In its March outlook, the Washington-based lender projected Indonesia's GDP would grow 4.4 percent this year, an unchanged figure from its December outlook. The forecast is equal to the average growth expected for the East Asia and the Pacific (EAP) region, excluding China and Vietnam.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia chose not to fight the disease hard by hurting livelihoods," World Bank EAP chief economist \uc2 Aaditya Mattoo\uc2  told The Jakarta Post in a video interview on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "In a way, it had a more accommodative approach to the disease, which made the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  distress in the short run less of a shock than in the Philippines, but the long-term prospects were correspondingly less promising than those in Vietnam."\par \par \uc2 The outlook noted that Indonesia still largely relied on prolonged mobility restrictions, locally called micro-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Mikro), to contain the pandemic, whereas countries such as China and Vietnam relied on the more effective mass testing and tracing strategy.\par \par \uc2 The bank noted that Indonesia had also failed to capture the revival of global trade in manufactured goods, such as electronics, when compared to its neighbors. Instead, the country's recovery is poised to ride on recovering commodity prices such as coal and palm oil.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  adds to a list of multilateral organizations that have forecast that Indonesia will achieve at least a partial \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in 2021, with the country's GDP growing more than 4 percent, reversing the 2.07 percent contraction last year but short of the 5 percent growth it enjoyed in the decade before COVID-19 struck the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In January, the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2 , the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 's twin intergovernmental body, also downgraded its forecast for Indonesia's annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth by 1.3 percentage points to 4.8 percent, a stronger growth figure than the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 's.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 IMF\uc2  warned in a March 2 statement that a delay in the COVID-19 vaccination rollout would lead to a longer pandemic, which posed a downside risk to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, even though the vaccination program and various \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs ensured the forecast remained positive.\par \par \uc2 "[\uc2 IMF\uc2  directors] observed that risks to the outlook were tilted to the downside, mainly due to domestic and global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  associated with the pandemic," read the press release.\par \par \uc2 "They observed that Indonesia had the macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  space to provide additional support if downside risks materialized."\par \par \uc2 Contrary to the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  and the \uc2 IMF\uc2 , the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ), in its March outlook, upgraded the country's annual growth forecast for this year by 0.9 percentage points to 4.9 percent.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2 's Aaditya said the region was seeing positive developments in the form of vaccination campaigns, although the current stock and allocation of vaccines might force countries to adjust their vaccination strategies and complement them with other interventions.\par \par \uc2 "But the slow rollout of the vaccines could reduce growth as much as 1 percentage point," said Aaditya.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government started the COVID-19 vaccination program in mid-January. At least 6 million people, mostly medical workers and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  workers, had received the first jab as of Thursday, according to data from the Health Ministry.\par \par \uc2 The government is imposing PPKM in some cities and regencies on Java and Bali, as well as in South Kalimantan, Central Kalimantan, South Sulawesi, East Nusa Tenggara and West Nusa Tenggara, until April 5.\par \par \uc2 However, COVID-19 testing remains low in Indonesia. The country's COVID-19 positivity rate stood at 20.13 percent as of Friday, official data shows. That is much higher than the 5 percent standard of the \uc2 World Health Organization\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 With the country transitioning to a recovery phase, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  is also suggesting a more targeted \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support strategy so that the country can generate a larger multiplier effect and improve the efficiency of its \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The government raised the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery (PEN) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by 20.6 percent to Rp 699.4 trillion (US$48.51 billion) this year, of which 27 percent is for small business assistance and 25 percent is for health care. The government had spent 10.9 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as of March 17.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210328eh3s0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Rice Import Terror\b0\par\par\uc2 2,061 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 March 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 INDONESIAN Ombudsman Deputy Chairman Bobby Hamzar Rafinus received a phone call on Wednesday, March 24. On the other end, Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s Deputy of Food Coordination and Agribusiness, Musdhalifah Machmud, complained about the press conference held virtually by the Ombudsman only several hours prior.\par \par \uc2 Earlier that same day, the Indonesian Ombudsman announced the results of its study of the plan to import 1 million tons of rice, which has been a controversy over the past month. As explained by Ombudsman member, Yeka Hendra Fatika, the institution sharply criticized the government. The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services monitoring institution believes that there is potential for maladministration in the rice import \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s decision-making mechanism.\par \par \uc2 Bobby did not deny that the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had protested through Musdhalifah. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are good friends,\u8221\'20\'1D Bobby told Tempo on Friday, March 26. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat was conveyed in the press conference was according to the Ombudsman\u8217\'20\'19s duties, functions, and authority.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Bobby had indeed been with the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for some time. Before he took office as Ombudsman deputy chairman in February, Bobby had spent 11 years working at the ministry now led by Airlangga Hartarto. His last post was as a member of the regional development expert staff.\par \par \uc2 According to Yeka, the Ombudsman takes issue with the mechanism for making the decision to import rice during a limited coordinating meeting at the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  some time ago. The decision is believed to not have taken heed of the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) data, rice supplies in the field, and the stability of the price of rice over the last three years. Because of this, the Ombudsman asked the government to postpone its decision to import rice until May 2021.\par \par \uc2 Musdhalifah did not respond to Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s messages regarding the issue. But the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has had an interest in the rice import \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  since the start.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Airlangga Hartarto said the government views food supply as one of the most important issues amid the Covid-19 pandemic. \u8220\'20\'1COne of the most important (duties) is to supply 1 to 1.5 million tons of rice,\u8221\'20\'1D said Airlangga in a working meeting with the trade ministry on March 4.\par \par \uc2 That day, Airlangga did not read out the details of the plan. But everyone watching the live broadcast on the trade ministry\u8217\'20\'19s \uc2 YouTube\uc2  channel would get the message. The government, according to the plan, intended to import 1 million tons of rice to secure a supply of 1 to 1.5 million tons of rice, as mentioned by Airlangga. As many as 500,000 tons will be meant for the government\u8217\'20\'19s rice \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while another 500,000 tons will be imported according to the needs of the state logistics company, Bulog.\par \par \uc2 The import plan without information regarding the date is what triggered the polemic. Confusion grew when Reuters reported on March 9 that the Thailand government had approved a draft agreement to continue selling rice to Indonesia. The news was confirmed by Thai Trade Minister Jurin Laksanawisit, who explained the plan to sign a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) between Thailand and Indonesia for the sale of 1 million tons of rice annually for four years.\par \par \uc2 Bulog Chief Executive Officer (CEO) Budi Waseso said that the assignment given to his institution to import rice was not decided in a limited coordinating meeting. \u8220\'20\'1CThere was no decision to import (rice) during the meeting. It was only the coordinating minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the trade minister\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that in the end gave us the sudden task to import (rice),\u8221\'20\'1D said Budi in a hearing with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 (DPR) Agriculture Commission on Monday, March 15.\par \par \uc2 Three days later, it was Agriculture Minister Syahrul Yasin Limpo\u8217\'20\'19s turn to criticize Minsiter Airlangga\u8217\'20\'19s rice import plan. During a hearing with the Agriculture Commission, Minister Syahrul said rice supply in January to May was estimated to reach 24.9 million tons. As many as 7.38 tons come from last year\u8217\'20\'19s supply. Meanwhile, 17.51 million tons of rice are projected to be produced in the first harvest season this year.\par \par \uc2 With an estimated demand for rice at only 12.33 million tons in January to May, the agriculture ministry predicts that the country will still have a rice surplus of 12.56 million tons until May. \u8220\'20\'1CThe average price of rice at the milling stage and retail are predicted to remain in a stable condition until June 2021,\u8221\'20\'1D said Syahrul on March 18.\par \par \uc2 Amid the plummeting price of unhulled rice suffered by farmers in a number of regions in this year\u8217\'20\'19s first harvest season, the controversy surrounding the plan to import rice has grown into a debate between ministries and institutions.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE plan to import rice has, in fact, been started since mid-last year. At the time, the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) warned governments all over the world to prepare in anticipation of a food crisis during the pandemic. Restricted activities to prevent Covid-19 from spreading was predicted to cause a decline in production among rice exporting countries. There was also concern that trade distribution between countries would not run smoothly.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the wish to import rice was not realized. Besides the predicted decline in demand, the government\u8217\'20\'19s rice reserve in June 2020 was still at around 1.4 million tons. The BPS predicted that unhulled rice production in 2020 would reach 55.16 million tons, or an increase of 1.02 percent compared to the previous year. At the same time, Bulog recorded that the government\u8217\'20\'19s rice reserve in June 2020 was also at around 1.4 million tons, which adequately met the required supply of 1 to 1.5 million tons.\par \par \uc2 In fact, this year\u8217\'20\'19s yield is predicted to increase. The trouble is, according to a government official familiar with the discussions surrounding the rice import plan, concerns grew after Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s warehouse stocks and absorption performance came under the spotlight.\par \par \uc2 Trade Minister Muhammad Lutfi mentioned the same issue during a working meeting with the DPR\u8217\'20\'19s Agriculture Commission on Monday, March 22. He explained that the option to import rice in order to keep Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s reserve at 1 to 1.5 million tons was already decided before he took office as trade minister in December 2020. According to him, there were cabinet meeting minutes asking Bulog to increase this year\u8217\'20\'19s rice supply. \u8220\'20\'1CWhich is why I calculated (the supply),\u8221\'20\'1D said Lutfi.\par \par \uc2 According to his calculations, Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s rice supply is only at around 800,000 tons, with 270,000 to 300,000 tons being a left over from rice imported in 2018, whose quality may have declined. Meaning, without including the imported rice, Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s rice supply is only around 500,000 tons. On the other hand, Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s absorption of unhulled rice is considered to be less than optimal during the current harvest season. As of mid-March, only 85,000 tons had been absorbed out of the expected 400,000 to 500,000 tons.\par \par \uc2 Minister Airlangga Hartarto\u8217\'20\'19s presentation on March 4 also mentioned that the government aims for Bulog to absorb 900,000 tons of unhulled rice during the March-May harvest. In the June-September harvest period, Bulog is targeted to absorb 500,000 tons.\par \par \uc2 It was these conditions that became the trade ministry\u8217\'20\'19s reason to explore the option of supplementing the country\u8217\'20\'19s rice supply from overseas. Lutfi confirmed that there is indeed an MoU with Thailand. \u8220\'20\'1CI signed (the MoU) with Thailand in early March, not at the end of March,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on March 26.\par \par \uc2 A similar MoU was signed in 2012 and was in effect until 2016. During that period, 925,000 tons of rice was imported through cooperation between the two governments.\par \par \uc2 Lutfi ensured that the MoU is simply a basis for the two countries to meet the demand for rice, especially Indonesia. Meaning, an import scheme according to the agreement can be performed should the country\u8217\'20\'19s rice production fail to meet the government\u8217\'20\'19s need for Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s rice reserve supply. \u8220\'20\'1CSo that if something happens we have the goods.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 According to Lutfi, Indonesia did not only explore import options with Thailand, but also with Vietnam and China. To lobby China, Lutfi asked for Coordinating Minister for Maritime Affairs and Investment Luhut Binsar Pandjaitan\u8217\'20\'19s help in communicating with Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi about the opportunity to supply rice to Indonesia. Wang Yi came to Indonesia on January 12 and visited Lake Toba, North Sumatra.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, an MoU with Vietnam is in its final stages, with the Indonesian embassy in Hanoi negotiating with the Vietnamese government. \u8220\'20\'1CNow nearing the final stages, or maybe it\u8217\'20\'19s even completed,\u8221\'20\'1D said Lutfi. He believes that Indonesia must ensure supplies of rice with many exporting countries to allow alternatives should the need to import arise.\par \par \uc2 Lutfi also ensured that the signed MoU does not bind Bulog to importing rice. Bulog is allowed to purchase rice from any producing country as long as the quality standards are met. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are facilitating so that Bulog can buy the best and the cheapest,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CWe\u8217\'20\'19re using the G-to-G (government-to-government) umbrella to ensure transparency.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Former head of Bulog, Sutarto Alimoeso, confirmed that in prior rice import MoUs between governments, some did not require Bulog to conduct import. During his leadership, Bulog was free to negotiate to find the best prices for rice. In regard to price negotiations, Sutarto said such negotiations require persistence. \u8220\'20\'1CI would pursue even a price difference of a quarter of a dollar per ton,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CA quarter of a dollar times one million tons is a great number.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Budi Waseso refused Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s request for an interview and assigned the company\u8217\'20\'19s spokesperson to relay information from Bulog.\par \par \uc2 During a meeting with the Agriculture Commission on March 16, Budi also spoke about the problem of rice supply. According to him, the rice supply in Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s warehouse as of March 14 reached 883,000 tons. There were still 275,000 tons of rice imported in 2018, almost half of which have declined in quality.\par \par \uc2 On Thursday, March 25, Budi again took issue with the remaining supply from the rice imported in 2018, which has been shouldered by Bulog for years without any resolution. The 1.78 million tons of rice was imported to fulfill the government\u8217\'20\'19s assignment to ensure a rice reserve at that time. \u8220\'20\'1CWe proved that the country\u8217\'20\'19s (production) is adequate. Furthermore, the leftover imported rice is what is problematic. This is a fact,\u8221\'20\'1D said Budi during a virtual discussion with RelawanPerjuanganDemokrasi on March 25. He explained that because the rice imported in 2018 has not been able to be fully distributed to this day, Bulog has had to pay a monthly loan interest of Rp282 billion to a state bank.\par \par \uc2 Bulog Corporate Secretary Awaludin Iqbal said that his institution is still absorbing rice from farmers in the regions. As of Tuesday, March 23, Bulog had absorbed 146,000 tons. Meanwhile, Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s current supply of rice reaches 935,000 tons. With a storage capacity of 3.9 million tons, said Awaludin, it would be impossible for Bulog\u8217\'20\'19s warehouse to be too full to absorb harvested rice.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 AFTER one month of controversy, President Joko Widodo finally responded to the polemics surrounding the rice import plan. He stressed that no rice has been imported.\par \par \uc2 The President ensured that the government would not issue a permit to import rice until June. Meanwhile, the MoUs signed with several countries, said Jokowi, are simply precautionary steps in order to anticipate \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the Covid-19 pandemic.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi asked farmers not to worry because Bulog will absorb their harvest. To this end, the President will immediately instruct Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati to help allocate the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  needed by Bulog. \u8220\'20\'1CI ask to immediately stop the debate about rice import. This can cause the price of unhulled rice from farmers to decline or crash,\u8221\'20\'1D said Jokowi at the State Palace on March 26.\par \par \uc2 But the price of unhulled rice has already plummeted since last month.\par \par \uc2 RETNO SULISTYOWATI, FRANCISCA CHRISTY ROSANA\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/03/28/768090/768090_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/03/29/768185/768185_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210329eh3s00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
