\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Rupiah to remain stable amid market volatility\b0\par\par\uc2 988 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 March 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Reny Eka Putri, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The COVID-19 pandemic has affected all sectors of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as the financial markets. High \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the money market has made investors more selective about where they place their funds. Safe haven assets are still preferred, as they can protect investments and are attractive during periods of market volatility.\par \par \uc2 Safe haven assets generally include precious metals (gold, silver), utilities stocks (the most stable stocks on the market), United States Treasury exchange traded funds (ETFs), Treasury bonds, safe haven currencies (US dollar, Japanese yen, Swiss franc) and cash.\par \par \uc2 The market's growing interest in safe haven instruments will pressure emerging market instruments, including the rupiah. Market optimism has increased over the US dollar following rising expectations for US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery even as new risks emerge in Europe, such as the increase in new COVID-19 cases resulting in a return to lockdowns.\par \par \uc2 The US dollar index (USDX) recently increased to 92.9 after briefly hovering at 89 in early January. The upward trend of the USDX indicates that the dollar is appreciating against most major currencies. The US dollar's appreciation, accompanied by restraint in the flow of funds to regional markets, also put pressure on most Asian currencies.\par \par \uc2 Regional currencies such as the Chinese yuan, Thai baht, Malaysian ringgit and Singapore dollar recorded a downward trend through the first quarter of 2021 from the end of 2020. If we look at comparative data on currency volatility in emerging market peers, the rupiah's volatility of 8 percent is still lower than the average volatility of 21.6 percent for the Turkish lira, Brazilian real and South African rand.\par \par \uc2 The rupiah depreciated 2.8 percent to 14,445 against the greenback at the end of the first quarter from the end of 2020. The movement of the rupiah was influenced by a combination of external and internal factors at the beginning of the year, when the currency had strengthened to 13,900 per US dollar.\par \par \uc2 As a safe haven currency, the US dollar has strengthened against major currencies, driven by hopes over the US$1.9 trillion American Rescue Plan \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , made effective on March 17, in encouraging recovery of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A number of US indicators also showed preliminary improvement, such as the purchasing managers' index (PMI) in manufacturing, consumer confidence, retail sales and unemployment figures. The market has responded positively to this development, prompting an increase in \uc2 US Treasury\uc2  yields and higher US inflation expectations toward a stronger US dollar, which put pressure on the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 However, we see that the rupiah will remain relatively stable this year. On the assumption that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to recover, coupled with national synergy in \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies and progress in the smooth-running vaccine rollout, investor confidence will increase and thereby open opportunities for rupiah appreciation.\par \par \uc2 The national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery program is supported by synergy between five \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures on opening safe and productive national and regional sectors, accelerating \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , channeling bank credit from both the demand and supply side, continuing monetary and macroprudential stimuli, and accelerated \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial digitization, particularly related to micro, small and medium enterprise (MSME) development.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the efforts to maintain rupiah stability will certainly be supported by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 policies, such as continuing the rupiah exchange rate stabilization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in line with market fundamentals and mechanisms, continuing to strengthen monetary operation strategies to support its accommodative monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance, continuing to accelerate financial market deepening by strengthening the Jakarta Interbank Spot Dollar Rate (JISDOR). These policies are a reference for the rupiah-US dollar exchange rate to increase the credibility of the domestic foreign exchange market and to strengthen the payment systems \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . BI will strengthen its triple intervention \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to bring its rupiah exchange rate stabilization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in line with its fundamentals.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, rupiah stability will be maintained with the support of foreign capital inflows and relatively good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data, such as the low current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , consecutive monthly trade surplus, controlled inflation and external sector resilience maintained by a good balance of payments and high foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  ($138.8 billion as of February).\par \par \uc2 From a global perspective, several volatility indicators have declined, including Indonesia's 5-year credit default swap (CDS) to 86 from 245 when the COVID-19 pandemic emerged in March 2020. Likewise, the Volatility Index (VIX) of the \uc2 Chicago Board Options Exchange\uc2  (\uc2 CBOE\uc2 ) remains relatively stable at 21.\par \par \uc2 Potential support for rupiah stability will also come from the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2 , which will continue its dovish and extra accommodative \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by maintaining the Fed funds rate at a low level (currently in the 0 percent to 0.25 percent range), at least until 2023.\par \par \uc2 The Fed will also maintain its quantitative easing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  until US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth occurs, marked by a 2 percent inflation rate increase and improvements in the labor sector. Throughout 2020, the Fed made an emergency rate cut of 150 basis points (bps) amid the COVID-19 pandemic. The \uc2 US government\uc2  will also continue its expansionary \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to boost consumption and reduce unemployment.\par \par \uc2 Going forward, we see that the rupiah volatility projection will not be as high as in 2020. This year, the rupiah is expected to move within the range of 13,800 to 14,500 against the US dollar to close the year in the range of 14,200 to 14,300 per US dollar. We project that the USDX will see a downward trend in the second semester of the year in line with capital inflows that support rupiah stability.\par \par \uc2 The government and BI will continue to strengthen \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy to spur \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery from the impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic. The accommodative BI \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures, accompanied by liquidity injections and gradual domestic recovery, are expected to support financial market performance.\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 Senior quantitative analyst at Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210330eh3u0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pi