he case of Peter, deny him for the sake of their own safety.\par \par \uc2 The same state of fear and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has prevailed over us all in the past year as a result of the pandemic. Millions of lives have been lost, more people have been hospitalized and many more have lost jobs or income as the pandemic has dragged the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a halt. Mass vaccination has commenced in some countries, including Indonesia, but the end of the tunnel is not visible yet.\par \par \uc2 As if the devastating pandemic was not enough, Indonesia has to deal with the latent threat of terrorism, which in the last few days has manifested itself in actual attacks. Following the Makassar cathedral suicide bombing on Sunday, a suspected terrorist, a woman apparently armed with a pistol, stormed into the National Police headquarters in South Jakarta on Wednesday. The police shot her dead, before they could identify the motive behind the attack.\par \par \uc2 For Christians the terror attacks will not only disrupt their celebration of faith, which will peak on Easter Sunday, but also serve as a warning their lives remain in danger because of their beliefs. Certainly the state bears the responsibility of protecting every citizen from fear, let alone the threat of terrorism.\par \par \uc2 Jesus repeatedly urged his disciples to dispel their fears but to believe in him instead. We, too, should have nothing to worry about as long as the state protects us.\par \par \uc2 Happy Easter! Never fear!\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210331eh3v00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
