\par\par \b \uc2 IMF\uc2  lowers Indonesia's GDP growth for 2021\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 570 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 April 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  has lowered its 2021 growth projection for Indonesia and is far less optimistic than the government about the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery as the country faces setbacks with its COVID-19 vaccination program.\par \par \uc2 In its April outlook, the \uc2 IMF\uc2  downgraded Indonesia's GDP growth projection by 0.5 percentage points to 4.3 percent for this year. That figure is lower than the government's projection, which assumes GDP growth of between 4.5 and 5.3 percent.\par \par \uc2 Josua Pardede, an economist at publicly listed \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 , said the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's downgraded outlook was in line with the country's slow vaccination rollout compared with other emerging economies, like India and Turkey.\par \par \uc2 "With the slow distribution of vaccines, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities in the majority of sectors cannot return to normal, which depressesemployment rates and keeps people's purchasing power low," Josua told The Jakarta Post via text message on Friday.\par \par \uc2 Around 9.7 million Indonesians had received their first jab and 4.9 million had been fully vaccinated against the virus as of Friday, according to Health Ministry data. But Indonesia is also facing shipment delays and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over millions of \uc2 AstraZeneca\uc2  doses.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 IMF\uc2  is the only multilateral \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  organization so far to downgrade its Indonesia GDP growth outlook for this year.\par \par \uc2 Previously, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  held its GDP growth projection for Indonesia at 4.4 percent for 2021, while the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) raised its projection by 0.9 percentage points to 4.9 percent.\par \par \uc2 These organizations' outlooks not only reflected Indonesia's vaccination progress but also Indonesia's GDP contraction of 2.19 percent year-on-year in the fourth quarter of 2020, which was less severe than the previous quarters, according to Statistics Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's April projection, like any other projection, was subject to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and involved many assumptions, including a third wave of the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 "But we can only control the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  side, thus we will keep making adjustments," Sri Mulyani said in a virtual event on Friday, adding the vaccination program was expected to be a game changer.\par \par \uc2 "We also need to safeguard businesses to keep them afloat or start recovering, and we also need to keep making structural reforms."\par \par \uc2 In a bid to recover the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government raised the COVID-19 \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 699.4 trillion (US$47.9 billion) for this year, which is 20.6 percent higher than last year.\par \par \uc2 Faisal Rachman, an economist at state-owned \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , said the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's downward revision mainly reflected Indonesia's high COVID-19 case number in the first quarter of the year.\par \par \uc2 But the renewed mobility restrictions, officially called \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM), have reduced the number of daily new cases. The PPKM added pressure on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  but was expected to build a solid foundation for growth starting in the second half, he said.\par \par \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  is marginally more optimistic than the \uc2 IMF\uc2 , as it expects Indonesia's GDP to grow 4.43 percent this year.\par \par \uc2 "The growth figure is still below the pre-pandemic level, which averaged around 5 percent," Faisal said in a note released on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 "Downside risk may arise if the front-loading \b \highlight22\uc2 economic stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , COVID-19 crisis management and vaccine rollout do not go as planned."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210411eh4b00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Back to Live\b0\par\par\uc2 1,649 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 April 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 ANAS Syahrul Alimi has three months left. The Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of Syakira Ghyna Rajawali Indonesia Communication is preparing for the Prambanan Jazz Festival, a jazz festival set to happen on July 2-4.\par \par \uc2 This time around, the preparation is unlike anything Rajawali Indonesia had done before. The July event is set to become a comeback stage for the Prambanan Jazz Festival, its return to Candi Prambanan in Yogyakarta\u8217\'20\'19s Sleman Regency. In November last year, the festival\u8212\'20\'14a regular since 2015\u8212\'20\'14had to be live-streamed because of Covid-19.\par \par \uc2 With the pandemic still ongoing, Anas and his team are now making extra plans. To bring the show back with live audience, there are health protocols to apply. \u8220\'20\'1CEverything is being finalized. The concert organizer must get a recommendation from the regional (Covid-19) task force,\u8221\'20\'1D said Anas on Tuesday, April 6.\par \par \uc2 Tempo met Anas that day after he had a meeting with his team to discuss the stage design and the audience area. The festival in July would only have one stage, unlike in past events when there were two stages built in front of the temple complex\u8217\'20\'19 east side.\par \par \uc2 For the audience area, Rajawali Indonesia plans to copy the concept used during the first pandemic-era concert in Newcastle, England, in August 2020. Spectators would be separated in boxes. Each box can fit four seats, one meter apart from one another. Anas is also preparing the mechanism to screen visitors, including the process of ensuring they wear masks and show proof that they tested negative for Covid-19.\par \par \uc2 Ardhito Pramono\u8217\'20\'19s performance on the second day of the Jakarta International BNI Java Jazz Festival 2020 music concert at the Jakarta International Expo, in February 2020. Tempo/Nurdiansah\par \par \uc2 All these preparations began after the government said they would allow event and concert organizers to hold live shows. The green light was first turned on by Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister Sandiaga Salahuddin Uno in mid-March.\par \par \uc2 According to Sandiaga, the government needs to save many sectors of the creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CTo reactivate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities that have had to delay production during the pandemic,\u8221\'20\'1D said Sandiaga in a written reply to Tempo on Friday, April 9. He said that the government takes into account the vaccinations and declining rate of Covid-19 transmission. \u8220\'20\'1CBut we must maintain our discipline in following health protocols.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 His ministry hopes that tourism will resurrect from the comma condition brought by a pandemic onslaught. Holding live shows, he said, is one of the strategies to revive tourism whilst at the same time supporting the creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  business.\par \par \uc2 The last live international concert held in Indonesia was the Java Jazz Festival at the Jakarta International Expo on February 28 to March 1, 2020. Just three days after the event, President Joko Widodo announced the first case of Covid-19 in Indonesia. Since then, numerous performances were postponed, even canceled. Some event organizers turned to virtual platforms to show their programs online. This was what Anas did for the 2020 Prambanan Jazz Online last July. The offline show scheduled to take place in October-November 2020 was also held online.\par \par \uc2 Rajawali Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s business had turned upside down. Anas said that his company lost nearly Rp80 billion of potential revenue during the pandemic. Instead of being compensating for the production cost, these \u8216\'20\'18virtual\u8217\'20\'19 concerts actually forced them to spend more. \u8220\'20\'1CWe spent Rp200 million more,\u8221\'20\'1D said Anas.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 STRUGGLING to deal with a business running on life support, seven concert organizing companies resorted to forming the Indonesian Music Promoters Association (APMI) on October 28, 2020. They are Rajawali Indonesia, Java Festival Production, Berlian Entertainment, Nada Promotama, Synchronize Festival, Hype Music Asia, and Ravel Entertainment (Hammersonic).\par \par \uc2 The pandemic really brought them together, people who previously had difficulty establishing formal communication. Moreover, holding \u8216\'20\'18virtual events\u8217\'20\'19 apparently is not enough to keep the industry afloat, including in terms of providing jobs. \u8220\'20\'1CMany parties are affected. That\u8217\'20\'19s why we had to move early this year. Events must be held again, adopting new ways,\u8221\'20\'1D said APMI Chairman Dino Hamid, who is also the CEO of Berlian Entertainment, on April 7. \u8220\'20\'1CNo one had thought that the impact would last this long. Before all of this, everyone had done things their own ways, independently.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Through APMI, music show veterans joined 14 other creative industry associations and sent an open letter to President Joko Widodo on March 3. They asked his permission to hold shows offline, actual live performances. Three days later, film industry players comprising producers, directors, actors, cinema owners, and association managers also sent an open letter to Jokowi via social media.\par \par \uc2 The film industry players are facing a similar problem. Their business collapsed as theaters were forced to close its doors. As with online concerts, online film distribution has not been able to sustain the industry.\par \par \uc2 These issues have sparked discussions among entertainment industry players. APMI has been communicating intensely with the tourism ministry since the beginning of this year, including meeting directly with Minister Sandiaga Uno on January 25. A week later, Sandiaga met with the National Police Chief Gen. Listyo Sigit Prabowo asking his support to bring back live music concerts.\par \par \uc2 From then on, technical discussions began. On March 8, five days after 15 industry associations submitted their open letters to Jokowi, the tourism ministry invited a number of creative association representatives to meet at Jakarta\u8217\'20\'19s Mercure Hotel. Among the people who attended were Gen. Listyo; National Covid-19 Task Force spokesman Wiku Adisasmito; and the Health Ministry\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Health acting Director-General Kartini Rustandi.\par \par \uc2 In the meeting, the government said they would determine the locations of live events based on zone classifications: red, yellow and green. Only locations with a green zone status can hold live performances under strict health protocols. Meanwhile, creative industry players are asked to prepare presentations to ensure that the concerts they plan to hold can meet health protocols.\par \par \uc2 A follow-up technical meeting to discuss the licensing for organizing events\u8212\'20\'14as well as meetings, incentives, conferences and exhibitions (MICE)\u8212\'20\'14was held on March 25. In the last discussion, Dino said, the police stated that they would allow live music concerts. \u8220\'20\'1CThe important thing is to be really disciplined. An event can be held if the Covid task force approves the mechanisms,\u8221\'20\'1D said Dino.\par \par \uc2 Alia Karenina, spokesperson for the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , said that people are now used to strict health protocols of mandatory wear of masks, avoiding crowds, and maintaining physical distance. Therefore, Alia said, the government is considering plans to reopen a number of arts and cultural activities under certain terms and conditions. \u8220\'20\'1CArts and culture activities are allowed to open for a maximum capacity of 25 percent, provided they implement health protocols during the micro community restrictions until April 19,\u8221\'20\'1D said Alia on April 8.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 DEWI Allice Lydia Gontha is also worried. The CEO of Java Festival Production is making preparations to ensure that all requirements are met, in order to hold the Java Jazz Festival this year.\par \par \uc2 She said that coordination with various parties can actually be done in organizing international-scale events. \u8220\'20\'1CThe difference is, nowadays we have to hold discussions with more agencies, all the way to the health ministry and the Covid-19 task force,\u8221\'20\'1D said Dewi on April 6.\par \par \uc2 On Wednesday, April 7, Dewi was scheduled to make a video on the simulation of health protocols implementation for the Java Jazz Festival, which is scheduled at the end of July. The video will be one of the items presented to the tourism ministry, the National Police, and the Covid-19 task force.\par \par \uc2 Like Anas Alimi from Rajawali Indonesia, Dewi was unable to confirm the list of performers for the festival. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat we want first is a license. If we don\u8217\'20\'19t have that, everything is useless. We need written permits saying that it\u8217\'20\'19s a go,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. \u8220\'20\'1CBecause this is crucial, you have to know how many audiences you can bring in, and others.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The green light for organizers to bring back live shows will not answer a number of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  faced by promoters. Implementing health protocols will automatically reduce the number of visitors, thus reducing some revenues.\par \par \uc2 The hope of getting funds from sponsors also remains a question. Anas revealed that a number of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) had stipulated internal provisions not to cooperate in events that bring in crowds. This is quite a huge problem, as SOEs had been the biggest financier for live performances\u8212\'20\'14their sponsorships accounting for up to 70 percent of the total revenue.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, various means to ensure safety and health during a pandemic require additional costs. As a result, a number of business strategies need to be merged. The Prambanan Jazz Festival will be a hybrid show, held before a live audience as well as streamed online. The prices for live show tickets would likely soar, from Rp250,000 to Rp500,000 for the cheapest.\par \par \uc2 Major adjustments to reduce production costs will also be made by changing musicians\u8217\'20\'19 accommodation. Airline tickets, for example, will be changed with road travels where possible. Organizers are also making huge bargains with vendors. Anas estimates that the revenue from concerts during the pandemic will be not more than 20 percent compared to that of normal situations.\par \par \uc2 The plan to bring back live concerts is also a breath of fresh air for local governments, including the Yogyakarta administration, which in the past year has been struggling with the collapse of tourism. Yogyakarta\u8217\'20\'19s Tourism Office Chief, Singgih Raharjo, said that music concerts have been a source of regional income. Spectators, who come from around the country and overseas, would spend money for accommodation, food and drinks. \u8220\'20\'1CWe just have to keep going,\u8221\'20\'1D said Singgih.\par \par \uc2 AISHA SHAIDRA, SHINTA MAHARANI (YOGYAKARTA)\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/04/11/769287/769287_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/04/11/769286/769286_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210412eh4b0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Tourism Dilemma\b0\par\par\uc2 583 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 April 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE government has to carefully weigh the impact of reopening tourism businesses against the Covid-19 pandemic. Despite it being important for several badly hit tourism destinations to start the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  moving again, without careful calculation based on solid data, reopening this sector could trigger unwanted spikes in the coronavirus contagion.\par \par \uc2 In mid-March, Minister of Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Sandiaga Uno declared that tourism in Bali would be reopened for foreign travelers in June and July. At the same time, musical shows and sporting events will begin to be held in stages throughout the country. Indeed, several sports events have already been held. For tourism enterprises this is obviously good news.\par \par \uc2 We cannot deny that the loosening of restrictions is important for economies in the regions which depend on tourism for income. Many small and medium enterprises were badly hit when tourist numbers dwindled. After all, the sector contributes 4 percent to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and it also has a multiplier effect which expands that contribution to 9 percent.\par \par \uc2 Yet there is a fundamental flaw in the government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to loosen up restrictions for tourism. First, reopening tourism entities should not include sectors that incite mass crowding. The government\u8217\'20\'19s decision to allow music concerts and other forms of entertainment, for instance, needs reconsideration. The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is clearly contradictory with the government\u8217\'20\'19s decision to prohibit people from going home for Idul Fitri at the end of the fasting month. Two opposing policies at odds with each other could make the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  think there is no coordination among policymakers.\par \par \uc2 The government also has to ensure proper risk mitigation if reopening tourism triggers a spike in Covid-19 contagion. Therefore, the readiness of health facilities should be a priority in all the tourist destinations, though care is also needed to avoid creating paranoia. For instance, we need to quickly upgrade the health care system\u8217\'20\'19s ability to trace people with possible exposure to Covid-19. Without appropriate testing and tracing capacities, policymakers cannot make informed decisions when to put the brakes on and when to step on the gas with regard of the loosening \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In short, the hotel sector and open-air tourist destination spots are the ones that relatively safe for reopening sooner. Obviously, the government has to make sure all the business entities adhere to CHSE protocol, i.e. cleanliness, health, safety and environmental sustainability. Sanction mechanisms for violators also need to be firmly in place.\par \par \uc2 It is important to note that, to date, we do not yet know when the pandemic will end. Though already underway, continuation of the vaccination program still very much depends on availability of the vaccines. Thus in this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, opening up the doors to international travelers can be considered risky. Moreover, the effectivity of airports and harbors in handling coronavirus inspection is as yet untested.\par \par \uc2 In the current situation, targeting domestic tourist travel is more realistic. If Bali, say, can capture 75 percent of the local tourists who like to travel abroad, that would be more than sufficient to reinvigorate their \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In 2019, the number reached 11.69 million people with shopping \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  totaling US$11.32 billion, or around Rp165 trillion. This alone is equivalent to 91 percent of Bali\u8217\'20\'19s income from international tourists.\par \par \uc2 In the midst of the pandemic, health and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  have to walk in tandem. Failure to manage one or the other would bring certain disaster for many people.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/04/12/769363/769363_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210412eh4c00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
