\par\par \b \uc2 Advertorial: Hope, Harmony and Humanity\b0\par\par\uc2 815 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 April 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Dr. M. Azis Syamsuddin,\par \par \uc2 It has been more than a year that we have struggled with the COVID-19 pandemic. One thing we need to be aware of is that health is a basic need that supports the upholding of human civilization. Therefore, building a strong "resilience system in the health sector", is now of vital importance.\par \par \uc2 In my appearance as a speaker at the Raisina Dialogue 2021 casted from New Delhi, world leaders and scholars, once again, sat together to discuss this challenging issue from various dimensions of geopolitics, geoeconomics and geostrategy. However, the question is: What have we done and what should be done?\par \par \uc2 It is true that, so far, the world has made many efforts and tried various ways to build a "health resilience system". However, the COVID-19 pandemic shows that this is not enough. It is proven that not a single international authority or government in the world has yet been able to demonstrate its readiness to face this disaster. Everyone stuttered, startled and seemed to be groping. There is no single \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that is absolutely effective in reducing the pace of this pandemic. In fact, no one really knows the "depths" of this catastrophe. For that, we cannot find a "fixed" standard reference about the right attitude to take in a situation like this.\par \par \uc2 In this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  time, communication, openness, cooperation and togetherness between nation-states are the keys for the world to get through this crisis. Multilateral cooperation and concrete actions taken together in facing common threats have been the most effective responses during this pandemic. These include preparing mitigation measures, management, crisis communication strategies, as well as cooperation and openness in vaccine development.\par \par \uc2 For this, although world leaders are being prevented from directly attending discussions due to the prohibition of travel, multilateralism has become, and is still, one of the best solutions to face global challenges during the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 A future coming sooner than it should\par \par \uc2 Apart from international cooperation, without realizing it, we are all saved by a "future" that is coming sooner than it should. In fact, sooner than we expected.\par \par \uc2 In the last few decades, developments in the field of science and technology have taken a significant leap. These include advances in the fields of communication and information, artificial intelligence (AI), biotechnology, nanotechnology, aerospace technology and non-fossil alternative energy.\par \par \uc2 All these achievements, however, are not yet optimal and far from perfect. But, we realize, this is the infrastructure of the future that will be our goals ahead. That is why we are slowly improving and starting to adapt.\par \par \uc2 However, the COVID-19 pandemic that is sweeping the world today is making that future come sooner than it should, faster than we expected. In the confusion that prevails, the technological achievements of the future are the answer. When everyone is strictly advised to keep their distance and stay indoors (locked down), global interconnectivity becomes the answer: AI replaces the basic work done by humankind, biotechnology through derivation continues to push through the boundaries to find vaccines and other solutions that are useful to mankind.\par \par \uc2 Massively the world community has shifted direction and entered into the offered future. Therefore, we (the stakeholders) are required to immediately prepare adequate infrastructure to accommodate the multiple effects of such sudden changes.\par \par \uc2 States and regions must work together at various levels to face real change, and jointly fight against the various common threats we challenge together.\par \par \uc2 With this pandemic, we have all witnessed a change in the "face" of global threats faced by each nation, where the main enemy of a nation is actually not another nation, but something outside it, in fact beyond it. Ranging from the issue of climate change, environmental issues, energy crisis, global security and human security issues, and the COVID-19 pandemic that hit almost all nations in the world.\par \par \uc2 Not a single nation is able to stand alone in the 21st century, which means that multilateralism will play a very important role in creating a world order for the upcoming future.\par \par \uc2 Indo-Pacific as a role model\par \par \uc2 The Indo-Pacific region, in this respect, is emerging as one of the most important and highly strategic regions in the world. This region is home to the world's fastest growing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Apart from that, the region is also the most important \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  center, which has attracted the attention of investment. This region has attracted more foreign direct investment (FDI) than other regions in the world. And this fact shows how important the strategic significance of this region is at the global political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  constellation.\par \par \uc2 The current success of the Indo-Pacific region can only continue if its stability is maintained. Apart from peace and cooperation, the fundamental aspect that greatly affects the stability is the health of its population.\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 Vice Speaker, The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Republic of Indonesia\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210418eh4j00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
