\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA'S  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2  TO RETURN TO 5% GROWTH IN 2022: ADB\b0\par\par\uc2 453 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Azis Kurmala\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The \uc2 Asian Development Bank\uc2  (ADB) has projected that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will return to high growth, last seen in the pre-pandemic era, in 2022, with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecast to expand 5 percent next year.\par \par \uc2 The bank also projected a 4.5-percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for Indonesia for this year.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia passed 2020 well thanks to a well coordinated and communicated crisis response and strong leadership in tackling the pandemic," ADB director for Indonesia, \uc2 Winfried Wicklein\uc2 , said in Jakarta on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia would return to its growth trajectory next year, driven by a sustainable trade recovery, a revival in the manufacturing sector, and a large national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 2021, he added.\par \par \uc2 Household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia is expected to increase in 2021 as the vaccination program advances and more \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors resume operations, he elaborated.\par \par \uc2 Investment is expected to increase again with improving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects, while the pace of recovery in financing or credit will still lag behind considering the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in investor sentiment, he said.\par \par \uc2 According to ADBestimates, inflation, which averaged 1.6 percent last year, will rise to 2.4 percent in 2021.\par \par \uc2 This inflation rate will still be within \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 "s target range as inflationary pressures due to currency depreciation and higher food demand will be partially offset by the decline in prices for goods set by the government, it said.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, net exports supported by strong commodity exports will result in a current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 0.8 percent of Indonesia"s gross domestic product (GDP) in 2021, according to the ADB.\par \par \uc2 As investment increases next year and volumes of imported capital goods, such as machinery and equipment, increase, Indonesia"s current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to reach 1.3 percent of the GDP, it said.\par \par \uc2 Wicklein said there are several risks to this estimate, including disruptions to the global recovery due to the threat from coronavirus mutations, uneven vaccination rates in the world, and unexpected global financial tightening.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile at home, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery could slow if there is a spike in COVID-19 cases during the month of Ramadan, or on account of delays in vaccination efforts and weakening government revenues, he added.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, ADB has recommended that Indonesia mobilize domestic resources and ensure environmentally friendly \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, excessive debt can be overcome by \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform to broaden the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  base, improve \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration and compliance, and close \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  loopholes, it suggested.\par \par \uc2 "Also encouraging an environmentally friendly recovery will protect the environment and support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and create jobs," Wicklein said. (IN