\par\par \b \uc2 The return of taper tantrum?\b0\par\par\uc2 993 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 May 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Winarno Zain, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In May 2013, \uc2 Ben Bernanke\uc2 , the then-\uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  (Fed) chairman, testified to the \uc2 US Congress\uc2  about the possibility of slowing down the pace of the Fed's quantitative easing (QE) \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continued to improve.\par \par \uc2 QE, which injected billions of dollars into the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , provided a boost to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and capital markets around the world. But what happened then was extraordinary, because mere talk of tapering QE by the Fed's chairman resulted in disastrous effects on emerging economies.\par \par \uc2 This episode, which was dubbed the "taper tantrum", generated turmoil in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There was a huge capital outflow, with foreign direct investment plunging from US$5.3 billion in the third quarter of 2013 to just $500 million in the fourth quarter of that year.\par \par \uc2 Over the same period, portfolio investment dropped from $7.6 billion to $3.3 billion. Exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  fell from $108 billion to $93 billion. The rupiah depreciated by 20 percent against the US dollar. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth slowed to 5.8 percent in 2013 after reaching a record 6.5 percent in 2011.\par \par \uc2 And now that the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is recovering strongly amid the pandemic, speculation that the Fed will taper off QE has begun to emerge. The market generally believes that the huge $1.9 trillion US \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  and President \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2 's proposed \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on infrastructure would spur rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and overheating.\par \par \uc2 As inflation rises and the labor market tightens, the market doubts that the Fed would maintain its current loose monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and many believe that at a certain point, the Fed would tighten its policies by raising the benchmark rate and unwinding its asset purchases. These kinds of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have triggered market volatility recently.\par \par \uc2 According to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 there was a capital outflow of $1.6 billion in the first two weeks of March, after a surplus of $7.1 billion in the previous two months. The Jakarta Composite Index (JCI) was down 4.1 percent, and the rupiah depreciated by 3.5 percent against the green back.\par \par \uc2 In its April \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting, the Fed reiterated that it was not in a hurry to buckle up. It would wait for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  changes to be warranted.\par \par \uc2 But there have been fears in the market that the expected surge in American \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity could fan inflation and force the Fed to step back from its loose monetary policies.\par \par \uc2 According to Fed chairman \uc2 Jerome Powell\uc2  the expected spike in inflation would be temporary owing to last year's low base of comparison and is not likely to require \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  action. He said that an episode of one-time price increases as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reopened would not be the same as persistently higher year-on-year inflation. And so it is not yet time to start talking about tapering the Fed's vast bond buying programs.\par \par \uc2 But the market has 