\par\par \b \uc2 GDP forecast to recover in Q2 but downside risks loom\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 936 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 May 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is forecast to reenter positive territory starting in the second quarter this year after posting a smaller contraction in the first, bolstered by the vaccination drive and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support, but pandemic risks still loom.\par \par \uc2 The government forecasts the country's gross domestic product (GDP) to rebound to between 6.9 and 7.8 percent year-on-year (yoy) in the April-June period this year, according to Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The base is pretty low in the second quarter of last year," Airlangga said in an online press conference on Wednesday. "It is so low that if the GDP at constant prices stays the same as the first-quarter level, it will jump 5.62 percent."\par \par \uc2 The forecast follows the recovery trend as reflected in the smaller GDP contractions since the July-September period, when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  plunged into its first recession in over two decades as it contracted by a sharp 3.49 percent yoy, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data show.\par \par \uc2 In the January-March period, Indonesia's GDP contracted 0.74 percent yoy, BPS reported on Monday. The decline was less severe than the 2.19 percent annual contraction seen in the October-December period last year and fell within the government's forecast range of a contraction of between 1 and 0.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 "Taking into account the development of various indicators that have continued to improve up to April and the low base effect from the minus 5.32 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the second quarter of 2020, we expect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the second quarter of 2021 will return to positive territory," BPS head Suhariyanto said in an online briefing on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Suhariyanto added that the return to positive territory hinged on the COVID-19 vaccination campaign and implementation of health protocols to boost confidence among people and businesses.\par \par \uc2 The government had fully vaccinated 8.15 million citizens as of Wednesday with plans to vaccinate 181.5 million by March 2022 but recent setbacks with \uc2 AstraZeneca\uc2  shipments and the detection of a new, more transmissible variant have put containment plans at risk.\par \par \uc2 The latest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was supported by government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  and net exports that respectively contributed 0.17 and 0.44 percentage points to offset the contraction in consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment.\par \par \uc2 Government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew 2.96 percent from a year earlier, in part driven by the Rp 699.43 trillion (US$48.4 billion) \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  that covered health care, social protection, small business assistance and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives. As of April 16, the government had disbursed Rp 134.07 trillion, or nearly one-fifth, of the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Exports and imports grew 6.74 and 5.27 percent, respectively, from a year earlier. The rebound in trade occurred as Indonesia's trading partners such as China and the United States began recovering from the pandemic, which catapulted demand for Indonesian products.\par \par \uc2 "Although trade performance exceeded expectations and net exports strengthened on the tailwind of China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not out of the woods yet," Sonia Zhu, an associate economist at financial intelligence firm Moody's Analytics, said in an analysis released on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the largest contributor to GDP, was still down 2.23 percent annually with the deepest contractions recorded in transportation, communication, restaurant and hotel-related \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The decline in household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  aligned with a 1.75 percent yoy fall in the average monthly labor wage to Rp 2.86 million in February, according to BPS data.\par \par \uc2 With the prolonged localized mobility restrictions already weighing on household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the upcoming mudik (exodus) travel ban was expected to further dampen consumption during an otherwise peak \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  period, Zhu said.\par \par \uc2 While investor confidence has generally improved, businesses tended to hold back from investing in industries with slow recovery outlooks such as retail and tourism, said Shinta Kamdani, deputy chairwoman of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin).\par \par \uc2 "We think the recovery process in investor confidence has been quite good," Shinta told The Jakarta Post in a text message on Wednesday. "We just need to improve the business climate with better pandemic handling, implementation of the Job Creation Law and liquidity provided by banks to businesses that need it most so their investment rises until the end of the year."\par \par \uc2 Fixed asset investment, the second-largest contributor to GDP, also continued to improve with a yearly contraction of 0.23 percent, much less severe than the 6.15 percent contraction in the fourth quarter of last year.\par \par \uc2 Machines, equipment and vehicle-related investments led the growth in overall investment. The annual contraction in building-related investments aligned with the annual contraction of 0.79 percent in the construction sector.\par \par \uc2 The manufacturing sector, which accounts for nearly one-fifth of GDP, showed a recovery trend by contracting 1.38 percent from a year earlier, less severe than the 3.14 percent annual contraction in the October-December period last year.\par \par \uc2 The highest annual growth was recorded at 8.72 percent in the information and communication sector and the deepest annual contraction at 13.12 percent in the transportation and warehouse sector.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is expected to improve moving forward," Faisal Rachman, an economist at state-owned \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , the second-largest bank by asset value, said in a written briefing published on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 "The downside risk may come from \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the pandemic, particularly regarding the new COVID-19 variant, uneven global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery triggering capital outflow and availability of vaccine supplies."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210505eh5600003\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 A More Realistic Reading\b0\par\par\uc2 669 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 May 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 INDONESIA has to walk through a long and winding road to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. At the end of Q1-2021, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is still negative, at minus 0.74 percent year-on-year. This contraction is deeper compared to the average estimate of economists surveyed by Bloomberg, which predicted negative 0.65 percent. On the positive side, there are signs of improvements. From quarter to quarter, since the Covid-19 pandemic began, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contractions have been less and less severe.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth statistics are obviously very important references. However, we must not forget that those statistics are merely records of what has passed. For the market, it is more important to read the future of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  trend. In this regard, the most valuable reference is a realistic estimate that will hit close to the mark.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government will clearly attempt to maintain the optimism. Officials are convinced that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not only recover, but also take off and flying, so that the graph of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will form a V-shape starting from Q2-2021.\par \par \uc2 The Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Airlangga Hartanto even gave an estimate that can be considered highly ambitious: at the end of Q2 2021, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow between 6.9 percent to 7.8 percent. If this optimistic estimate being realized, then Indonesia will experience its most rapid growth spurt since 2008.\par \par \uc2 There are indeed several factors that can boost growth. One of them is the rise of various commodity prices recently, pulled up by the rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in China and the United States. Higher prices mean higher export earnings for Indonesia. This is an important factor in calculating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 For the last 11 months, Indonesia has recorded a monthly trade surplus. This includes the first three months of 2021, each netting US$1.96 billion, US$1.99 billion and US$1.56 billion respectively. But from these monthly statistics, there is something that needs to be carefully examined. The trade surplus was falling in March. Is this fall in surplus due to the new wave of Covid-19, which broke out on March and slowed the flow of trade?\par \par \uc2 The tsunami of Covid-19 in India has widespread global effects. This Covid-19 fear also creates a difficult situation for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coming into Q2 2021. Learning from India\u8217\'20\'19s experience, which was unable to prevent massive crowd gatherings in religious festivals and political campaigns, the Indonesian government has no other option than to put restrictions to people mobility once again. And the biggest impact of this lies on the prohibition of mudik, annual massive exodus of city dwellers to celebrate Idul Fitri festival back home.\par \par \uc2 The restriction of people mobility surely will slow down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , one dominant component in our gross domestic product, also will go down. Without the restriction, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be enjoying a massive seasonal boost of Ramadan and Idul Fitri. This time, that once-a-year boon that is relied upon as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  booster will be diminished.\par \par \uc2 And there is another signal. Banking statistics have not shown a positive trend as yet. Throughout Q1 2021, banks loans kept seeing contractions. In March 2021, the contraction in banks loans was even worse compared to February 2021, minus 3.8 percent versus minus 2.9 percent. The loan disbursement in banking industry is a good leading indicator of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity. If credit growth is still in the negatives, it is difficult to expect that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity will move more quickly.\par \par \uc2 Weighing the various factors, market analysts have started recalculating. Market sentiments are generally still optimistic that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be on its track to recovery. However, that growth trajectory will not be a kind of skyrocketing one. The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of Covid-19 pandemic can still get in the way. The growth in each quarter might just be slower for the remainder of the year.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/05/09/771839/771839_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210510eh590000k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
