\par\par \b \uc2 Apindo expects employment recovery in 2022\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 674 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 May 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) labor affairs deputy chair Bob Azam expects domestic employment to return to pre-pandemic levels by the second quarter of 2022, led by the reopening of small businesses.\par \par \uc2 He predicted a faster recovery among micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs) than among larger companies, as the recent easing of micro-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM) tended to favor the informal sector.\par \par \uc2 "We can see that the formal sector has not been very active," Bob told The Jakarta Post on May 6.\par \par \uc2 "There was a rise in employment in February because of the harvest season, so the informal sector has actually been more active. Employment will go down in August [as the harvest season ends]."\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's unemployment rate fell to 6.26 percent in February this year from a decade-high 7.07 percent in August of last year, according to a biannual survey by Statistics Indonesia (BPS).\par \par \uc2 Under Bob's projection, Indonesia's unemployment rate in 2022 will approach the 4.94 percent recorded in February 2020, a month before the country confirmed its first cases of COVID-19.\par \par \uc2 Many economists have said that helping MSMEs, which employ 97 percent of the country's workforce, is key to lowering unemployment to pre-pandemic levels, wherein roughly half of the informal labor force worked in agriculture.\par \par \uc2 Ikhsan Ingratubun, chairman of the Indonesian MSME Association (Akumindo), said employment rates among MSMEs had started to pick up since November of last year, when the government imposed micro-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM).\par \par \uc2 "Hopefully by year-end or the third quarter of this year it will start recovering," Ikhsan said.\par \par \uc2 "The success of MSMEs in hiring workers back to normal levels [...] goes in line with the handling of the pandemic. The better the COVID-19 handling, the more successful the hiring."\par \par \uc2 The government allocated Rp 699.43 trillion (US$49.3 billion) in national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery (PEN) funds this year. The largest chunk, some 27 percent, is slated for small business aid. The second- and third-largest portions will go toward health care and social welfare respectively.\par \par \uc2 With the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  picking up in the first three months of the year, the number of pandemic-hit workers declined by 10.02 million from August 2020 to 19.10 million in February, BPS reported on May 5. The remaining pandemic-hit workers account for 9.30 percent of the country's workforce. Most have faced reduced working hours and lower pay.\par \par \uc2 While most micro enterprises have not changed their employment terms, small and medium enterprises (SMEs) have tended to lower wages and religious holiday bonuses (THR), according to a survey of 1,180 MSMEs conducted from July to August of last year by the University of Indonesia's Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Research (LPEM).\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP), which relies mostly on household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , contracted 0.74 percent year-on-year (yoy) in the January to March period, showing a further sign of recovery as the contraction was less severe than in the previous three quarters, BPS reported on May 5.\par \par \uc2 While some sectors, such as information and communication, grew, the transportation and warehousing sector posted the steepest decline with a 13.12 percent contraction from a year earlier, followed by accommodation and food and beverage services.\par \par \uc2 The manufacturing sector, which accounts for nearly one fifth of GDP, was down by 1.38 percent from a year earlier. The share of workers in the sector correspondingly shrank by 0.44 percentage points to 13.6 percent in February.\par \par \uc2 "We cannot yet expect the unemployment rate to return to the February 2020 level, since \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth remains negative," SMERU Research Institute researcher Adi Rahman told the Post on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 He added that businesses, especially SMEs, were still holding back on hiring new workers because of the pandemic-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There was also a risk of declining wages, job security and labor protections, because many businesses were still in survival mode.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210510eh5b0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Trust Matters\b0\par\par\uc2 1,297 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 May 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 In recent months, the world has faced an exceptional challenge, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and complexity. A pandemic swept the globe and affected almost every area of our lives. Our personal freedom to travel, work, and play as we did before was radically altered. The way in which the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  operates was also profoundly affected. Remote working became the norm almost overnight. Indeed, all forms of digitalization accelerated sharply. The significance of this digitalization of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot be understated.\par \par \uc2 The new norm has placed added value and emphasis on building and maintaining trust, which provides the basis of collaborative action and innovation. Indeed, the trust that links us all now matters more than ever. The interplay between societal norms and technology will, I think, be one of the key drivers of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth over the next decade. This interface is embodied in two ways.\par \par \uc2 The first way of embodying this interface between society and technology reflects how we choose to regulate digital technologies and their uses. Digital technologies have an absolutely incredible potential to drive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth around the world for decades. Still, unregulated use of these technologies would not be conducive to long-term prosperity and freedom.\par \par \uc2 Accordingly, governments and regulators worldwide are working together to build principles-guided \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  frameworks that allow and encourage appropriate developments and uses of technological innovations. As our economies become ever more digital, they generate vast lakes of data that must be transmitted, stored, processed, and retrieved. The regulations that allow this technology to be implemented efficiently and effectively are essential but should be made objectively and evolve rapidly.\par \par \uc2 There is much continuing discussion of the right approach to adopt. And yet, given the issues at stake, regulators and governments need to move quickly to avoid being left behind by innovation.\par \par \uc2 In this regard, Germany\u8217\'20\'19s recent IT Security Act 2.0 presents an excellent step forward. It provides a clear legal framework and a sound basis for further improving the IT security of the critical infrastructure. For 5G development, this means that there will be higher and more uniform security standards for all providers. This clarity is a crucial component of the trust that we need to foster.\par \par \uc2 The second way we can see this interface between society and technology is in the standards that we adopt. The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is interconnected to the extent that would have seemed unimaginable a generation ago. A generation from now, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will doubtless be even more enmeshed and even more digital. The success of this new global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be built on common standards.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, not only is the establishment of standards conducive to the formation and development of markets, but it is also a key factor in consumer protection. Without competitors, a company like \uc2 Huawei\uc2  might be better off. But if all products were to use \uc2 Huawei\uc2 's proprietary technology, it would be an absolute disaster for consumers.\par \par \uc2 Standards force manufacturers to compete with each other on technological terms. From the earliest days of technology, growth has been driven by the almost universal adoption of technological standards. The 2G standard brought us voice and text services, the 3G standard gave the world the mobile internet, and 4G has given us data-rich services and streaming content on mobile devices. 5G is adding yet further possibilities to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but competition has remained high.\par \par \uc2 Standards and regulations are two highly visible embodiments of the interaction between society and technology, and they share two fundamentally important characteristics. The first is that they build trust. The second is that the more widely they are adopted, the more effective they are.\par \par \uc2 The digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to change how we interact and trade with each other. When international trade was developing, it required our ancestors to acquire new technical skills and form new ways of trusting their partners. So does the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for today. It will affect how people interact with each other and build trust with commercial interests.\par \par \uc2 Common regulations across the globe are an essential part of building this trust. As our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  becomes increasingly digital and data-driven, the regulations on technology governance and data uses will be critically and strategically important to global trade. Building trust is essential, and the best way to build trust between people is on common ground.\par \par \uc2 When we say \u8220\'20\'1Ctrust matters,\u8221\'20\'1D we are not just referring to trust in our commercial partners: users also have to trust the technology that they use. The knowledge that technology is properly regulated is an important first step towards trusting that technology. However, only common rules that are widely shared can build the widespread trust that technology needs to be adopted.\par \par \uc2 Global technical standards are also critically important to building trust because they allow services and products to be deployed to a broader market more easily. As a result, people could rely on technological innovations operating across borders without hindrance. A certain proportion of the success of the \uc2 European Union\uc2  has been built on the operation of its internal market.\par \par \uc2 But the success of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development in a digital age depends on widespread adoption of both regulations and standards. If a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is adopted and implemented unilaterally, then some companies may simply avoid trading with or in the country concerned. As all parts of our global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  become increasingly closely interlinked, our efforts to find the best path to regulatory success must become increasingly global.\par \par \uc2 In particular, our increasingly digital and mobile \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  demands a focus on security-related trust and dialogue. We must ensure that digital and cyber sovereignty are mutually respected, that user privacy and security are respected, and that data is allowed to flow across borders in a secure and orderly manner.\par \par \uc2 Technical innovation, increased digitalization, and increased product complexity are all driving increased collaboration between \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  partners. In turn, this will drive further increases in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  importance of the secure transmission of data. These data flows are the supply chains of the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the future, and we must make conscious efforts to protect them.\par \par \uc2 Just as global supply chains have lifted millions out of poverty, data-driven value chains in the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will make a vast contribution to global prosperity. At a time when trust\par \par \uc2 matters more than ever before, \uc2 Huawei\uc2  is proud of its contribution to a prosperous digital future.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, the company is a particularly active contributor to the creation and adoption of the global digital and regulatory standards that are so crucial to building this trust. These regulations and data standards will not only ensure that the post-pandemic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to recover in a way that allows the global society to build a resilient and prosperous \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but they will also allow the benefits of this prosperity to be distributed as widely as possible.\par \par \uc2 When the pandemic arrived, closing international borders and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  venues of all kinds may have brought a terrible temptation to adopt narrow nationalist attitudes. Still, we seem\par \par \uc2 to have resisted this temptation very well. As our society now begins to reopen and move into the post-pandemic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , we are all keenly aware of just how much trust\par \par \uc2 matters.\par \par \uc2 The global focus now needs to be on driving widespread adoption of truly common technical standards and regulatory and legal frameworks that reflect nations\u8217\'20\'19 specific values and norms. The adoption is essential to unlocking the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth that will meet the needs of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the upcoming years. These common principles will form the bedrock of trust on which we will build our joint efforts to innovate and grow. This trust will be the foundation of our common success. Trust matters.\par \par \uc2 Chen Lifang\uc2  is the corporate senior vice-president and director of the board at Chinese technology giant \uc2 Huawei\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020210518eh5i00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
