\par\par \uc2 FEATURES\par \b \uc2 NEW INVESTMENT MINISTRY EXPECTED TO DRIVE  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  TRANSFORMATION\b0\par\par\uc2 1,176 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The Joko Widodo administration"s decision to upgrade the \uc2 Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) \uc2 into the Ministry of Investment has been welcomed by the business community as it is expected to create positive sentiment among domestic as well as foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 The new ministry, announced by President Widodo on April 28, 2021, has been created to improve the ease of doing business in Indonesia as it struggles to recover from the COVID-19 pandemic. BKPM chief Bahlil Lahadalia has been appointed as the Investment Minister.\par \par \uc2 Indonesiahas been working to realize \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of around five percent this year through direct investment, among other things.\par \par \uc2 The newly formed Investment Ministry is expected to attract investment into the country and create jobs, which are key to driving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2021, according to Widodo.\par \par \uc2 "The key to growth, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, is investment. Because it is impossible for us to drastically increase our state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This means that the key is in investment and creating as many job opportunities as possible,\u8221\'20\'1D the President said recently.\par \par \uc2 He then asked that trade policies be formulated to invite investment inflows. Such policies must also help recover \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors that contracted last year due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, he added.\par \par \uc2 Investment Minister Bahlil Lahadalia has formulated a strategy to increase the investment target up to Rp900 trillion for 2021 and Rp5 thousand trillion in 2024.\par \par \uc2 The new minister has a five-point plan to increase added value with downstream orientation to drive Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation.\par \par \uc2 "The first one is investment in the health sector. We know that almost all of our medical devices and medicinal raw materials are imported," he said.\par \par \uc2 The other sectors that will become investment priorities are the automotive sector, followed by the mining, infrastructure, and new and renewable energy sectors, he added.\par \par \uc2 The minister assured the government is continuing efforts to expedite licensing to offer better services to domestic and foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 "BKPM"s commitment is that we will not slow down licensing since it is akin to holding back jobs and potential state revenue, as 76 percent of the country"s revenue comes from state \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he explained.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, slowing down issuing of business licenses is also the same as holding back the rate of national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and holding back the growth of Ease of Doing Business (EoDB), he remarked.\par \par \uc2 President Widodo is seeking to boost Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s EoDB ranking to 40th in 2024 from 73rd currently.\par \par \uc2 "This is tough work for us. Hence, let us build together the optimism that is essential in this era of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The BKPM is always ready to run and serve the community in order to encourage investment," Lahadalia remarked.\par \par \uc2 Yusuf Rendy, an economist at the Indonesian Center for Reform on Economics (CORE), lauded the establishment of the new ministry, saying he believes the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19 approval for the ministry will lend positive sentiment to investors.\par \par \uc2 "This adds to the government"s efforts to improve the investment climate by upgrading (BKPM) from agency to ministry. It will surely be perceived as a positive sentiment for investors," he said.\par \par \uc2 The sentiment, however, will also depend on the extent to which the Ministry of Investment conducts key tasks and functions, he pointed out.\par \par \uc2 "The Ministry of Investment can encourage investment, especially in the manufacturing sector. This is an effort to encourage higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth," he stated.\par \par \uc2 Data from the \uc2 Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) \uc2 shows that industrial investment clocked a double-digit growth of Rp272.9 trillion in January-December, 2020 and accounted for 33 percent of the total national investment of Rp826.3 trillion.\par \par \uc2 This year, the government is targeting investment realization in the manufacturing industry sector to increase by Rp323.56 trillion. This optimism is supported by the implementation of the Job Creation Law, post-vaccination global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, and the establishment of the Ministry of Investment\par \par \uc2 In the first quarter of 2021, investment realization reached Rp219.7 trillion, a 4.3-percent rise from Rp210.7 trillion clocked during the corresponding period of last year. It also reflected an increase of 2.3 percent compared to Rp214.7 trillion posted during the previous quarter.\par \par \uc2 "Our investment realization amounted to Rp219.7 trillion," Lahadalia revealed in April this year.\par \par \uc2 The investment value constitutes 24.4 percent of the investment realization target of Rp900 trillion set by President Widodo.\par \par \uc2 A total of 311,793 people got employment during that period, an increase from 303,085 people during the corresponding period of the previous year.\par \par \uc2 "The initial investment target of \uc2 Bappenas\uc2  (National Development Planning Agency) was Rp856 trillion. However, the President ordered us to increase the target to Rp900 trillion. This is not an easy job during the pandemic era, but as an assistant to the President, we must always find a way," Lahadalia stated.\par \par \uc2 The investment realization in the first quarter of 2021 comprised domestic investment (PMDN) of Rp108 trillion and foreign direct investment (FDI) of Rp111.7 trillion.\par \par \uc2 In comparison with the January-March, 2020 period, FDI grew considerably by 14 percent from Rp98 trillion. Meanwhile, PMDN declined by 4.2 percent from R112.7 trillion.\par \par \uc2 "Our FDI was 50.8 percent, while PMDN touched 49.2 percent, which is slightly different. This shows that the world"s confidence in Indonesia and our FDI activities has started to normalize. We can adapt to the developments in the COVID-19 pandemic," Lahadalia stated.\par \par \uc2 Based on project locations, investment realization in the first quarter of 2021 was spread across West Java, Jakarta, East Java, Banten, and Central Java.\par \par \uc2 The investment projects were mainly in the fields of property, industrial estates, and offices; basic metal industry, metal goods, and non-machines and equipment; transportation, warehouse, and telecommunications; food industry; as well as electricity, water, and gas.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the top five investing countries were Singapore, China, South Korea, Hong Kong, and Switzerland.\par \par \uc2 Between 2015 and March, 2021, FDI in the agriculture sector was dominated by investments in oil palm plantations. FDI realization in agriculture during the period reached US$9.5 billion, accounting for around 5.2 percent of the country"s total FDI (in Indonesian value). Meanwhile, domestic investment (PMDN) reached Rp173.9 trillion, accounting for 9.1 percent of the total PMDN in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Foreign investment in food crops, plantations, and livestock came from Singapore (53.7 percent) and Malaysia (15.8 percent) and mostly flowed into Kalimantan and Sumatra Islands, Jumina Sinaga, head of the sub-directorate for agribusiness at the ministry, disclosed during a webinar on \u8216\'20\'18How foreign investment can advance Indonesian agriculture\u8217\'20\'19.\par \par \uc2 During the webinar, associate researcher at the Center for Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Studies (CIPS), Donny Pasaribu, highlighted the importance of foreign investment in agriculture for increasing productivity to ensure food price affordability and better food quality.\par \par \uc2 Foreign investment is expected to bring advanced agricultural technology to Indonesia, help promote Indonesian agricultural products in international markets, and improve national agricultural productivity.\par \par \uc2 (T.H-FDH/A/R013/R013) 26-05-2021 23:51:16\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020210526eh5q000m9\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
