\par\par \b \uc2 GDP growth forecast to exceed 6% in Q2\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 654 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Top government officials expect Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) to grow between 6.5 and 8.3 percent year-on-year (yoy) in the second quarter this year, which would mark the first quarter of annual GDP growth since the COVID-19 pandemic struck.\par \par \uc2 The finance minister, the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 governor and the coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister announced their respective growth forecasts over the course of May. Their forecasts vary, but all are above 6 percent, a figure unseen since 2013, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data shows.\par \par \uc2 The officials expect the recovery to occur on the back of rising consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment more than a year into the COVID-19 pandemic. BPS is slated to deliver the official GDP report for the second quarter in early August.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2 , providing the most optimistic forecast, said the country's GDP was expected to grow between 7.1 and 8.3 percent yoy in the second quarter. The range reflected the pandemic-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that still plagued the country.\par \par \uc2 "It is the contribution from consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  that will still grow, especially with the fasting and Idul Fitri momentum, even though there was no mudik [exodus]," Sri Mulyani said at an online press conference on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 "We also expect investment to rebound in line with various indicators, from electricity to cement, steel and commercial vehicle [sales]. Our exports also surged very high in April, and we expect that momentum to continue until June."\par \par \uc2 The unusually high growth forecast for the April-to-June period this year is largely a result of the base effect, after the steep decline in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity early in the pandemic saw the country's GDP contract 5.32 percent yoy in the second quarter, according to BPS data. The country has never posted growth as high as 7 percent yoy in more than a decade.\par \par \uc2 Providing the least optimistic forecast, BI expects a 6.5 percent annual increase in the GDP in the April-June period, although the recent trend pointed toward potential growth above 7 percent, said BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "What is the source? First, the rising exports, second, the nonbuilding investment, and, of course, support from \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as increased financing and improved government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Perry said in a virtual briefing on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 To support the country's recovery, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has lowered the benchmark interest rate by 150 basis points (bps) to a record-low 3.5 percent. The government supports the recovery through a Rp 699.4 trillion (US$48.95 billion) \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  package this year. As of May 21, it has disbursed 26.3 percent of those funds.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2 , who gave a middle-ground forecast, said on May 5 that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow between 6.9 and 7.8 percent yoy in the second quarter.\par \par \uc2 David Sumual, the chief economist at publicly listed \uc2 Bank Central Asia (BCA)\uc2 , said he forecast GDP growth of around 7 percent yoy in the second quarter, but not higher than 8 percent.\par \par \uc2 "Although consumption is picking up, it has not returned to the normal level, and mobility has not returned to its initial position," David told The Jakarta Post in a phone interview on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "Mobility has a positive correlation with transactions and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Second, I also see that government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  tends to be stronger in the second [half]."\par \par \uc2 The number of visitors to retail and recreation places on Sunday was still 2.86 percent below the level seen in the January-February period last year on a seven-day moving average basis, according to the community mobility report published by \uc2 Google\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Visitors to parks, groceries and pharmacies, meanwhile, have also risen to above the normal level, while visitor numbers at \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation stations and workplaces remain below normal levels.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210530eh5u0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Two Sides of the Planned Revision\b0\par\par\uc2 1,584 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 NOT all the contents of the General Provisions of \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Procedures (KUP) Bill is seen in positive light by the business community. As business owners impatiently wait for another \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty program due this year, they are becoming concerned over some changes to the provisions on value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PPN) and income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PPh).\par \par \uc2 Increasing the PPN \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2 , said Indonesia Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) Deputy Chair for Trade Affairs Benny Soetrisno, may place burden on end consumers who pay the final price. Benny, who is also the commissioner of Asia Pacific Investama, reminds that household consumption has always been the largest contributor to the gross domestic product (GDP). \u8220\'20\'1CIt means this goes against the government\u8217\'20\'19s plan in the effort to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth,\u8221\'20\'1D said Benny to Tempo on Saturday, May 29.\par \par \uc2 A similar concern is voiced by Indonesian Retail Association Chair Roy Nicholas Mandey. Roy, the Vice President Commissioner of Matahari Department Store, said that \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  hike will increase the selling price of goods and services. He worries that it will weaken the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s purchasing power, further aggravating the performance of the retail industry, which still recorded negative growth in the first quarter. \u8220\'20\'1CThe end of the Covid-19 pandemic remains unknown, and mobility restriction may continue on,\u8221\'20\'1D said Roy on the factors that have already been troubling the association members\par \par \uc2 Prepared by the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR), the KUP Bill does not only regulate the second \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty program that recently sparked debates. It also contains article changes, including erasures and additions, to the Law No. 8/1983 on value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of goods and sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on luxury goods. Law No. 7/2983 on income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also subject to revision.\par \par \uc2 On a number of occasions during the last month, Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati has revealed the planned increase to VAT and income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Minister Sri mentioned VAT increase as one of the means the government will take to boost state revenue next year.\par \par \uc2 In the latest development, Sri Mulyani also announced a particular change to income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  provision concerning high-income individuals with a taxable income of more than Rp5 billion annually. \u8220\'20\'1CThe increase is not too high, from 30 percent to 35 percent. This only applies to those who earn more than Rp5 billion of income per year. There are not too many of them,\u8221\'20\'1D said Sri Mulyani during a work meeting with the DPR Finance Commission on May 24.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, higher \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden awaits in 2022. The government aims to suppress \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year to below 5 percent, between 4.51 to 4.58 percent of GDP. This year, \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to reach 5.7 percent of GDP due to the large amount of state \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , related to the Covid-19 pandemic mitigation and national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery efforts in particular.\par \par \uc2 State \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2022 is projected to be between Rp2,630.6 to 2,776.6 trillion. In order to meet the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  target of less than 5 percent of GDP, state income will need to reach at least Rp1,823.5 to 1,895.4 trillion.\par \par \uc2 Among the income components, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue is expected to contribute between Rp1,499.3 to 1,528 trillion, representing a 5.8 percent increase compared to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  target this year of only Rp1,444.5 trillion.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 REVISION to the Law on Value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of and Sales \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Luxury Goods becomes one of the most crucial issues in the KUP Bill. Value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  is levied on transactions of goods and services by individuals or business entities. The VAT is paid by end users or consumers. Provider of the corresponding goods or services is responsible for collecting, depositing, and reporting the payment by consumers to the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  authority.\par \par \uc2 Changes to the VAT provision is prepared in Article 44E of the draft of the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Bill. Article 7 of the Law on VAT and Luxury Goods mentions an increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2 , from 10 percent to 12 percent. As with the previous law, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  may be changed to as low as 5 percent or as high as 15 percent. The difference lies in another provision stating that the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  change will need to be regulated through government \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  after being submitted to the DPR to be discussed when formulating the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan.\par \par \uc2 The government is not only planning to change tariffs. There is also the new article 7A concerning the imposition of VAT with different \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  than in Article 7. The tariffs range from as low as 5 percent to as high as 25 percent. This different \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  is to be imposed on deliveries of certain taxable goods and services, imports of certain goods, and utilizations of intangible goods and services from outside of the customs area. These certain goods and services will be defined in the government regulations.\par \par \uc2 This is what the government\u8217\'20\'19s plan of changing VAT provision from single-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  to multi-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  means. The finance ministry, particularly its \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  directorate-general, had expressed the intention of implementing the multi-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  VAT scheme several times. Later on, during the meeting with the DPR Finance Commission on May 24, Minister Sri Mulyani reiterated the importance of the new VAT scheme. \u8220\'20\'1CWe see that VAT becomes very important from the perspective of justice, or the number of sectors to which it should not or should be levied on,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani elaborated further on the sense of justice that she meant. Higher VAT may be imposed on transactions of certain goods and services such as luxury goods, and vice versa. \u8220\'20\'1CThe reform in \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is designed to create justice and equality,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, regarding income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Bill changes article 17 of the Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Law. One most apparent change comes in the form of an additional tier of taxable income. Individual taxpayers are currently categorized into only four tiers of taxable income with tariffs between 5 to 30 percent. In the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Bill, the government adds one more tier for individual taxpayers with more than Rp5 billion of annual income. Those in this new category will be subject to a new income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate of 35 percent.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  for domestic corporate taxpayers and permanent establishments is to be lowered from 28 percent to 20 percent, effective in the 2022 \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. In the planned change to article 17 of the Income \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Law, the government also reduces the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut for corporations that trade at least 40 percent of their shares in the stock exchange. The issuer is previously eligible for a 5 percent income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut. In the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Bill, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut is only 3 percent.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 HERMAN Juwono cannot yet imagine how the various \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revisions will be implemented. The Kadin Deputy Chair for \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee said that the industry is still waiting for a definitive calculation scheme in each change of \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2 . However, he also said that the business community cannot just reject the government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CKadin is a partner of the government. We know that the government needs state income,\u8221\'20\'1D said Herman on May 28.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, Herman expressed \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  towards the plan for multi-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  VAT scheme implementation. Different tariffs that depend on the type of goods and services subjected to \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  could potentially add to the complications of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration records. He said that the inconvenience in multi-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  VAT collection and reporting may be partly alleviated through the use of digital technology. \u8220\'20\'1CBut this needs further study and direct testing because it has never been implemented in Indonesia,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Director-General Suryo Utomo did not respond to Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s text messages and phone calls to talk about the various planned revisions in the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Bill. \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Director Hestu Yoga Saksama said that inquiries to the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  directorate-general should be addressed to the Counseling, Services, and \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Relations Director Neilmaldrin Noor. However, Neilmaldrin also did not respond to Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s messages and phone calls.\par \par \uc2 What is clearly apparent is that, throughout this May, the finance ministry has been communicating more intensively with the business community. On May 11, for example, it invited representatives from a number of industry associations under the Indonesian Employer Association (Apindo) to a meeting in the office of the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  directorate-general in Jalan Gatot Subroto, South Jakarta. Exactly a week later, Apindo organized similar communication through an online webinar involving around 100 associations. \u8220\'20\'1CNot specifically talking about the increase, but exchanging ideas. Discussing the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Finance Ministry special staff member Yustinus Prastowo on May 29.\par \par \uc2 Amid the plan to discuss the KUP Bill, a study by the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) mirrors the concerns of Benny Soetrisno and Roy Nicholas Mandey. By Indef\u8217\'20\'19s calculation, an increase to the single-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  VAT from 10 percent to 12.5 percent may cause \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption to contract by 3.32 percent. On the other hand, export and import performance may also decrease, by minus 0.14 percent and minus 7.02 percent respectively. In turn, gross domestic product may shrink by minus 0.11 percent. \u8220\'20\'1CThe impact to \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is adverse,\u8221\'20\'1D said Indef Executive Director Taufik Ahmad on May 29. \u8220\'20\'1CThere will be deflation due to lower demand for goods, and state revenue may decline.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 AISHA SHAIDRA, GHOIDA ROHMAH\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/05/31/773514/773514_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210531eh5u0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Optimism Embraced, Reality Forgotten\b0\par\par\uc2 714 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 AN optimistic outlook has gained traction, saying that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  statistics in Q2 2021 will show a rapid growth. The government even went as far as to predict over seven percent growth. This is certainly a good sign. However, statistics can trick those who do not read them carefully. One should read the bright statistics at the end of Q2 2021 just as the starting point. How the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow in the following quarters should be the real focus.\par \par \uc2 The explanation is simple. The basis of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth predictions for Q2 2021 is the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition at the end of Q2 2020. At that time, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was at its lowest point due to the damage from the Covid-19 pandemic; the country experiencing a contraction of minus 5.2 percent. This low reference point will make the Q2 2021 growth prediction looks incredible, even though the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance is nothing out of the ordinary.\par \par \uc2 Contrary to that prediction, in recent weeks, there are more risks threatening the market and the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The biggest one is the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the end of the pandemic. While in the United States the situation appears to be under control, our nearest neighboring countries must once again lock themselves down due to the spread of the much more dangerous Indian variant.\par \par \uc2 Without a doubt, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is closely linked to the end of the pandemic. Yet it is so hard to predict when the pandemic will end and how far the damage it will cause to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The best strategy should be to prepare ourselves for the worst-case scenario. The investors could possibly take a wrong step if they let themselves besotted by optimism just because of one growth statistic at the end of the quarter.\par \par \uc2 There is still another risk that looms just as large. Massive vaccinations in the US have successfully reduced the number of new cases and restored \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  trust so that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can move. Inflation has sharply risen. One of the main indicators for the Federal Reserve in making monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the core inflation that does not include food and energy prices due to their volatility. This indicator came out on Friday, May 28. As of April, year-on-year core inflation in the US has reached 3.1 percent, the highest since 1990. The US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is heating up.\par \par \uc2 Next up in the chain of consequences, the risk that has loomed large over the emerging economies for so long, including Indonesia, will continue to grow larger. The warming up of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will push The Federal Reserve to begin their tapering, reducing liquidity injections into financial markets which currently amounts to US$120 billion per month. When the liquidity flow to the financial market is reduced, the risk of capital flight from emerging economies will increase. The exchange rate of the rupiah will be under pressure and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will soar soon after.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, it is safe to assume that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still in a very precarious position. The government must continue to provide \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  to prevent the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from slumping.\par \par \uc2 However, there is a limit to what the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  can do. The government cannot possibly increase \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  by taking on more debt. The government is drawing on new debt of up to Rp1,060 trillion this year. This limit cannot be crossed because its cost is already massive enough. The burden of interest on the government this year has surpassed Rp374 trillion, sucking out 21.4 percent of its total revenue.\par \par \uc2 Actually, amidst all the limitations, the government still has room to increase the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as long as it is willing to choose. Expenditures that have a bigger effect on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should become a priority. For instance, labor-intensive simple infrastructure construction projects will surely have a bigger impact to help the struggling populace than building a new national capital with a grand palace. Another example: the defense \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year is Rp137 trillion. If these funds are used to import fighter jets, that will actually reduce growth.\par \par \uc2 All of these more rational choices are still not apparent until now. Embracing optimism, the decision makers seem to be forgetting the reality.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/05/31/773533/773533_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210531eh5u0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Wrong Time to Increase  \highlight22\uc2 Taxes \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 597 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 May 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) should not force through the revision to the General \b \highlight22\uc2 Taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  System Law this year. With the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government must be realistic: this is not the right time to be trying to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues. If this is forced through, rather than recovering, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could collapse.\par \par \uc2 The plan for the fifth revision to Law No. 6/1983 on general provisions of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  procedures was sent to the DPR last week. Included in the 2020 National \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Program, all that remains is for the bill to be discussed by the government and the DPR. In the bill, the government wants to apply multi-\b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and increase personal income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is all to increase revenues.\par \par \uc2 As well as this, although it is not explicitly stated in the bill, the government has also promised a \u8216\'20\'18\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty\u8217\'20\'19 for those who did not participate in the same program five years ago. This plan was put forward by Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Airlangga Hartarto, who seems to be passing on the aspirations from businesspeople who have been keen on expressing this from the outset. There are reports that the finance ministry is not very comfortable with this plan.\par \par \uc2 The lack of unanimity from the government over this program as well as over the procedures for the second \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  amnesty provide more reasons for delaying the deliberations. The bill aimed at improving Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio must not turn into a vehicle for the interests of a small number of tycoons.\par \par \uc2 It must be admitted that our \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio now is low. In 2020, it was only 8.3 percent of the GDP. This is clearly concerning because countries with strong economies in general have high \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratios. However, we should realize that the fall in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio last year was mostly triggered by our worsening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has been negative for the last three quarters\u8212\'20\'14although the trend is now positive. The fall in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues led to dramatic reduction in government income. It is predicted that this year will not see a full recovery.\par \par \uc2 Given this fall in income, the government should save money by allocating funding only to priority sectors. For example, the plan by the ministry of defense to procure primary weapon systems should be postponed. So should the plan to build a new capital in East Kalimantan. President Joko Widodo must be at the forefront of efforts to tighten budgetary discipline. He must not be swayed by the idea of increasing growth through large-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If state funds are used up buying imported goods\u8212\'20\'14such as weapons, submarines and fighter planes\u8212\'20\'14those large \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  would not affect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 In the future, \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms should still be a priority. But beforehand, the government must build a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system trusted by businesspeople and citizens alike. The recent \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  embezzlement cases uncovered by the \uc2 Corruption Eradication Commission (KPK) \uc2 must not be repeated. \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials such as Angin Prayitno Aji, who is now a KPK suspect, must immediately be dismissed.\par \par \uc2 In order to drive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, President Jokowi has another option. The government could pass more business friendly policies by simplifying the permit process and eradicating bribery and other corrupt practices. Rather than insisting on gathering \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government should ensure that money continues to circulate in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This way, we hope that businesspeople will be able to breathe easier and move more quickly to bring about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/05/31/773551/773551_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210531eh5v00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
