\par\par \b \uc2 The new competition challenge for banking\b0\par\par\uc2 940 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Piter Abdullah Redjalam, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Banking competition by nature focuses on competing for the number of customers. Banks must have as many customers as possible so that they can reduce costs and widen the spread, or interest margin, to achieve higher profits, capital and have a greater chance of multiplying their assets.\par \par \uc2 However, in the past decade, we have seen a seismic change in the banking landscape as a result of the rapid development of digital technology and the disruptive force of fintech.\par \par \uc2 Advancements in digital technology over the last 10 years have brought forth several e-commerce start-ups and ride-hailing services that have grown rapidly into unicorns or even decacorns. This has been followed by the development of start-ups in the financial sector known as fintech firms, with services ranging from digital payments, peer-to-peer lending and crowdfunding to financial management. Now, fintech firms have become real competitors for banks.\par \par \uc2 What has recently occurred and attracted the attention of many parties is the merger of Gojek and Tokopedia into GoTo. These two digital giants, in the field of ride-hailing services and e-commerce, helped give birth to the fintech industry. Taking advantage of the vast ecosystem they already have, the penetration of fintech services from GoTo is expected to be very easy and fast.\par \par \uc2 Fintech offers many conveniences and is considered efficient. Supported by information technology that enables algorithmic innovation, fintech companies are able to develop business models that are reachable for a wider range of customers, without requiring too many human resources. They also do not require any extended network of branch offices, which are usually quite costly.\par \par \uc2 With all the conveniences of reaching new customers, it's no surprise that fintech is growing rapidly these days. As of March 2021, the number of fintech peer-to-peer lending operators, or registered fintech lenders with official licenses from the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2 , had reached 147.\par \par \uc2 These companies have total combined assets of around Rp 4.1 trillion (US$290 million) with a combined lending portfolio of 181.7 trillion. Even though this is still small in comparison to conventional banks, their exponential growth is something worth observing, especially because while bank lending tends to decline, fintech lending has started to grow by almost 30 percent year on year. This seismic change in the financial sector has also been confirmed by the OJK.\par \par \uc2 In February 2021, the OJK outlined four structural challenges banks were facing in the digital era, for both the short and long term. Short-term challenges included the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding the resolution of the COVID-19 pandemic, which was causing a slow global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, the presence of an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recession, high volatility in financial markets, and the potential for an end to \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the structural challenges to banking included four aspects, namely structure and competitiveness, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  revolution and digital services, as well as regulatory and supervisory transformation.\par \par \uc2 Amid these challenges, the OJK recommended that banks anticipate the rapid development of the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a shift in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  expectations regarding financial services, the risk of cyberattacks, large investment in information technology infrastructure and competition with financial technology companies.\par \par \uc2 In this new era of competition, the banks that will win will be those that are able to innovate digital services (digital banking).\par \par \uc2 Hence it is not surprising that local banks, such as Mandiri, BNI and BCA, and also foreign banks. such as DBS, \uc2 HSBC\uc2  and Citibank, are tightly competing to develop digital innovations to provide conveniences to their customers.\par \par \uc2 Recently, we were surprised by the announcement of Citibank's exit from the consumer banking business in 13 Asian and European countries, including Indonesia. This news was quite shocking considering that Citibank is known as one of the most prestigious global banks with excellent performance.\par \par \uc2 The decision to withdraw from the consumer banking business is actually not new. Previously ANZ, \uc2 ABN Amro\uc2  had left Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 The banks have made the right strategic decision. They have come to understand that the financial inclusion landscape in the world has changed because of the various disruptions and breakthroughs generated by fintech. In the case of Citibank, this pullout was taken at the right time, when the consumer banking business in various countries, including Indonesia, is dominated by local banks and fintech with formidable reach and resources.\par \par \uc2 This global trend "forced" Citi to take a hard look into its strengths and the competitive edges that it could bring to the market. Citi is known for its global networks and footprint, as well as its cutting-edge digital solutions and innovations. From this honest clinical look, Citi decided to focus on the institutional banking business and high-net-worth individuals that require transnational mobility and support.\par \par \uc2 By nature, financial institutions will compete over the number of customers. However, with more players, the landscape and strategy have significantly shifted. Conventional banks can no longer rely solely on physical presence and the provision of basic banking services.\par \par \uc2 These banks need to be at the forefront of innovations while also honing on their own individual strengths. Therefore, there is no better time than now for banks to have that honest clinical look into their organization to identify how they can continue to grow and thrive in today's disruptive digital landscape.\par \par \uc2 Citi's choice to exit consumer banking is an example of a timely, well-thought-out corporate strategy. Through this strategy, Citi can focus on battles that it can actually win. In fact, through this timely response, Citibank can emerge as a front-runner.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Research director of CORE Indonesia\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210602eh630008o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
