\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Maintaining household  \highlight22\uc2 spending \highlight\uc2  recovery momentum\b0\par\par\uc2 1,045 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Nadia Kusuma Dewi, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is showing gradual improvement after experiencing the deepest contraction in the second quarter of 2020 (2Q20) due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Although \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 1Q21 was still negative, the contraction was smaller (-5.32 percent year-on-year in 2Q20 vs. -0.74 percent yoy in 1Q21).\par \par \uc2 The improvement in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was supported by all components of GDP, including household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth contracted 2.23 percent yoy in 1Q21, better than -3.61 percent, -4.05 percent and -5.52 percent yoy in 4Q20, 3Q20, and 2Q20, respectively.\par \par \uc2 The contribution of household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure is still dominant, at 56.93 percent in 1Q21 and 57.66 percent in the 2020 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. However, with such high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the COVID-19 pandemic, will the recovery in household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  be sustainable and can it become a driver for future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth?\par \par \uc2 The Office of the Bank Mandiri Chief Economist estimates that household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2Q21 may grow 6.57 percent yoy, a significant increase compared to the previous periods. However, this is possible given the lower base effect from last year, when household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  contracted very deeply in 2Q20. In more detail, there are several factors influencing the hike in household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2Q21.\par \par \uc2 First, the seasonal factor of Ramadan and Idul Fitri celebrations in April-May 2021 boosted \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Even though the government imposed a ban on going home, which is suspected to have had a counterproductive impact on household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, the result of Mandiri Institute's research compiled from the Facebook Mobility Index shows that people's mobility in the 2021 Idul Fitri homecoming period was higher than in the 2020 period.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, there has been an increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  outside Jakarta, especially in areas where travelers come from, such as Probolinggo and Cimahi. This means that \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to grow, although not as much as previously expected if the homecoming ban is not enforced.\par \par \uc2 Second, government \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs and \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  macro prudential policies were implemented in order to increase consumption. The government is committed to allocating a total \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 699.43 trillion (US$49.07 billion) to the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery (PEN) program in 2021, which includes the social safety net of Rp 150.88 trillion to support purchasing power and encourage consumption.\par \par \uc2 As of May 25, the social safety net had reached 57.4 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government also provides \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives in the form of discounting sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on luxury goods for cars and reducing value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  for residential properties. Meanwhile, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  relaxed the loan-to-value property credit \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Third, increasing community mobility along with the progress of the vaccination program and relatively controlled COVID-19 cases have also increased \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is important to encourage consumer confidence in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially the upper middle class. We see that the recovery in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  among the upper middle class is the key to national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth going forward. This is because they make the biggest contribution to national \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  (>70 percent).\par \par \uc2 As we know, purchasing power has fallen, causing the level of demand and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to decrease significantly during the pandemic. While on the other hand, the upper middle class, who still have relatively good purchasing power, are reluctant to spend because they do not have confidence in future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. Therefore, we think the government needs to maintain the momentum for consumer confidence to recover going forward so that they will be eager to spend more.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's consumer survey shows the consumer confidence level in April 2021 at 101.5, returning to optimistic levels (>100) for the first time since March 2020. Interestingly, a significant increase in the consumer confidence index was shown by the group of respondents with \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  above Rp 3 million per month as a representation of the upper middle income class. In more detail, the consumer confidence index of respondents with \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  above Rp 5 million per month experienced the highest increase of 28 percent yoy in April 2021.\par \par \uc2 Other data also confirmed the increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the upper middle class. GDP data for household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  by allocation of use recorded a fairly high growth improvement in \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  on clothing and footwear (-2.71 percent yoy in 1Q21 vs. -5.14 percent yoy in 2Q20), durable goods and \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  on restaurants and hotels (-4.16 percent yoy in 1Q21 vs. -16.53 percent yoy in 2Q20) and leisure needs.\par \par \uc2 In line with this, the Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index shows the Department Stores and Restaurants \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index of the higher income class is above the pre-pandemic level. Meanwhile, in terms of retailers, the same-store sales growth of several retailers targeting the upper middle-class, such as \uc2 Ace Hardware\uc2  and Mitra Adi Perkasa, is better than retailers targeting the lower middle-class, for example Ramayana.\par \par \uc2 In our view, some efforts need to be made to encourage increased consumption, especially for the upper middle income bracket.\par \par \uc2 First, more serious and effective handling of the COVID-19 pandemic, including vaccine program acceleration, will determine consumer perception and confidence about current and future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. In this case, firmness, consistency and integrated government policies between sectors and institutions is needed.\par \par \uc2 Second, strategic solutions are needed to support sectors that are closely related to the upper middle income class, for example e-commerce. The upper middle class continues to drive the growth of e-commerce with the biggest penetration and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  per buyer. We appreciate the government's efforts to encourage online retail sales by providing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for free shipping of up to Rp 20,000 for shopping for local products last month. This program can also be synergized with micro, small and medium enterprises so that it has a wider impact on the community.\par \par \uc2 Last but not least, the government should continue to monitor and ensure the progress of the PEN program in order to maintain purchasing power and consumption at large.\par \par \uc2 In sum, we all hope that the pandemic can end soon so that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity can recover and improve the welfare of the whole community.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Senior industry analyst at Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210609eh6900007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
