\par\par \b \uc2 Too important to fail\b0\par\par\uc2 528 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 National flag carrier \uc2 Garuda Indonesia\uc2 , the largest carrier in the world's largest archipelagic country and one of the few publicly traded state-owned enterprises (SOEs), is certainly too important to be allowed to fail as a result of its severe financial bleeding amid the COVID-19-induced travel restrictions.\par \par \uc2 Garuda is more than just an airline. It is a critical development entity, which should be anchored on good governance, operational excellence and the prudent use of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds. Air travel stimulates growth as travelers spend money with tourism service providers, such as hotels, restaurants and land transportation companies, thereby generating business throughout their own diverse supply chains.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, an active and efficient airline industry boosts competition and trade, facilitates business interactions and foreign investment, and encourages new experiences and the exchange of know-how, connecting people, businesses and ideas across the vast archipelago. This process thus brings about productivity gains across the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The problem, however, is that Garuda, like all other airlines across the world, has been forced by the COVID-19 pandemic to operate at only around 25-30 percent of its capacity, thereby suffering severe financial losses. This financial bleeding will not stop until the pandemic is fully controlled and air travel restrictions are widely eased, which most analysts predict will not occur until late 2023.\par \par \uc2 Worse still, Garuda also carries a burden left behind by the previous bad management, which was fired in December 2019 for running a smuggling ring, a debt overhang of almost US$5 billion, questionable plane leasing costs that took up to 27 percent of its revenues and many other forms of inefficiencies.\par \par \uc2 Both the government, as the controlling shareholder, and the management have begun drastic cost-cutting measures, including reducing the size of the Garuda fleet and staff and renegotiating its leasing costs, which analysts say are the highest within the industry. The government should back up Garuda in forcing suppliers to cut procurement costs that are unusually high as a result of malfeasance and should encourage other state or government creditors to reschedule their loans.\par \par \uc2 But the government should tie whatever forms of additional financial aid to Garuda to strict terms and conditions, imposing tough performance indicators for any disbursement of bailout funds. The gradual process by which the government disbursed the Rp 8.5 trillion ($560 million) in convertible bonds it committed to Garuda recently was an effective way of keeping the management on their toes in following the government directives.\par \par \uc2 Latest reports said only Rp 1 trillion of the convertible bonds had been disbursed because Garuda had failed to meet the performance indicators. But the indicators should be open for review due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the COVID-19 infection rate.\par \par \uc2 The main purpose of the bailout is to enable Garuda to serve its function as a critical national development entity and to eventually turn it into a profitable commercial entity. But until the pandemic is brought under control and travel restrictions are eased, Garuda will serve mostly as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure to serve the strategic interests of the state in enhancing the process of domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  integration.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210609eh6900009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\p