 the range of 8 percent.\par \par \uc2 However, in the last few years, Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has missed the target, reaching only 5 percent on average. In line with this, electricity demand growth has fallen below the target at only 4.5-5 percent per year. Even worse, as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2020 reached minus 2.07 percent year-on-year (yoy). The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  states the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still facing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and will take approximately five years to recover. This means that in the next few years, the road of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will be rocky.\par \par \uc2 The mismatch between the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  projection and electricity development has resulted in an oversupply problem for PLN's electricity balance, with nearly 40 percent of electricity production remaining unabsorbed. This is a particularly detrimental situation because the Take or Pay scheme requires PLN to buy all the electricity production, whether it is used or not. Thus, new coal-fired power plants in the future are likely to be a stranded asset for PLN.\par \par \uc2 A new coal-fired power plant will further burden PLN's finances, which are already in a debilitated condition. Until 2021, PLN has the staggering debt of Rp 694 trillion (US$48.71 billion), almost a quarter of the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . PLN stated that the debt was inseparable from the 35,000 MW project, whose main energy source comes from coal.\par \par \uc2 With the estimated range of capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  (capex) per 1 gigawatt (GW) of installed capacity being $2 billion, the continuation of the 6,000 MW coal-fired power plant projects will add approximately Rp 156 trillion to PLN's financial burden.\par \par \uc2 These facts show the importance of linking commitments to achieve zero-emission targets with the right and concrete choices of action. Otherwise, the "business as usual" strategy in energy development, which still depends on coal with a veil of net-zero commitment, will lead to more complicated problems.\par \par \uc2 A serious net-zero commitment means taking a firm stance on an energy transition and halting the use of coal immediately. The choice to keep building coal-fired power plants would thus become irrelevant. Renewable energy sources in Indonesia are so abundant, reaching 417.8 GW--or nearly 7 times the country's current installed capacity. The cost of producing renewable energy according to a recent study by the \uc2 International Energy Agency\uc2  is also much cheaper than coal.\par \par \uc2 The government and PLN must reorient their energy development plans, which have to prioritize a low-carbon and climate-conscious strategy. The utilization of renewable energy must be accelerated to replace the cancellation of new coal-fired power plants and the closure of old coal-fired power plants.\par \par \uc2 If they are unwilling, then the net-zero commitment will just be the latest in high-flown jargon without any valuable impact.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Researcher and program manager at Trend Asia\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210611eh6b0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
