\par\par \b \uc2 EU\uc2 , ASEAN are partners with common agenda\b0\par\par\uc2 956 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Josep Borrell\uc2  , Brussels\par \par \uc2 My visit to Jakarta and ASEAN early this month underlined the \uc2 European Union\uc2 's commitment to the Indo-Pacific region, and it reconfirmed a clear demand in the region for more cooperation and \uc2 EU\uc2  presence. All my interlocutors stressed that they want to shape a broad common agenda for cooperation: from the pandemic and recovery, to connectivity and trade, from the green agenda to the key area of security.\par \par \uc2 As the \uc2 EU\uc2 , we are well aware that the global center of gravity is shifting toward the Indo-Pacific region. The Indo-Pacific creates 60 percent of global gross domestic product and two-thirds of global growth. It is the second largest destination for \uc2 EU\uc2  exports and home to four out of the \uc2 EU\uc2 's top ten trading partners. Around 40 percent of the \uc2 EU\uc2 's foreign trade passes through the South China Sea. The \uc2 EU\uc2  is also the top investor in and development assistance provider for the Indo-Pacific.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 EU\uc2  is the ASEAN's number one development partner, and its third trade partner and investor.EU exports to ASEAN countries grew from 54 billion euros (US$65.39 billion) in 2010 to 85 billion euros in 2019 and our imports grew even more, from 72 billion euros to 125 billion euros. These numbers remind us of our strong connection and the big stakes the \uc2 EU\uc2  has in this dynamic part of the world.\par \par \uc2 The Indo-Pacific region is the future, but the present is just as important. Insecurity and tensions are rising, threatening the order and balance of this region. Stability, development and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rests on openness, on stable and shared rules and shared security, and the \uc2 EU\uc2 's interest is precisely this: that the regional order stays rules-based and free and open for all. We can contribute to this significantly and our regional partners, who view the \uc2 EU\uc2  as a trusted and reliable actor, recognize this.\par \par \uc2 Last year, we upgraded EU-ASEAN relations between the two most advanced regional integration schemes of the world to a Strategic Partnership, after we had established dialogue relations in 1977. This was long overdue and important, because in a world of power politics and general \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 ASEAN and the \uc2 EU\uc2  should pull together. Our bonds with ASEAN are founded on a joint commitment to rules-based multilateralism. Currently, ASEAN is a bit like the "swing state" in the wider Indo-Pacific, where the US and China are throwing their weight around. ASEAN countries are united by their wish not to be cajoled by US-China strategic competition. ASEAN is the nucleus around which inclusive forms of regional cooperation are built, and regional integration is a way to safeguard our respective "strategic autonomy".\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 EU\uc2  launched in April 2021 an Indo-Pacific strategy, with one key message: We want to step up our engagement and work with our partners to boost trade and investment, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  openness and a sustainable approach to connectivity in the region. Besides being an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powerhouse, the \uc2 EU\uc2  is also ready to be a political and security actor in the region and to do more work on strategic and security issues, in particular maritime security.\par \par \uc2 We already have a dialogue with ASEAN on maritime security cooperation, and are currently extending our Critical Maritime Routes Program, which strengthens regional maritime surveillance capacities from the Indian Ocean to South East Asia. We are also exploring options to enhance the \uc2 EU\uc2 's maritime presence in the vast Indo-Pacific space.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, we have to step up cooperation to respond to the ongoing "democratic recession" worldwide and the growing attacks on pluralism and political freedoms. Myanmar is the most dramatic case in point in this regard in Southeast Asia. The \uc2 EU\uc2  looks to ASEAN leadership in this situation and we are ready to back more regional engagement. Given the complete refusal by the military junta to engage in negotiations and their growing repression, the \uc2 EU\uc2  is also working on a new sanctions package to further defend human rights.\par \par \uc2 Many countries and certainly the people in this region share our view: These values and principles are universal and people should determine their own political future and have their rights protected. Often, as we see in Myanmar, the erosion of such rights and freedoms comes with severe consequences for one's personal safety and security.\par \par \uc2 Beyond the regional angle, the \uc2 EU\uc2  and Indonesia are close partners and our ties are strong, with tremendous scope for further growth. The discussion I had with the country's leadership made clear how much room there is for even more cooperation.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 EU\uc2  supports Indonesia's objective of becoming a high-income country by 2045, while realizing the 2030 United Nations sustainable development goals, and our future CEPA/Free Trade Agreement will support that goal by generating more trade, more European foreign direct investment, and jobs. Linked to this, we will continue to build a partnership for green growth - without the \uc2 EU\uc2  erecting a green wall as is feared by some, and indeed security will be increasingly central in our cooperation.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is a force for peace and stability in the region and globally, and its 2022 \uc2 Group of 20\uc2  presidency and the 2023 ASEAN chairmanship will provide further opportunities to work together on strengthening the region and the multilateral system.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 EU\uc2 's message is clear: We want to do more with ASEAN, in Southeast Asia and in the wider region. ASEAN, and the people of the region, can count on the \uc2 EU\uc2  to be a strong and reliable partner as we jointly tackle the challenges of our time.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 EU\uc2  high representative for foreign affairs and security \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 /vice-presidentof the \uc2 European Commission\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210614eh6e0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
