\par\par \b \uc2 Prabowo, Ganjar lead poll, but is it enough?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,021 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Camilia Adianti , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Defense Minister \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  and Central Java Governor Ganjar Pranowo topped the list of potential candidates for the 2024 presidential election, according to a recent opinion survey. It remains to be seen, however, whether the electability rate will ensure their spot in the highly anticipated 2024 presidential race.\par \par \uc2 A nationwide poll conducted from May 21 to 28 by Jakarta-based Saiful Mujani Research and Consulting (SMRC) gave Gerindra Party chairman Prabowo the highest electability rating for the 2024 presidential election at 21.5 percent. Ganjar came second with 12.6 percent, while Jakarta and West Java governors Anies Baswedan and Ridwan Kamil ranked third and fourth respectively with 12 percent and 4.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo was a clear frontrunner when 1,220 respondents were asked who they would vote for if the election were held today. When they were provided with a list of 15 names, Prabowo continued to outrank other candidates with 24.4 percent, while Ganjar, Anies, Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Sandiaga Uno\uc2  and Ridwan trailed behind with 15.7 percent, 14.3 percent, 7.9 percent and 5.3 percent respectively.\par \par \uc2 The lineup was unchanged when the list was shortened to eight and three candidates, with Prabowo leading with 26 percent and 34.1 percent respectively.\par \par \uc2 While at this stage the favor seemed to be on Prabowo's side, the pollster also highlighted the fact that his electability rating had been stagnant for over five years at around 20 percent. The highest surge came in the May 2018 poll, when his electability rating increased by 7.8 percentage points. The rating fell by 4.3 percentage points to 19.5 percent, according to a survey in March 2020.\par \par \uc2 Although trailing Prabowo, Anies, Ganjar and Ridwan have seen their electability rate climb significantly since March 2020.\par \par \uc2 Such a rise can, in a way, be explained by the fact that three of them are regional leaders who have been constantly visible in the media and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  eye amid the COVID-19 pandemic as they flaunt their policies in managing the crisis. Whereas Prabowo, as defense minister, has no direct role in the pandemic response.\par \par \uc2 Regardless, Indonesian Presidential Studies executive director Nyarwi Ahmad said the three governors had the potential to surpass Prabowo's electability once political parties declared them presidential candidates. By then, Prabowo probably would not have enough time to boost his electability.\par \par \uc2 The recent SMRC poll also noted that Ganjar, unlike Anies and Ridwan, had consistently experienced a substantial rise in electability since the last presidential election in 2019, which made him a particular candidate to watch out for.\par \par \uc2 While the electability rates of Prabowo and Ganjar appear somewhat promising, their prospects of running in the 2024 race are a different matter.\par \par \uc2 The recent SMRC poll also noted that Ganjar, unlike Anies and Ridwan, had consistently experienced a substantial rise in electability since the last presidential election in 2019, which made him a particular candidate to watch out for.\par \par \uc2 Just recently, Prabowo, who ran against President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo in the 2014 and 2019 elections, stated that he was "ready to [run again in 2024] should he be given the opportunity to serve [the country]".\par \par \uc2 Several Gerindra executives, such as deputy chairmen Habiburokhman and Sufmi Dasco Ahmad, have also confirmed that there has been no internal schism regarding Prabowo's third quest for the presidency.\par \par \uc2 The party has not ruled out the possibility of forming a coalition with the ruling Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P). In this regard, many have speculated about Prabowo pairing with \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Speaker Puan Maharani in 2024.\par \par \uc2 Considering his lead in the polls, party chairmanship and close ties with the PDI-P, Prabowo currently appears to be the strongest contender for the 2024 race.\par \par \uc2 Despite his sufficient political capital, however, experts insist that Prabowo needs more. Indonesia Political Review executive director Ujang Komarudin, for one, said it would be difficult for Prabowo to reclaim support from conservative Muslim groups that had backed him in the 2014 and 2019 races, particularly after he joined Jokowi's coalition.\par \par \uc2 As for Ganjar, a PDI-P cadre, he recently appeared to be entangled in a quarrel with Puan, daughter of PDI-P chairwoman \uc2 Megawati Soekarnoputri\uc2 , allegedly pertaining to the party's presidential nomination.\par \par \uc2 Despite his popularity, largely due to his position as a regional leader and increased online activity, Ganjar, as well as other candidates, badly needs an endorsement from a political party or a coalition of parties in order to contest the presidential race.\par \par \uc2 The recent SMRC poll also found that Ganjar still had the potential to win the 2024 race "without the backing of the PDI-P". Excluding PDI-P voters, Ganjar's electability ranked first with 35.5 percent, followed by Prabowo at 30.8 percent and Anies at 25.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, if he was not endorsed by the PDI-P, the poll found that Ganjar could still win the race. He is likely to get the most votes from the National Awakening Party (PKB) with 68 percent, followed by the Democratic Party with 40 percent, as well as non-legislature political parties with 46 percent and undecided voters with 31 percent.\par \par \uc2 At the end of the day, however, it looks like the PDI-P will still be the best political vehicle for Ganjar to maintain his \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  presence, especially after his gubernatorial term ends in 2023.\par \par \uc2 The poll, for one, found that the PDI-P would maintain its position as ruling party, securing almost 26 percent of the vote.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) political observer Arya Fernandes said it was still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether Ganjar would want to contest the 2024 race without being endorsed by the PDI-P, considering that other political parties had yet to show serious interest in giving the ticket to Ganjar. Paramadina University political observer Hendri Satrio concurred, noting that Ganjar owed his political career to the PDI-P.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Researcher of Tenggara Strategics, a think tank cofounded by The Jakarta Post. The original article was published in Tenggara Backgrounder.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210618eh6i0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
