\par\par \b \uc2 Now, the debt pandemic\b0\par\par\uc2 546 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 June 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 The COVID-19 pandemic has caused debt distress for many governments worldwide -- Indonesia is no exception.\par \par \uc2 The twin crises of health and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  virtually have crippled the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Tight social-mobility restrictions caused the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to contract by almost 2.2 percent in 2020, slashing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues at a time when the government needs more funds to fight the pandemic and finance social assistance programs for the vulnerable.\par \par \uc2 An unprecedented crisis certainly calls for an unprecedented bold measure. The government last year doubled the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to more than 6 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). The huge additional financing could be fulfilled only by borrowing from the domestic and international financial markets. Consequently, government debts increased last year by almost 30 percent to Rp 6.07 quadrillion (US$433.5 billion).\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Supreme Audit Agency (BPK) \uc2 warned the government last week that it must be extra careful in applying for new loans because measured by the three indicators of debt vulnerability set out by the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2 , the level of government debt has been worrisome, nearing the borderline of unsustainability.\par \par \uc2 The three groups of indicators measure the risk that current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions generate over \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debts, evaluate the government's ability to face upcoming contingencies considering certain expected circumstances and show the liabilities' 