\par\par \b \uc2 Factory imports show recovery  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 570 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's imports may fall back to levels not seen since last summer as manufacturers face renewed risks following the recent surge in COVID-19 cases and deaths, the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) has said.\par \par \uc2 Kadin deputy chairwoman Shinta Kamdani said she was expecting import growth to slow down again in the next one to three months as manufacturers remained under pressure and had no room for speculative imports, such as hoarding raw materials.\par \par \uc2 "Instead, companies limit imports and production [and decide on these] depending on placed orders or [current] demand, so that their overhead costs do not swell up and make cash flow vulnerable at a time when \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about domestic demand remains high," Shinta told The Jakarta Post in a text message on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has recently seen a series of record-breaking daily new confirmed coronavirus cases, surpassing 20,000. The latest wave of the pandemic has also led to daily new confirmed deaths exceeding 400, close to the peak seen in January.\par \par \uc2 While exports rebounded earlier, imports only started to grow annually in February of this year as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity at home picked up. In May, a month after the peak \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  period in Ramadan, imports grew 68.68 percent year-on-year (yoy) to US$14.23 billion, driven largely by raw materials, followed by consumer goods.\par \par \uc2 In April, the annual growth of capital goods imports slowed to 9.71 percent, although the trend remained upward. Not all capital goods imports booked growth.\par \par \uc2 Conversely, raw material imports continued to grow rapidly in April, rising 29.88 percent yoy, with the highest growth seen in fuels and lubricants at more than 100 percent yoy. Industrial supplies remained the largest contributor, accounting for 12.63 percentage points of total raw material import growth.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's imports, of which the overwhelming majority are raw materials, tend to move in line with the manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI). The index, a gauge of factory activity published by business consultancy \uc2 IHS Markit\uc2 , stood at 55.3 in May, marking a record for the third month in a row.\par \par \uc2 The impact of the latest wave of the pandemic is expected to show up in the June and July trade data, according to Andry Satrio, an economist researching trade and industry at the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef).\par \par \uc2 "[The worsening pandemic] can mean a setback for industries and will affect their performance in the latter part of the second quarter and in the third quarter," Andry told the Post in a voice message on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Rising capital goods imports typically reflect increasing business activity and investment, which is why a 14.09 percent month-to-month decline in May -- notwithstanding strong annual growth -- is a sign that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery remains vulnerable.\par \par \uc2 Analysts at financial intelligence firm Moody's Investor Service noted that Indonesian private sector activity was lackluster and that several indicators, such as consumer goods imports, remained weak.\par \par \uc2 "For now, the limited restrictions may contain the impact on growth, but the recovery is likely to be a shallow and bumpy one," the analysts wrote in a report released on June 23.\par \par \uc2 "Those who are able to are likely to self-isolate, which will drag on domestic demand. And with hospitals nearing capacity in some regions, additional restrictions may ultimately be unavoidable."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210701eh710000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
