\par\par \b \uc2 Advancing business respect for human rights in financial sector\b0\par\par\uc2 932 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Bahtiar Manurung and Ratih A. Putri , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Ten years have passed since the unanimous endorsement of the United Nations Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights (UNGPs) by the \uc2 UN Human Rights Council\uc2  on June 16, 2011.\par \par \uc2 Although it has long been acknowledged that businesses contribute to the fulfillment of human rights by creating jobs that allow people to achieve an adequate standard of living, delivering health services and equipment, and developing technologies that improve the quality of life, among others, business activities may also harm human rights. The UNGPs thus provide the authoritative framework for states and businesses to address this issue, prevent harm to human rights from business activities and providing victims with access to remedy when such harm has occurred.\par \par \uc2 In marking the 10th anniversary of the UNGPs, the UN Working Group on Business and Human Rights has released a stocktaking report covering the past decade. The report highlights achievements, including the adoption of human rights due diligence by global standards such as the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) Guidelines for Multinational Enterprises, the ISO 26000 standard on social responsibility and the amended 2017 Tripartite declaration of principles concerning multinational enterprises and social \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (MNE Declaration) of the \uc2 International Labor Organization\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The stocktaking report also underscores a wave of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on mandatory human rights due diligence in European countries that include France, the Netherlands, Germany and Norway, plus the current development of the \uc2 European Union\uc2  directive on mandatory human rights and environmental due diligence.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the report sheds light on the development of national action plans on business and human rights in 25 countries, one of the most visible signs of UNGPs uptake among states.\par \par \uc2 For its part, Indonesia has announced a plan to develop a similar national strategy on business and human rights, but has not completed and published such a strategy as yet. Although a national strategy on business and human rights is not a panacea in and of itself, it would be fundamental to providing comprehensive national direction, detailed actions plans and defined targets with a clear timeline for Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Another thing the report focuses on is the unparalleled power of financial actors, such as banks, insurance companies, pension funds, financing companies, institutional investors and development finance institutions, to influence businesses and scale up progress on implementing the UNGPs. These financial actors have the leverage and ability to prevent human rights harm by the companies that receive their investments or loans.\par \par \uc2 Many global financial actors are increasingly recognizing their responsibility to respect human rights and are considering human rights as criteria for their financing and investing activities, a development that has been accelerated by increased Environmental, Social and Governance (ESG) investments. These include the signatories of the Investor Alliance for Human Rights, which has a current membership of over 170 institutional investors representing over US$4 trillion in assets under management that have committed to increasing their capacity in addressing human rights risks and impacts.\par \par \uc2 Another example is the establishment of the Principles of Responsible Investment (\uc2 PRI\uc2 ), supported by the \uc2 UN\uc2 . The \uc2 PRI\uc2  signatories comprise more than 3,600 institutional investors in over 60 countries with more than $103 trillion in assets under management that acknowledge the importance of respecting human rights. The \uc2 PRI\uc2  has just published a multi-year agenda for its signatories to implement respect for human rights as defined in the UNGPs.\par \par \uc2 Realizing the unparalleled role of financial actors in influencing the uptake of respect for human rights, stock exchanges around the world have picked up the trend. Sixteen out of 56 bourses surveyed by the Sustainable Stock Exchanges Initiative referred explicitly to the UNGPs in their ESG disclosure guidance.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia needs to keep up with this trend. While \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK) \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 51/2017 on the Implementation of Sustainable Finance requires financial services institutions and publicly listed companies to submit sustainability reports, the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  does not explicitly require a report on implementing respect for human rights with reference to the UNGPs.\par \par \uc2 The absence of explicit regulations that require financial actors to report on the implementation of respect for human rights is likely one of the reasons for the lack of uptake of the UNGPs among financial actors in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 A 2019 study by the Foundation for International Human Rights Reporting Standards (FIHRRST) on the implementation of respect for human rights at large \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies and a separate 2020 study on sustainability reports revealed that the large financial services institutions included in the studies have not reported their commitment, processes and performance on human rights.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia needs to accelerate businesses' uptake of respect for human rights, particularly at a time when we are facing multiple challenges, including the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic that put workers' health and safety at risk, and amid the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the future of the modern workplace as a result of the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 As a first step, the government of Indonesia should expedite the completion of the national strategy on business and human rights. The strategy should mandate \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies\par \par \uc2 and financial services institutions to implement human rights due diligence. Meanwhile, the OJK should issue or amend the existing regulations to require \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  companies and financial services institutions to report on their human rights practice and performance.\par \par \uc2 Lastly, financial services institutions should start embedding human rights criteria into their financing and investment activities, which would significantly influence the uptake of respect for human rights among companies in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 Bahtiar Manurung is operations director and Ratih A. Putri is business and human rights specialist at FIHRRST.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210701eh7200035\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
