\par\par \b \uc2 Jokowi vows to maintain balancing act amid second wave\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Fabian Thomas, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 695 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo has vowed to keep balancing between \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health in an approach that has become increasingly precarious as a renewed COVID-19 surge brings Indonesia's healthcare system to its knees.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi told members of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) on Wednesday that he remained optimistic that the country could achieve its target of over 7 percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth in the second quarter.\par \par \uc2 However, he also acknowledged that a prolonged pandemic may mute Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth prospects such as by hitting consumer confidence and retail sales.\par \par \uc2 "We must remain vigilant. Do not just talk about economics but not look at health and do not just look at health but not look at economics. Both must go hand-in-hand," he said during the opening of Kadin's general assembly in Kendari, Southeast Sulawesi.\par \par \uc2 A second COVID-19 wave has struck Indonesia with daily new cases breaching record highs over consecutive days, peaking at 21,807 new cases on Wednesday, following the annual mudik (exodus) and the \uc2 Delta\uc2  variant's arrival.\par \par \uc2 The wave has pushed the bed occupancy rates (BORs) of hospitals in Jakarta, West Java and Banten to over 90 percent, triggered oxygen tank supply shortages in the capital and brought Indonesia's cumulative COVID-19 deaths to 58,491 as of Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 "The key to recovering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs is how to reduce this COVID-19 and suppress it so that it disappears from the motherland," Jokowi added.\par \par \uc2 The government is currently mulling plans to implement emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat) to curb the outbreak. The restrictions reportedly include a full work-from-home \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for workers in nonessential sectors and a ban on dine-in services at restaurants.\par \par \uc2 The current restrictions allow 25 percent dine-in services for restaurants and limit office occupancy to 25 percent of capacity in COVID-19 red zones.\par \par \uc2 Outgoing Kadin chairman Rosan Roeslani, in his speech on Wednesday, said the business group also hoped to see 7 percent GDP growth in the second quarter this year.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue growing this year and we will see trade surpluses in the coming quarters," he said.\par \par \uc2 Rosan also listed former Kadin heads who currently hold positions within the Jokowi Cabinet and the People's Consultative Assembly such as \uc2 Sandiaga Uno\uc2 , Erick Thohir, \uc2 Muhammad Lutfi\uc2  and \uc2 Bambang Soesatyo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Center of Economics and Law Studies (CELIOS) director Bhima Yudhistira told The Jakarta Post separately that a full lockdown would cost a fraction of the lost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  opportunities of a prolonged pandemic.\par \par \uc2 He calculated that a 14-day lockdown in Jakarta would cost Rp 7.7 trillion (US$530.1 million) whereas continuous micro-scale \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Mikro) would cost at least Rp 848 trillion by the end of the year, mostly as a result of business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Lockdown is also cheap because, once daily cases fall, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow faster," Bhima said.\par \par \uc2 United Overseas Bank (UOB) \uc2 Indonesia economist Enrico Tanuwidjaja said that tight mobility curbs might reduce the country's third quarter GDP growth to between 4.8 and 5 percent from the bank's baseline projection of 5.2 percent in the July-September period.\par \par \uc2 As a result, Indonesia's full-year GDP growth might be muted to between 3.6 and 3.7 percent compared with UOB Indonesia's baseline projection of 3.8 percent.\par \par \uc2 "This [mobility curbs] is a very bitter pill that is necessary to recover," he told the Post in an interview on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 However, he also pointed out that the government lacked the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  capacity to sustain a full-on lockdown.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Supreme Audit Agency (BPK) \uc2 recently raised concerns over Indonesia's ability to service debt given that its government debt-to-revenue ratio was 369 percent, far exceeding the International Monetary Fund-recommended threshold of 90 to 150 percent.\par \par \uc2 "For developed countries, they can do it, but for the majority of developing economies, that's where the problem lies," said Enrico.\par \par \uc2 -- Norman Harsono contributed to the story.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210701eh720002z\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 This Is Not About Money\b0\par\par\uc2 2,701 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 July 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 FINANCE Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  has her work cut out for her following the sharp increase in the number of Covid-19 cases in the past month. She now has to recalculate the state fund as the health care \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is bound to rise. The health ministry, for example, has increased the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  from Rp172 trillion to around Rp185 trillion. \u8220\'20\'1CThe \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is primarily for the purchase of 400 million doses vaccines and for patient treatment,\u8221\'20\'1D said Sri Mulyani, 58, during a special interview with Tempo via a video conference on Friday, July 2.\par \par \uc2 With the Covid curve for new cases shooting up, Sri Mulyani said, the health care costs would also soar. Last year, her ministry disbursed Rp14.6 trillion for the treatment of 200,545 Covid patients in 1,575 hospitals across the country excluding a pile of bills still being audited by the Finance and Development Supervisory Agency (BPKP) and the health ministry. Add to this the delay by several local governments in distributing the Covid response \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  which resulted in arrears in incentive payment to health care workers. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are in red zone right now so it\u8217\'20\'19s important that the PPKM (\b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions) should be enforced at the micro level such as neighborhood and community units and villages,\u8221\'20\'1D she reminded.\par \par \uc2 Having experienced in dealing with the 1997-1998 monetary crisis and steered the country through the impact of the 2008 financial crisis, Sri Mulyani sees the pandemic as a starkly difference challenge. She must brainstorm a series of strategic policies amid a barrage of news of her close family and friends being infected with the coronavirus. Not seldom, she has to personally explain policies that spark controversy and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  criticism such has those on increased state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Speaking to a team of Tempo journalists, Sri Mulyani explained about the complexity of managing the state fund amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  induced by the pandemic and the impact of the emergency PPKM on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. She must also bite the bullet and cut the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for certain ministries and institutions that are slow in channeling the Covid fund. She said the pandemic has made her more open-minded. Besides reading a lot lately, she communicates with other finance ministers to get ideas about Covid response policies in their respective countries.\par \par \uc2 The surge in Covid-19 cases has impelled the government to enforce the emergency PPKM. How does it affect the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the second quarter?\par \par \uc2 It is quite likely to affect the second quarter especially at the end of June. It (the growth) was quite high in April-May and was still okay in June up to the second week. But you could already see the softening especially in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities in the third and fourth weeks. People saw the rising cases and began to hold back. They are not as mobile. That would definitely affect, particularly our consumption. It might still reach around 7 percent in the second quarter but the growth for the third quarter will very much depend on how long the emergency PPKM will be. The longer it is, the bigger its impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. If it\u8217\'20\'19s short and effective, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will continue.\par \par \uc2 What are the consequences on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 The previously rebounding revenues and positive gross will likely remain positive but the growths will not be consistent. And the pressure to spend will increase. The need for health care \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rise and the previous \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp172 trillion has been increased to around Rp185 trillion. The \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is primarily for the purchase of 400 million doses vaccines for 181 million people and also for treatment. Our \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is almost Rp59 trillion (for this). Last year alone, we spent Rp14.5 trillion to pay for the treatment of 200,545 patients in 1,575 hospitals. And turns out that was not all. We are still receiving bills which are being audited by the BPKP and the health ministry.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani shortly before a working meeting with Commission XI of the DPR at the Parliament Complex, Jakarta, in March. Tempo/M Taufan Rengganis\par \par \uc2 How is the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjusted?\par \par \uc2 We keep trying several initiatives. First, we identify increases in health care \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Besides through the health ministry and the National Disaster Mitigation Agency (BNPB), fund for Covid-19 management and vaccination are transferred to the regions as general allocation fund or revenue sharing fund through the regional \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation process. We informed them that out of what we transferred, 8 percent must be set aside for Covid management. But the regions\u8217\'20\'19 \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for health care workers turned out to be not as swift as we imagined. That\u8217\'20\'19s why a lot of incentives have not been paid out to health care workers.\par \par \uc2 What budgets have been diverted for health care?\par \par \uc2 We will divert part of the PEN (National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp699 trillion. We will reallocate the budgets of programs that are not running or cannot be run or face hurdles to other places. Or we can divert the fund previously earmarked for business incentives such as \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives if the utilization is not big as we initially estimated. We have to because frankly speaking, we calculated \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimates based on the pre-Covid 2020 condition. Now we have to calculate based on the 2020 in the Covid pandemic. So, budgets will be reallocated but as minimal as possible within the same place. Otherwise, I will be forced to write to the ministries to refocus some trillions of rupiah previously budgeted for non-Covid purposes on Covid related matters. Or I will even have to cut their budgets and take it back for Covid. There will surely be risks but we are looking for minimum risks. Sometimes, not all the options are pleasant.\par \par \uc2 You said that the impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery would be deeper if the emergency PPKM drags on. How huge is the impact of the 17-day PPKM?\par \par \uc2 We estimate the growth of 6.5 percent particularly for the third quarter if there are no more outbreaks. But the two-week PPKM will definitely have impact. First, just look at consumption. Without the PPKM, the growth should have been around 5.5 and 5.7 percent compared to last year\u8217\'20\'19s. With the PPKM, it could drop to around 4 percent. If it goes on for one full month, consumption will nosedive. Especially in July when it usually goes up due to school holiday. Usually people are busy with holiday activities, recreation, etc. They won\u8217\'20\'19t be happening now. So, there will be a deep impact. It could even go down to 3 percent.\par \par \uc2 The government has received input from experts to strictly enforce the PPKM to stem the rising cases. What about the government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  capacity?\par \par \uc2 Some accused that the government put the emergency PPKM in effect because it is broke. Well, let me tell you that the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to assist the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  still has not been absorbed fully. As the Javanese would say turah or there is still leftover. The Family Hope program targeting 10 million people have just reached 9.9 million people this June. It was paid as per the targeted time and recipients. Only 15.9 families have received kartu sembako (basic food card) targeted for 18.8 million families as of June because Bu Risma (Social Affairs Minister Tri Rismaharini) is correcting the data. We still have the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Another one is BST (Social Cash Assistance) of Rp300,000 for 10 million recipients. Only 9.6 million have received it. Again, Bu Risma said a lot of the data are incorrect. One more program that still has a lot of money is the Village BLT (Direct Cash Assistance) allocated for eight million households. Only five million have received it. That\u8217\'20\'19s Rp300,000 per month. Even now, because of the emergency PPKM, we\u8217\'20\'19ve decided jointly with the energy and mineral resources minister to extend the electricity discount period which is supposed to end in June for another three months. Customers of 450-volt ampere are given 50 percent discount. These are multi-layered social assistance schemes. So, the point is it\u8217\'20\'19s not about money.\par \par \uc2 The audit by the \uc2 Supreme Audit Agency (BPK) \uc2 found a myriad of discrepancies and off-targets in the distribution of social aid worth Rp2.28 trillion in 2020. What is the government\u8217\'20\'19s evaluation after the fund leak?\par \par \uc2 Most of the very large leak was in BST. Ibu Risma said she would rectify everything, from the bottom to the top. She used the assistance of the universities in the regions and the Central Statistics Agency (BPS) for data validation. BPK\u8217\'20\'19s audit has been very useful for us to say, although many of us are actually already aware, that these are the options. Do we wait until we have a complete data and a good system to act or we carry on with the risks of possible inclusion and exclusion? Our \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  choice is to just do it with the available data while making improvements and that is exactly what we are doing. There will surely be risks. Finding undocumented individuals, those with unclear citizen registration number or with completely different names.\par \par \uc2 Many ministries complain about regional government\u8217\'20\'19s slow Covid management and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  absorption. Doesn\u8217\'20\'19t the finance ministry have instruments that can force regional governments to expedite them and push them to be more optimal?\par \par \uc2 That\u8217\'20\'19s what we conveyed to them early this week. We had our first meeting with Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Airlangga Hartarto regarding identifying problems relating to incentives for health care workers, acceleration of vaccination and others including the micro PPKM implementation. Neighborhood and community units and villages are at the forefront, right? Fund has been allocated in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as village \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  or village fund. But even after the village fund has been transferred, they don\u8217\'20\'19t put it to use. There are 233 local governments that have not provided assistance to villages to enforce the PPKM, 23 among them are currently categorized as red zone. As said earlier, 8 percent of the general allocation and revenue sharing funds is for villages but only 7.56 percent has been distributed.\par \par \uc2 How will the government deal with errant local governments?\par \par \uc2 We respect autonomy and decentralization. They should manage the fund based on their own systems. This is an emergency situation and they repeatedly fail to carry out their duties, so I told the governors and the home affairs minister, \u8220\'20\'1CSir, we will intercept if it (the fund distribution) doesn\u8217\'20\'19t run in July.\u8221\'20\'1D It\u8217\'20\'19s better I\u8217\'20\'19m not popular or get berated by the regions instead of Covid spreading everywhere. That\u8217\'20\'19s what we had to choose. So, I used my authority. First, we have the target to vaccinate 2 million people per day. It is a really ambitious target. The regions should facilitate it as the program is carried out by the health ministry and related departments. So, we are trying to improve the situation. The priority now is certainly effectiveness, not centralization or autonomy.\par \par \uc2 Did the Covid management fund contribute to Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s rising debt which is approaching Rp6,000 trillion?\par \par \uc2 The state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been set with a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  no higher than 5.7 percent of GDP (gross domestic product). That equals to Rp1,006 trillion. The government may not owe more than what is stipulated by the law. So, the government may bend over backwards here and there but the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) said an additional debt may not exceed Rp1,006 trillion. Therefore, if you ask me where Rp699 trillion of PEN \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will come from, well, it will come from Rp2,750 trillion state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Does this additional debt carry risks?\par \par \uc2 All the countries are piling on debts because of Covid. We also know that too much debt cannot be good for any \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But the increase (of debt) is justified because there is no other instrument except the state\u8217\'20\'19s presence in this shocking situation. If the state doesn\u8217\'20\'19t want to get involved just because it wants to stay out debt, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will sink even deeper. That\u8217\'20\'19s what is called countercyclical. We deliberately took the risks because we know that the state is here to lift everyone up. When the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rebounds, when people\u8217\'20\'19s condition improved, we will restructure the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  Ministry of Finance\par \par \uc2 You are so tactical and effective in responding to the polemic about sembako (basic commodities) \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  with your impromptu visit to the Santa market in South Jakarta and it went viral. Who gave you the idea?\par \par \uc2 The finance ministry has a routine complete management meeting attended by the deputy minister, echelon 1 staff, special staffers and expert staff. We usually discuss all the issues. From there, we prepare (responses) be it for social media, print or electronic media or television. When my colleagues said, \u8220\'20\'1CIbu, just go to the market, to the sembako traders,\u8221\'20\'1D off I went to the market and I was quite happy. And the chats were really spontaneous. I asked how their conditions were. I always accompanied my mother to the market when I was young. It was the Bulu market in Semarang (Central Java). I\u8217\'20\'19m used to interacting with merchants in the market.\par \par \uc2 You first become the finance minister in 2005 and went through many tough times. One of them was when Bank Century had to be rescued in 2008. When compared with the current condition, which is harder?\par \par \uc2 What we are facing now is a disease, not the balance sheet. This is completely different. More than 2,600 employees of the finance ministry have been infected with Covid. So were my son who is a medical doctor, my daughter-in-law, my seven-year-old grandchild. This is frightening because the disease threatens life and strikes anyone indiscriminately. When I get dizzy, I like to write poems. In one of my poems, I wrote that so many angels of death were coming down to earth. You can imagine that. It\u8217\'20\'19s a totally different game. Its impacts are massive and deep.\par \par \uc2 You sound quite determined in facing such a scary matter.\par \par \uc2 As professionals, technocrats, we will mobilize all resources we have: data, indicators, techniques and our \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  instruments. I read a lot. When I learn, for example, a given country is implementing a given \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , I wonder whether or not we can apply the same \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  here. That is a maximum effort. We have to do it and there\u8217\'20\'19s no place for pessimism. Every obstacle comes with a solution. But I always say: be humble and have humility. Because if you are arrogant, this world is finished. We also must keep an open mind and remain vigilant because we don\u8217\'20\'19t know how long this pandemic will go on.\par \par \uc2 Does a finance minister need to appear confident?\par \par \uc2 Finance minister\u8217\'20\'19s duties and responsibilities are complex. If I falter, my subordinates will falter. If my shakiness measures 10 on the Richter scale, my subordinates\u8217\'20\'19 will be 20. The lower the levels are, the bigger the (scale) will be. How can you be an anchor if you yourself waver? So, I say Bismillah (in the name of God) and a lot of dhikir (meditative recitation of God\u8217\'20\'19s attributes).\par \par \uc2 SRI MULYANI INDRAWATI | Place and Date of Birth: Bandar Lampung, August 26, 1962 | Education: Bachelor of Economics, University of Indonesia (1986), Master of Science of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Policies, \uc2 University of Illinois\uc2  Urbana-Champaign, US (1990); Ph.D. in Economics, \uc2 University of Illinois\uc2  Urbana-Champaign (1992) | Career: Executive Director, International Monetary Fund (2002-2014), Head, National Development Planning Agency (2004), Finance Minister (2005-2010), Acting \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Coordinating Minister (2008-2009), Managing Director, World Bank (2010-2016), Finance Minister (2016-2019 and 2019-now) | Organization: Chair, Indonesian Islamic \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Expert Association (2019-2023) | Awards: Best Finance Minister of Asia (2006), World\u8217\'20\'19s Best Minister (2018), Best Finance Minister for Asia-Pacific (2017-2019)\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/07/04/776445/776445_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/07/04/776447/776447_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/07/04/776446/776446_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210705eh7400002\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Driving Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s Recovery Calls for a Robust Agri-Food Industry\b0\par\par\uc2 804 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. The Covid-19 pandemic has undeniably become the test of the century for Indonesia. Measures to mitigate the global health crisis saw trade flows and tourism grind to a halt, creating a domino effect on our lives and livelihoods and the wider \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 More than a year in, we\u8217\'20\'19re beginning to see signs of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. A recent national survey by the Jakarta-based Mandiri Institute reported that over four-fifths of Indonesian small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) have started to operate normal full hours, representing increasing confidence among consumers and businesses.\par \par \uc2 When it comes to the numerous industries responsible for driving Southeast Asia\u8217\'20\'19s largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the agri-food sector holds a prominent place. The sector is responsible for more than half of the nation\u8217\'20\'19s workforce and drives more than a third of the country\u8217\'20\'19s growth domestic product (GDP).\par \par \uc2 While the sector remained resilient during the height of the pandemic, seeing a 2 percent growth in GDP contribution in 2020, experts have come out to say that post-Covid-19 recovery may not come easily. According to a recent report by Oxford Economics, Indonesia placed the worst regionally for its \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Matrix for having the highest risk recovery. The country showed important vulnerabilities due to its dependence on tourism to revive its food industry.\par \par \uc2 While we\u8217\'20\'19re seeing a glimmer of progress emerging from this crisis, new challenges will continue to arise, whether it\u8217\'20\'19s a further development of the virus or supply and demand challenges. To truly advance the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s leaders must possess an inclusive mindset of one of its most important sectors when strategizing for its post-crisis emergence.\par \par \uc2 Support a Food Industry in Recovery\par \par \uc2 Firstly, there is a need for Indonesia to create a conducive trade environment that ensures food supplies remain open, transparent, and predictable. Indonesia has seen a history of protectionist policies, but we have seen progress in liberalization. By creating more conducive trade conditions, we can ensure a reliable food network and secure source of food and ingredients for everyone \u8211\'20\'13 both on a consumer and production level.\par \par \uc2 However, policymakers need to be mindful that as imports increase, this will create greater \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  amongst local players regarding the competitive landscape. It is more important than ever that Indonesian policymakers assure the domestic sector, especially agriculture, that the government supports the industry. This includes sustaining or even raising current \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for farmers.\par \par \uc2 This also includes in the long-term using technology and skills development to improve productivity and uplift farmers and the agriculture sector, such as equipping them with the right digital tools and platforms can help from monitoring production to assessing damage from natural disasters, and even implementing early warning early action protocols, among others.\par \par \uc2 But beyond Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s strong roots in agriculture, a recovering agri-food sector requires drive growth throughout the entire industry. There are tremendous opportunities for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s food and beverage manufacturing sector to tap into given the right tools for innovation. Specifically, the halal industry is significant, with the Muslim population worldwide standing at 1.8 billion, and the halal food industry is expected to hit $2 trillion by 2024, according to the Global Islamic \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Report.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia stands to benefit if it makes the right investments and identifies key trends. For example, numerous solutions have been developed to establish halal traceability solutions via blockchain.\par \par \uc2 Limiting the Industry\u8217\'20\'19s Roadblocks\par \par \uc2 But providing such support alone is not sufficient. It is also crucial for policymakers to review whether they are unintentionally setting up roadblocks for the industry. For example, measures like excise \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on sugar and plastic should also be made in careful consideration. In early 2020, we saw similar measures being considered in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 While these reforms seek to address ongoing health and environmental problems and generate \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues, the history of such interventionist \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies is littered with examples that have backfired because they hurt consumers, businesses, and the state treasury without delivering the intended benefits.\par \par \uc2 To succeed with \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures, governments and policymakers must engage in regular communication with stakeholders to be equipped with sector expertise and support that will enable them to develop effective policies and programs that can better achieve intended outcomes.\par \par \uc2 Turning Crisis Into Opportunity\par \par \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s agri-food sector has been resilient, but we will continue to meet with strong headwinds this year. How this affects us will depend largely on \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses over the short, medium, and long term. Looking ahead, we can emerge stronger from this global crisis if pro-recovery and growth policies are introduced, enhancing the resilience, sustainability, and productivity of the sector, and in turn, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Adhi Siswaya Lukman is the chairman of the Indonesia Food and Beverage Association (Gapmmi)\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020210707eh7700003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
