\par\par \b \uc2 Recovery calls for a robust agrifood industry\b0\par\par\uc2 807 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Adhi Siswaya Lukman, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The COVID-19 pandemic has undeniably become the test of the century for Indonesia. Measures to mitigate the global health crisis saw trade flows and tourism grind to a halt, creating a domino effect on our lives and livelihoods, and the wider \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 More than a year in, we're beginning to see signs of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. A recent national survey by Jakarta-based Mandiri Institute reported that over four-fifths of\par \par \uc2 Indonesian small and medium enterprises (SMEs) have started to operate normal full hours, representing increasing confidence among consumers and businesses.\par \par \uc2 When it comes to the numerous industries responsible for driving Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the agrifood sector holds a prominent place. The sector is responsible for more than half of the nation's workforce, and drives more than a third of the country's gross domestic product (GDP).\par \par \uc2 While the sector remained resilient during the height of the pandemic, seeing a 2 percent growth in GDP contribution in 2020, experts have come out to say that post-COVID-19 recovery may not come easily. According to a recent report by Oxford Economics, Indonesia placed the worst regionally for its \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Matrix for having the highest risk recovery. The country showed important vulnerabilities due to its dependence on tourism to revive its food industry.\par \par \uc2 While we're seeing a glimmer of progress emerging from this crisis, new challenges will continue to arise, whether it's further development of the virus, or supply and demand challenges. To truly advance the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it is imperative that Indonesia's leaders possess an inclusive mindset of one of its most important sectors when strategizing for its postcrisis emergence.\par \par \uc2 First, there is a need for Indonesia to create a conducive trade environment that ensures food supplies remain open, transparent, and predictable. Indonesia has seen a history of protectionist policies, but we have seen progress in liberalization. By creating more conducive trade conditions, we can ensure a reliable food network and secure source of food and ingredients for everyone -- both on a consumer and production level.\par \par \uc2 However, policymakers need to be mindful that as imports increase, this will create greater \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  amongst local players in terms of the competitive landscape. It is more important than ever that Indonesian policymakers assure the domestic sector, especially agriculture that the government continues to support the industry. This includes sustaining or even raising current \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for farmers\par \par \uc2 This also includes in the long-term using technology and skills development to improve productivity and uplift farmers and the agriculture sector, such as equipping them with the right digital tools and platforms can help from monitoring production, to assessing damage from natural disasters, and even implementing early warning early action protocols, among others.\par \par \uc2 There is a need for Indonesia to create a conducive trade environment that ensures food supplies remain open, transparent, and predictable.\par \par \uc2 But beyond Indonesia's strong roots in agriculture, a recovering agrifood sector requires drive growth throughout the entire industry. There are tremendous opportunities for Indonesia's food and beverage manufacturing sector to tap into given the right tools for innovation. Specifically, the halal industry is significant, with the Muslim population worldwide standing at 1.8 billion, and the halal food industry expected to hit US$2 trillion by 2024, according to the Global Islamic \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Report. Indonesia stands to benefit if it makes the right investments and identify key trends. For example, numerous solutions have been developed to establish halal traceability solutions via blockchain.\par \par \uc2 But providing such support alone is not sufficient. It is also crucial for policymakers to review whether they are unintentionally setting up roadblocks for the industry. For example, measures like excise \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on sugar and plastic should also be made in careful consideration. In early 2020, we saw similar measures being considered in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 While these reforms seek to address ongoing health and environmental problems as well as generate \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues, the history of such interventionist \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies is littered with examples that have backfired because they hurt consumers, businesses, and the state treasury without delivering the intended benefits.\par \par \uc2 To succeed with \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures, governments and policymakers must engage in regular communication with stakeholders so as to be equipped with sector expertise and support that will enable them to develop effective policies and programs that can better achieve intended outcomes.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's agrifood sector has been resilient, but we will continue to meet with strong headwinds this year. How this affects us will depend largely on \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses over the short, medium, and long term.\par \par \uc2 Looking ahead, we can emerge stronger from this global crisis if pro-recovery and growth policies are introduced, enhancing the resilience, sustainability, and productivity of the sector, and in turn, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Chairman of the Indonesian Food and Beverage Association (GAPMMI)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210708eh7800005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
