\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal \highlight\uc2  dominance to avert greater macro problems\b0\par\par\uc2 994 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Kristianus Pramudito Isyunanda, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The government has resorted to stricter mobility curbs, which will last until July 25. For the second time since the COVID-19 pandemic struck in March last year, such an intervention is inevitable to stop the exponential virus transmission. At the same time, we should examine and mitigate the impact of the emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat) on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial sectors as the trade-off.\par \par \uc2 The struggling \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will encounter challenges similar to previous problems. The real \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  faces "dual problems" from the supply and demand sides. Of course, the consequences might be minimized for essential goods and services by implementing a safe harbor for them. But we should not overlook the rest of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Some market experts have expressed that the financial sector is somewhat "immune" from the changing-mobility policies. But it is not necessarily the case. More constrained businesses would likely be transmitted to the financial markets, thanks to the intertwined relations among sectors in the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 For a solution, let us start by examining the current macro condition. The latest data on gross domestic product (GDP) growth in the first quarter (Q1) of 2021 is negative 0.74 percent year-on-year. Even though GDP is still contracting, it is quickly recovering, at least for the time being until we see what effect the PPKM Darurat have on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is evident that the contraction is getting smaller over time.\par \par \uc2 The government and authorities are optimistic, even if they revised the outcome projection to between 4.1 and 5.1 percent. The optimistic view is supported by some reliable data and dynamics. In the external sector, Indonesia has a better position on net international investment (25.3 percent of GDP per Q1 2021), \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  adequacy (US$137.1 billion as of June 2021) and trade balance surplus ($2.36 billion as of May 2021).\par \par \uc2 The advanced economies in the western world are showing a strong recovery, which is mainly due to their outstanding vaccination performance.\par \par \uc2 On the downside, we must be careful about the adverse impact on emerging markets, including Indonesia. Capital would rationally take off to safer havens once it is readily available (i.e., the rise of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in advanced countries). Nevertheless, the \uc2 European Union\uc2  region faces similar problems as ours, namely fast spread of the virus due to Euro 2020 euphoria.\par \par \uc2 United States inflation is, however, not yet so fundamental and wide that there is a serious risk of a "taper tantrum". But they might get there sooner than we expect. Hence, we must stay alert.\par \par \uc2 In the monetary and financial sectors, we have seen that \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) seven-day reverse repo rate (7DRRR) held at 3.5 percent. The easing of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues with more accommodative macroprudential \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to regain the state of credit.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, BI began to consistently publish the assessment on \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate transmission to banks' prime lending rate (SBDK).\par \par \uc2 Unsurprisingly, more transparency on SBDK works for gradually narrowing the gap between the market rate of credit and the 7DRRR. Although it remains negative 1.28 percent year-on-year, the banking intermediary is improving.\par \par \uc2 However, banking liquidity is leaning toward excessiveness. The embedded factors are still-loosened monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , credit restructuring program and the price of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . From the macro perspective, unproductive liquidity equals Keynesian "hoarding risks" as the deflationary force. Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has its limitation because it cannot directly affect the real sector.\par \par \uc2 In the words of Prof. Paul A. McCulley, too much liquidity creation relative to the credit creation for productivity is the existential macro problem (i.e. "hoarding risks"). Hence, we should look for a solution. And for the viable solution, just as at the beginning of this pandemic, we turn to \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance (i.e. government-dependent \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 I am not against PPKM Darurat. On the contrary, we should be sincere that today's exponential COVID-19 transmission must be met with more resolute measures. Even so, we should again highlight the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance position. It is essential to realize that more restrictions on mobilization of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would put the acceleration of the supply \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as consumption on hold.\par \par \uc2 We should focus on these three indicators: expected velocity of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, excessive liquidity on the banking system and embedded risks born from the global factors. It is now important, more than ever, to ensure productivity, invoke consumption and retain confidence. The goal is not to lose our momentum, not to start from scratch.\par \par \uc2 PPKM Darurat could serve as a "speed bump" for all of those, but with the right measures, we will soon regain our pace. Glad to know that Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  has stated that she would intercept if there was still slow absorption of the health sector \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the regional level and make the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  available to support PPKM Darurat.\par \par \uc2 We could expect a better government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance amid this lower mobilization of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 To conclude, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance should, by all means, lead the way of productive endeavors. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authority is in a position to lead the way by either \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  investment or productive private investments. In doing so, we could boost productivity, consumption and confidence.\par \par \uc2 Considering that credit growth remains slow, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance is the viable solution to avert greater macro problems. Other measures on monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and macroprudential toolkits are readily available as the support system of said \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance.\par \par \uc2 Soon after the COVID-19 pandemic is manageable, we must indeed reexamine the dynamics. The impact of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  dominance in the long run needs evaluation. But we are not there yet.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is about a cycle, thus perhaps it is true that economists shall never sleep, even if the condition is comfortable enough for them to sleep. We can and will go through this together.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par 