\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: 2H21  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  review: Mitigating further risk from second wave\b0\par\par\uc2 907 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Andry Asmoro, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Like other emerging countries, Indonesia is facing a major COVID-19 wave and the government has launched several measures to cushion the impact of the pandemic, including the implementation of emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat).\par \par \uc2 Prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  will affect people's confidence in doing business and hence will negatively affect the full-year \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Based on our calculations, GDP growth in the second quarter of 2021 (2Q21) year-on-year (yoy) could reach above 6 percent if the expansion continues and drop significantly in 3Q21 because of lower business transactions with the mobility restrictions. Now, the million-dollar-question will be about the further outlook of Indonesia's wider \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the banking sector during the current situation.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's GDP has room to recover from 2020's negative COVID-19 impact. Our leading indicators reveal that government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has pushed some sectors and segments to gradually recover since April. However, some mobility restrictions in January, due to rising COVID-19 cases after the New Year holiday, pushed down the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  index to below 100. It took 15 weeks to recover from the first implementation of restrictions on Jan. 10.\par \par \uc2 Thus, the lost momentum in 1Q21 has returned in the second quarter this year and reached its peak in May. Approaching the Ramadan fasting month and Idul Fitri, consumers began to have confidence to spend and reallocate their goods basket toward nonfood \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This was a good sign for recovery, and it was led by a positive \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  trend.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, rising commodity prices have pushed commodity-producing regions, for example Sumatra, Kalimantan and Sulawesi, to become the major drivers of recovery while Java followed behind due to some mobility restrictions in the midst of high numbers of COVID-19 cases. We have seen two kinds of recovery in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  indices: A "swoosh-shaped" recovery in Sumatra, Kalimantan, Java and Sulawesi and an "L-shaped" recovery in Bali and Nusa Tenggara, which are dependent on the tourist sector.\par \par \uc2 As for the impact from mobility restrictions, lower \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and reduced investment appetite can be expected if COVID-19 cases continue to rise and the restrictions continue. Based on our historical data, it took around seven to eight weeks for \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to recover and reach the same level of \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  index on the first day of the earlier large-scale social restrictions (PSBB). It took 15 weeks for the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  index to recover post mobility restrictions in January.\par \par \uc2 Thus, we expect that a similar pattern will apply to the current PPKM Darurat but with milder effect compared with the first restrictions. However, we should note that making sure that everyone is vaccinated and health protocols are implemented will also significantly ease healthcare providers' burden and give business players more confidence.\par \par \uc2 At this juncture, we see a downward revision of our GDP growth forecast to 3.7 percent, from the initial 4.4 percent. We still expect that direct investment, which kicked in since the beginning of the year, could provide support in the second half.\par \par \uc2 Lower GDP growth expectations will mean more pressure on the banking sector in terms of loan growth and asset quality. In fact, the banking industry also had a gradual recovery after the 2020 pandemic contraction, in line with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery path. As of May, loan growth had a much smaller contraction of 1.2 percent yoy from the previous year at around 2 percent. In the year-to-date performance, loans had finally posted positive growth in the last two months in a row at 0.7 percent.\par \par \uc2 Banks, indeed, remain selective in disbursing loans to ensure improvement in asset quality ratios but the loan growth is posted at gradual improvement. Going forward, we expect that loan growth will stay at around 3 to 4 percent, relatively lower than our initial projection of 5 percent, mainly due to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 From the asset quality side, the nonperforming loan (NPL) ratio has been relatively stable at 3.2 percent in the last three months. Banks' loans-at-risk have improved, as the outstanding restructured loans impacted by COVID-19 have decreased, given that some impacted debtors have started recovering. Some COVID-19 impacted debtors may still fall into NPL status even after the loans have been restructured and banks may need to conduct a second round of restructuring to ensure the soundness of asset quality.\par \par \uc2 To anticipate a further increase in NPLs, banks have continued to build loan loss provision to around Rp 326 trillion (US$22.53 billion) as of April, much higher than the Rp 311 trillion in January. Although loans-at-risk have improved, the NPLs in some major industries remain high. The NPLs were mostly affected by \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performances. The sooner the health situation and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recover, the better banks' asset quality will be.\par \par \uc2 Thus, we believe that Indonesia still has room to grow faster than its performance in 2020 based on several leading indicators. Some hiccups may occur in 3Q21 in some \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment numbers. But as people's \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has repeatedly rebounded fast in the past, this indicates that Indonesians will easily go back to \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  soon after the restrictions end. At this point, the recovery will return to the right trajectory and we hope that it will happen before the fourth quarter of this year.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Chief economist of Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210713eh7d0008h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
