\par\par \b \uc2 Employers call for relief as restrictions extended\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 758 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The looming extension of the COVID-19 emergency restrictions on travel and business activities could jeopardize Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, threatening businesses and workers alike, industry experts have cautioned.\par \par \uc2 Earlier this week, Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  told a \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  hearing that the government was considering extending the emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat) from 18 days at present to between four and six weeks.\par \par \uc2 The PPKM Darurat were initially implemented with a view to remaining in place from July 3 to July 20, but the alarming surge in infections has raised doubts over its efficacy in reducing daily cases during that time frame.\par \par \uc2 Deputy chair Shinta Kamdani of the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) said it was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  how long businesses could survive while the emergency restrictions were in place. Small businesses typically did not have the financial resources to maintain their operations for more than four weeks, she said, especially amid a drastic fall in demand.\par \par \uc2 "We hope a PPKM Darurat of between four and six weeks can significantly reduce COVID-19 transmission. We really do not want the PPKM Darurat to last any longer [than that]," Shinta told The Jakarta Post by text message.\par \par \uc2 Unemployment in the country could return to last year's level with businesses under pressure to operate at reduced capacity, Shinta noted, while adding that Apindo had not yet collected any relevant data.\par \par \uc2 The plan to extend the emergency restrictions emerged before Indonesia saw a record-breaking 54,517 new daily cases on Wednesday. This was followed on Thursday with another record-breaking 56,757 new cases, the highest daily tally since COVID-19 was declared a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health emergency in March 2020.\par \par \uc2 Under the current emergency curbs in place across Java and Bali as well as several other regions, all shopping malls must close. An exception applies to supermarkets, traditional markets and stores selling basic commodities, including retailers located inside malls, which are allowed to operate at 50 percent visitor capacity until 8 p.m.\par \par \uc2 We hope a PPKM Darurat of between four and six weeks can\par \par \uc2 significantly reduce COVID-19 transmission. We really do not want the\par \par \uc2 PPKM Darurat to last any longer [than that].\par \par \uc2 Restaurants may only provide takeaway and delivery services, and are banned from providing dine-in services.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Shopping Center Association (APPBI) expects the pressure to increase, as companies have been burning through their cash \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to survive the pandemic-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn.\par \par \uc2 APPBI chairman Alphonzus Widjaja said shopping centers needed government relief support through incentives to survive the PPKM Darurat period, such as the relaxation of land and building \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PBB) and a 50 percent wage \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Shopping centers' revenue has fallen sharply," Alphonzus stated in a press release on Wednesday. "It is true that the first half of 2021 was better than 2020, but shopping centers still booked losses because of the 50 percent cap on visitors."\par \par \uc2 Fitch Ratings\uc2  has forecast that Indonesia's retail sales will weaken in the third quarter but rebound in the fourth quarter, assuming that the restrictions were not extended and the government accelerated the national vaccination program.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  projected that the retail sales index would grow 4.53 percent year-on-year (yoy) in June, slowing from the 14.73 percent yoy increase seen in May.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  also indicated that it expected a slowdown in business activities. In its banking activities survey for the April-June period, the weighted net balance stood at nearly 19 percent, meaning that more businesses reported an increase in activity. The figure declined to 9.77 percent for the third quarter, however, suggesting waning business confidence.\par \par \uc2 The Confederation of Indonesian Trade Unions (KSPI) said it backed the emergency curbs but called on the government to protect labor rights amid potential layoffs. KSPI president Said Iqbal said sick workers needed government support to buy medicines and vitamins while they self-isolated.\par \par \uc2 "Honestly, the threat of mass layoffs is already in sight, because many companies have asked unions to talk about programs for cutting staff," he said in a press release on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Reflecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery seen earlier in the year, Statistics Indonesia data show that the number of workers affected by the pandemic through job loss or pay cuts had declined to 19.1 million in February, down 34.4 percent from August 2020. But the February figure still represented 9.3 percent of the workforce, with the majority experiencing reduced working hours.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210717eh7h0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
