\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Recovery process of manufacturing sector after PPKM Darurat\b0\par\par\uc2 917 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Astari Adityawati, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The manufacturing industry's performance increased in the second quarter of 2021, which was its expansion phase,as reflected in the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Prompt Manufacturing Index (PMI-BI) of 51.45 percent, up from 50.01 percent in the first quarter and 28.55 percent in the second quarter of last year.\par \par \uc2 The index increase occurred in almost all components, especially production volume and total order volume, which were in the expansion phase. By subsector, increased performances in the second quarter of 2021 were food, beverage and tobacco; paper and printed goods; as well as fertilizer, chemical and rubber goods, which were already in the expansion phase. These were driven by increased demand during Ramadan and Idul Fitri.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the IHS Markit Indonesian Manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) was recorded at 53.5 in June amid an increase in national COVID-19 cases. This figure was lower than the record seen in May, which was 55.3. The lower Indonesian Manufacturing PMI in June indicated a decrease in output, demand and purchases from the previous month, but it was still at the expansion level.\par \par \uc2 According to Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data, the manufacturing industry contracted by 1.38 percent year-on-year (yoy) in the first quarter of this year. Nevertheless, some industrial subsectors continued to grow, namely food and beverages, which grew by 2.45 percent, chemical and pharmacy (11.46 percent), basic metal (7.71 percent), machinery equipment (3.22 percent) and furniture (8.04 percent). The increase in these subsectors' growth is in line with the PMI-BI. At last, the manufacturing industry sector continues to show positive performance.\par \par \uc2 Due to the implementation of the government's emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat) on July 3-20 and the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 's planned extension, the Manufacturing Index is predicted to experience another slowdown. This is in line with BI's forecast that in the third quarter, the PMI-BI would be at 49.89 percent, lower than the achievement in the second quarter.\par \par \uc2 The lower PMI-BI projection is due to a decrease in the majority of its components, particularly production volume, volume of finished goods and total number of workers who were in this contraction phase. The subsectors that may slow down include paper and printed goods; food, beverage and tobacco; and transport and machinery equipment.\par \par \uc2 We also project that the future of the Manufacturing Index will depend on the surge of COVID-19 cases. We see that the manufacturing sector's performance is determined by the effectiveness of the efforts to reduce daily COVID-19 cases.\par \par \uc2 PPKM Darurat is expected to impact activities in several business sectors because of a high number of restrictions. In July, it seems that the manufacturing sector will have to face quite a challenge and it may potentially cause the sector's growth to decline. The number of restrictions in several regencies and municipalities may lead to a lower production rate as a result of a limited number of workers. Production levels could also fall as new businesses are weakened amid the second wave of COVID-19.\par \par \uc2 The increase in the spread of the Delta variant could also lead to a slowdown in production performance at factories, so business players will need more time to fulfill orders. At the same time, the price of raw materials will increase relatively quickly during PPKM Darurat. Moreover, there will be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects.\par \par \uc2 It is hoped that the emergency restrictions can reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  mobility and reducing COVID-19 cases, thereby helping the manufacturing sector to grow.\par \par \uc2 We also hope that the government's ongoing COVID-19 vaccination drive will help curb the virus. With government policies and community participation working to suppress the spike in COVID-19 cases, the manufacturing sector's performance can continue to show a recovery, including output, domestic demand, exports and number of workers, which can help increase production capacity.\par \par \uc2 From our viewpoint, the manufacturing sector will experience a contraction, although there is the expectation that some factors could drive recovery in the manufacturing sector going forward, namely domestic demand and exports.\par \par \uc2 We estimate that the manufacturing industry will recover gradually after the PPKM Darurat \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is eased. The first subsectors to recover will likely be those related to the consumption of basic needs, such as food and beverages, fast-moving consumer goods and pharmaceuticals.\par \par \uc2 They are followed by the consumption of durable goods, such as clothing, shoes, electronics and vehicles, which are related to the textile, footwear, transportation and machinery equipment subsectors.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, with domestic demand increasing for both basic needs and durable goods, the recovery in the manufacturing sector will occur in the near future. Hence, when emergency curbs come to an end, the growth of the manufacturing sector would be stronger.\par \par \uc2 To sum up, the COVID-19 pandemic has affected Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation. Hence, some strategies are needed in response to various challenges so that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can recover and grow. Improvements in the manufacturing industry, investment climate and productivity, as well as the expansion of exports strongly influence \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation. The manufacturing industry should be the main driver of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery because it offers great opportunities to create better jobs.\par \par \uc2 The industrialization strategy should be implemented in the future, with more adaptive strategies and better resilience against challenges such as the COVID-19 pandemic. This can create a better \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transformation.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Economist at Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210721eh7l00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
