\par\par \b \uc2 Help us pay wages or we cut jobs, firms tell govt\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Fabian Thomas, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 914 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Feeling the pinch of recently extended nationwide activity curbs to combat a second wave of COVID-19, businesses have urged the government to provide help, including a wage \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to alleviate their burden.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian Shopping Center Association (APPBI) chairman Alphonzus Widjaja said that the pandemic had hit them hard as they were forced to operate below capacity and even close malls during certain periods.\par \par \uc2 The latest extension of the emergency \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM Darurat) had worsened their financial situation.\par \par \uc2 Should the emergency curbs remain in place, APPBI members would be unable to pay their workers, forcing them to put staff on unpaid leave, or worse, cut jobs, Alphonzus said.\par \par \uc2 "We hope the government can subsidize around half of our employees' wages in order to avoid layoffs," Alphonzus told reporters during an online press conference on Wednesday, adding that the association also demanded \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and electricity relief.\par \par \uc2 The government recently extended the PPKM Darurat by five days to July 25 but promised to ease the rules once cases declined. Indonesia saw the number of new daily cases rise sharply to 56,757 on July 15. The number has since come back down, fallingto 33,772 on Wednesday, but that is still far above the government's short-term target of fewer than 10,000 new daily infections.\par \par \uc2 Other business associations backed the APPBI's plea about wage \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  through a joint statement, namely the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo), the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) and associations representing various industries, such as ceramics, textiles, footwear, cosmetics, electronics, plastic, cement and food and beverages.\par \par \uc2 Aside from wage \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the joint statement also demands looser workplace restrictions. Should COVID-19 cases rise again in such a scenario, the workplace occupancy cap could be selectively lowered again, the associations suggested.\par \par \uc2 In nonessential sectors, they demanded that at least 50 percent of employees be allowed to work on premises, and at least 25 percent in auxiliary roles. Currently, businesses in nonessential sectors must apply a 100 percent work-from-home (WFH) regime.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the demands include looser restrictions in essential sectors, allowing them to operate at full capacity, like the critical sectors. Currently, a 50 percent WFH mandate applies.\par \par \uc2 Kadin chairman Arsjad Rasjid said he would talk to the government regarding those demands. He said the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  could help alleviate the burden on both workers and businesses.\par \par \uc2 "The government must listen to what we [businesses] want, so that there is a balance [between the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and health]," Arsjad said at the same press conference.\par \par \uc2 Apindo chairman Hariyadi Sukamdani went further by asking the government not to extend the PPKM Darurat beyond July 25, warning that businesses could not bear the situation any longer.\par \par \uc2 He said many companies had already been forced to give employees unpaid leave, and some had terminated employment contracts. This situation, he admitted, was slightly better than in 2020 but could worsen again.\par \par \uc2 "If the rules are relaxed immediately by July 25, hopefully there will be no mass layoffs," Hariyadi said at the same press conference.\par \par \uc2 Fiber Producers Association (APSyFI) secretary-general Redma Gita Wirawasta added that prolonged restrictions could be burdensome for their members. He said many companies would be forced to lay off employees, especially those working on temporary contracts.\par \par \uc2 "We are asking for the government's cooperation so that the PPKM are not extended," Redma said at the same press conference.\par \par \uc2 The government appears to have an open ear for these concerns. Responding on the same day, Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said the government was expecting to finalize in a matter of days a plan to subsidize wages.\par \par \uc2 The government also added Rp 10 trillion (US$687.66 million) to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for its preemployment card program, which offers cash transfers for training and sustenance, raising the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the program to Rp 30 trillion.\par \par \uc2 "The preemployment card is focused on workers facing layoffs," Sri Mulyani said in an online press briefing on Wednesday. "With the additional Rp 10 trillion, we can add 2.8 million recipients, so we can add those facing layoffs or pay cuts."\par \par \uc2 While businesses are struggling, consumers too are under financial strain. According to the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2 , the nonperforming financing (NPF) ratio in the multifinance industry has reached 4.05 percent, the highest level so far this year.\par \par \uc2 The OJK said the rise was caused by financial stress on many borrowers, which lowered their ability to repay consumer loans, as quoted by Kontan. At the same time, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has made borrowers more reluctant to apply for loans.\par \par \uc2 Center of Reform on Economics (CORE) Indonesia researcher Yusuf Rendy Manilet warned the NPF ratio would continue to rise over the next few months as activity restrictions were likely to remain in place.\par \par \uc2 "I expect many consumers and businesses will still have trouble paying their loans," Yusuf told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 The same trend was seen in banks' nonperforming loan (NPL) ratio, which has reached 3.35 percent most recently, the highest so far this year.\par \par \uc2 Moody's Analytics mentioned Indonesia in a July 20 report among other emerging markets that would see a rise in problematic loans due to new waves of virus infections hampering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. By the end of the year, \uc2 Moody's\uc2  estimated, Indonesia's NPL ratio could reach 3.5 percent, increasing the asset risks in banks across the country.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210722eh7m00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
