\par\par \b \uc2 Vaccine diplomacy new paradigm in foreign  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 864 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Teuku Faizasyah, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Retno's vaccine diplomacy. That was the headline of The Jakarta Post's editorial on July 14. The editorial presents a succinct observation of her leadership to win national interest in the health sector during the pandemic through diplomatic means.\par \par \uc2 Such kudos from the Post is heartening to those serving in the Foreign Ministry in Pejambon, Central Jakarta and in Indonesian missions overseas. Simply said it is uplifting.\par \par \uc2 With the pandemic entering its second year, there has been much adaptation carried out within Indonesian diplomacy, including diplomatic conduct.\par \par \uc2 For one thing, the pandemic has made it difficult for diplomats to travel and have face-to-face interaction with their counterparts. Hence, the use of digital means to communicate has increased significantly, coining the term digital diplomacy.\par \par \uc2 Within the ambit of \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  management, this drop in traveling has been a means to refocus programs and the initial \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is then shifted for social safety net purposes.\par \par \uc2 Whereas refocusing in the context of foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is to bring about health and vaccine diplomacy as important features in Indonesian diplomacy. They complement the "four plus one" priorities in diplomacy as prescribed by Minister Retno LP Marsudi in early January 2021.\par \par \uc2 Those priorities are to strengthen the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , protect nationals overseas, safeguard national sovereignty and to sustain Indonesia's role at the regional and global level. While the additional priority is to strengthen diplomatic infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 These priorities provide Indonesian diplomats with a compass to navigate today's era of great \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The projection of those priorities from Pejambon are also in consonance with subsequent directives by President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo. Currently, the directive focuses on eff orts to mitigate COVID-19 and all its unintended consequences, and therefore vaccine diplomacy.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, vaccine diplomacy is one of the areas to which the ministry has paid greater attention since early on. Minister Retno on her own and the whole diplomatic machinery pursue diplomatic efforts to open access for vaccines, both from bilateral and multilateral frameworks.\par \par \uc2 On the multilateral front, as co-chair of COVAX Advance Market Commitment (AMC) Engagement Group, Minister Retno is entrusted with a noble mission to galvanize enough supply of vaccines for fair distribution among member countries.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia fully supports the concept of health for all and to ensure COVID-19 vaccines as a global \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  good. As the country that hosted the Asian-African Conference in 1955, Indonesia highly regards the principle of solidarity among nations.\par \par \uc2 A call for solidarity is even more urgent these days when many developing countries, especially on the African continent, are deeply aff ected by COVID-19. And they are struggling for access to vaccines. Roughly only 18 million people in Africa--1.5 percent of the total population--have been fully vaccinated.\par \par \uc2 On the encouraging side, we are witnessing new developments where some countries, including the United States, are engaging in vaccine sharing practices. Indonesia is one of the benefi ciaries of these practices and has received vaccine sharing from the US and Japan.\par \par \uc2 Such support and cooperation are timely as Indonesia is now facing a new surge of COVID-19 infections. In the process, the ministry is gauging expression of interest of support from some countries. Their good intention is highly appreciated as the coronavirus has put to test the capacity of our health system.\par \par \uc2 Hence, Minister Retno tasked the secretary-general of the Foreign Ministry with coordinating the international support and conducting a needs assessment exercise together with officials from the Health Ministry.\par \par \uc2 Cooperation and collaboration at the domestic and international levels during these trying times are conditio sine qua non. The pandemic aff ects us all, indiscriminately. At the domestic level every stakeholder, including the Foreign Ministry has their own fair share in the eff orts to tackle the COVID-19 challenges.\par \par \uc2 It is often mentioned, metaphorically, that as a nation the Indonesian people are sailing together in one big ship. President Jokowi as the shipmaster is navigating that ship, which at the moment has encountered a perfect storm.\par \par \uc2 The Foreign Ministry has a unique role during this turbulent time. It is standing in the crow's nest, scanning the horizon and helping the shipmaster to stay on course and survive the storm.\par \par \uc2 They also have the advantage of looking on issues with a helicopter view. While others tend to focus more on their areas of responsibility, the ministry can help connect the dots.\par \par \uc2 All in all, vaccine diplomacy to advance national capacity and health resilience are works in progress considering that the light at the end of the pandemic tunnel still looks dim. There are pundits who even suggest that we need to get ready to have this COVID-19 as our strange bedfellow. Their arguments are sensible as the virus continues to mutate across the globe.\par \par \uc2 As the global fight against the pandemic intensifies, the world where we are living has not been exempted from various sets of challenges. Hence, the Indonesian diplomatic corps need to find the right balance in pursuing each of the "four plus one" priorities in tandem with vaccine diplomacy.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 Former Indonesian ambassador to Canada. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210727eh7r00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
