\par\par \b \uc2 IMF\uc2  reduces Indonesia's GDP growth forecast for 2021\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 499 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 July 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  has revised down this year's gross domestic product (GDP) growth forecast for Indonesia to 3.9 percent as the country grapples with a Delta COVID-19 variant outbreak amid a low vaccination rate.\par \par \uc2 The revision is 0.4 percentage points lower than the growth forecast outlined in the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's April outlook.\par \par \uc2 The downward revision is in line with that of the government, which downgraded its GDP growth forecast to between 3.7 and 4.5 percent from between 4.5 and 5.3 percent for this year.\par \par \uc2 "The COVID-19 pandemic brings immense \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We need to be extremely careful and continue to comply with health protocols. We've also learned that vaccination acceleration is key to controlling cases," the head of the Finance Ministry's \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency (BKF), Febrio Kacaribu, was quoted in a news release as saying on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Daily new confirmed coronavirus cases swelled to more than 50,000 in mid-July but have shown signs of falling since. Daily new confirmed deaths remain on the rise, breaking another record at 2,069 on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 The recent pandemic wave, driven largely by the \uc2 Delta\uc2  variant, is expected to disrupt the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, which had shown progress, as reflected in the smaller annual GDP contraction of 0.74 percent in the first quarter.\par \par \uc2 While annual GDP growth is forecast to benefit from a low-base effect in the April-to-June period, it is estimated to slow to between 4 and 5.4 percent in the August-to-September period, according to Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2 , noting the impact on consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investment.\par \par \uc2 Then it will pick up to between 4.6 and 5.9 percent in the fourth quarter.\par \par \uc2 For next year, the \uc2 IMF\uc2  projects 5.9 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for Indonesia, up a mere 0.1 percentage point from the earlier forecast.\par \par \uc2 The government has raised the healthcare and social aid \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cushion the impact from the latest surge in cases and deaths, resulting in a Rp 46 trillion (US$3.17 billion) additional recovery \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The country's COVID-19 \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  in total is now worth a little over 4.8 percent of its GDP last year.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 IMF\uc2  left its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecast unchanged, expecting it to stand at 6.2 percent this year. However, this is wider than the 5.7 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  target outlined by the government.\par \par \uc2 The Center of Reform on Economics (CORE) Indonesia is less optimistic about this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook following the implementation of emergency COVID-19 curbs, estimating GDP growth at between 2.5 and 3.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 "But the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains high," CORE Indonesia executive director Mohammad Faisal told The Jakarta Post in a phone interview.\par \par \uc2 "The dynamics hinge on the fall in cases after implementing emergency curbs and how fast they get lifted."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210730eh7u0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
