\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Strategic alliances to herald new era in Indonesian oil and gas\b0\par\par\uc2 1,232 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 August 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Henricus Herwin, Eddie Martono and Pan Li, \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG)\uc2 , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's oil and gas production has been declining over the past decade. Oil production fell from 970 million barrels of oil per day (mbopd) in 2010 to just 710 mbopd in 2020.\par \par \uc2 We are already seeing an accelerating decline in the production of both oil and gas, primarily driven by the natural decline of mature assets. Compounding this challenge has been the reduction in capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in recent years, triggered by the 2014 oil price drop and reducing resources to develop. As a result, the capital allocated to oil and gas exploration almost halved in 2014-2018.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has an aspirational target to reverse this decline and deliver 1,000 mbopd of oil and 12,000 million standard cubic feet (mmscfd) of gas by 2030, a rise of 30 percent and 60 percent respectively, to meet energy demand.\par \par \uc2 Realizing these goals will require focus in four strategic areas: (1) managing baseline production, (2) accelerating conversion from resource to production, (3) implementing enhanced oil recovery (EOR) technology and (4) enhancing exploration.\par \par \uc2 Each focus area presents specific challenges which must be overcome. Operational excellence and robust reservoir management will be critical to sustaining baseline production while tackling cost challenges in the journey from resource to production.\par \par \uc2 Narrow success in the use of EOR technologies must be overcome and advancements maintained while mitigating high capital cost requirements. Indonesia must also overcome its stalling exploration segment, which has had a reserve-replacement ratio of just 60 percent over the last four years.\par \par \uc2 The industry also faces wider challenges with the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of future oil prices compounded by the green energy shift by the super majors and global oil companies. Average capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  on green energy was 10 percent in 2020 compared to 3 percent in 2018, and is expected to reach 30 percent by 2030. Many global investors are shifting from fossil fuels toward cleaner energy.\par \par \uc2 This presents an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  platform for the entire oil and gas ecosystem and requires a shift to a more collaborative system of strategic alliances, whereby operators and contractors not only share risks and upsides but also optimize joint ways of working with better planning, culture and technology transfers, with a fit-for-purpose program.\par \par \uc2 Strategic alliances could also be formed between operators and contractors to implement valuable digitalization programs. For example, Total and \uc2 Google\uc2  Cloud have signed a strategic alliance deal to jointly develop artificial intelligence (AI) solutions for subsurface data analysis in exploration and production. This will allow Total to explore and assess oil fields faster and more effectively, reducing the duration from acquisition time to seismic data interpretation from months to days.\par \par \uc2 Strategic imperative\par \par \uc2 Different operating models and toolkits are required to capture maximum value from different assets. Most major global oil companies operate more than 80 percent of their assets with partners, recognizing the benefits of their partners' technical capabilities and risk sharing. In contrast, major national oil companies (NOCs) in Southeast Asia retain full operatorship over 60 percent of assets, with \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  operating over two-thirds of its asset \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 There are many reasons for this difference, with NOCs playing an integral role in energy security and offering arm's-length government management of terminated and returned assets.\par \par \uc2 Strategic alliances offer an important alternative with zero equity transaction, whereby a contractor owns a specific scope of work and in return commits to an attractive value proposition with shared risks and upsides. This creates a win-win collaboration for both operator and contractor.\par \par \uc2 Value creation for operators includes a potential increase in production and \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 , faster exploration and development of assets, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits through better planning and execution.\par \par \uc2 Value creation for contractors includes the potential for significant business opportunities, tapping into the upside potential based on risk-reward schemes, and expanding the country's footprint by growing with the operator. The urgency for contractors to form longer term partnerships, especially in oilfield services, is being accelerated by the shift to non-fossil fuel businesses by many global oil and gas operators.\par \par \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG) \uc2 recently helped to establish a strategic alliance between a European operator and a contractor for an integrated drilling well hub powered by machine learning and AI-enabled analytics, resulting in up to 25 percent reduction in well drilling cost.\par \par \uc2 Reaching Indonesia's ambitious target\par \par \uc2 Significant efforts will be needed to meet Indonesia's ambitious oil and gas aspirations, with a projected US$400 billion to $500 billion investment needed over the next 20 years. State-owned oil holding company \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  will play an integral role in this journey. We have identified four prioritized use cases that could successfully drive this transformation.\par \par \uc2 Alliance to manage late-stage assets: Alliances with contractors who specialize in late-stage assets could help free up capital, allowing allocation of high-performing resources to priority assets.\par \par \uc2 Alliance to implement EOR technologies: Successful implementation of EOR in maturing fields will be a key enabler to improving recovery rates and production. Operators could benefit from an alliance with contractors who possess EOR IP and with successful implementation experience.\par \par \uc2 Alliance to drive exploration success: There are over 50 unexplored basins in Indonesia, with sizeable oil potential in the west and gas potential in the east. Indonesia's success rate is around 50 percent, relatively lower than peers like Thailand (77 percent) and Argentina (65 percent). Operators could benefit from alliances with contractors that have proven technological capability to increase the probability of big discoveries.\par \par \uc2 Alliance to unlock value through digitalization: Improving uptime and reducing operating expenses (OPEX0 by partnering with contractors that have advanced digital solutions will enable remote asset monitoring, improved efficiency and enhanced reliability, as well as provide predictive maintenance benefits.\par \par \uc2 Building a successful alliance\par \par \uc2 Strategic alliances under Kerja Sama Operasi (KSO) are already being implemented in Indonesia, primarily in smaller fields. We see an opportunity for Indonesia to elevate these benefits and unlock further value.\par \par \uc2 Collaboration across key parties, including the Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry, the State-Owned Enterprises Ministry, the Upstream Oil and Gas Regulatory Special Task Force (SKKMigas) and \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 ,will be key to enhancing current KSO models to attract global contractors and promote collaboration in meeting the nation's production ambitions.\par \par \uc2 Based on our experience, there are four key factors that enable a successful strategic alliance:\par \par \uc2 Organization alignment & executive sponsorship: Mobilization of cross-functional teams with well-defined governance structures to accelerate decision-making and undertake interventions.\par \par \uc2 Flexible scope and robust management: Integrated program management to enable an agile scope of work and technology innovation.\par \par \uc2 Outcome-linked commercial model: A commercial model to incentivize and reward achievement and over-achievement of desired outcomes.\par \par \uc2 Medium-to-longer term partnership: Balancing the value of quick-win initiatives with the substantial benefits presented by long-term partnerships which catalyze knowledge transfer and sustainable cultural changes.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has ambitious goals to ensure energy security while building a more efficient oil and gas ecosystem. Meeting these targets could unlock benefits for the nation and the industry, and ensure that oil and gas continues to be an essential pillar of Indonesia's prosperity.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Henricus Herwin is a board member at the Society of Indonesian Petroleum Engineers (IATMI); Eddie Martono is partner at \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG) \uc2 and Pan Li is project leader at BCG.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210805eh850005m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
