\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 KADIN SUPPORTS GOVERNMENT'S  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  PROJECTIONS DESPITE  \highlight22\uc2 UNCERTAINTY \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 592 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 August 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) supports the government"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  projections submitted by President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  (Jokowi) in spite of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Kadin Chairman Arsjad Rasjid stated here on Tuesday that the association was also optimistic about the president"s statement that Indonesia would record an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of five percent in 2022 in line with the 2021 second-quarter growth.\par \par \uc2 However, Rasjid reminded the government to continue to prioritize the health recovery program as a vital solution to boosting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Kadin Indonesia feels realistic and optimistic that the government will achieve this growth rate. The point is that we support and offer advice to the government," Rasjid noted in a written statement.\par \par \uc2 Kadin believes that the government should apply three key policies in the midst of the pandemic that encompass efforts to prioritize health recovery, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  revival, and social protection.\par \par \uc2 "We have to realistically realize that we are currently living in a pandemic as the new norm of life," he affirmed.\par \par \uc2 Kadin and businesspersons have accepted the extension of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on community activities restrictions (PPKM), as they believe the decision was taken after meticulous calculation and deliberation, Rasjid noted.\par \par \uc2 However, the government should also take into account the possibility of opening up activities in the manufacturing and retail sectors on grounds that its workers adhere to strict health protocols and get vaccinated to ensure smooth running of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.\par \par \uc2 "This is part of the efforts to adapt to the new normal as an unavoidable situation in the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic," he affirmed.\par \par \uc2 While delivering the 2022 \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Bill (APBN) and the Financial Note at the parliament complex, President Jokowi was optimistic that Indonesia would record an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of around five to 5.5 percent in 2022 despite the situation still being overshadowed by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the COVID-19 pandemic. This projection is higher than the forecasted figure of five percent this year.\par \par \uc2 Apart from the COVID-19 pandemic, the president also highlighted the need for readiness to address other global challenges. To this end, the 2022 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be designed flexibly to respond to such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  but still reflect optimism and prudence.\par \par \uc2 According to Jokowi, the health \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is estimated to reach Rp255.3 trillion, or 9.4 percent of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The government also targets \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues in 2020 to reach Rp1,506.91 billion in the Draft State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  Year 2022, growing by 9.5 percent from the outlook for \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues of Rp1,375.8 trillion in 2021. However, in comparison with the target of Rp1,229.6 trillion in the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  Year 2021, the projected \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue in 2020 will increase by 22.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 "Refocusing and restructuring the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is deemed necessary in the era of the pandemic. However, health recovery and the provision of social assistance and \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  still rely on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Most importantly, (the government) needs to prioritize health and micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs). The government must also be careful regarding \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We believe all companies are keen to contribute by paying \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D he remarked.\par \par \uc2 However, the government must realize that several industries have been acutely affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, so \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  obligations are considered as burdensome. Hence, Rasjid has encouraged the government to delineate industries subject to \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and those eligible for relaxation.\par \par \uc2 (T.K012/A/H-FDH/H-FDH) 17-08-2021 19:35:27\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020210817eh8h001up\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Jokowi Introduces Expansive 2022  \highlight22\uc2 Budget \highlight\uc2  Bill, Promises Reform to Overcome Prolonged Pandemic, Uneven Global Recovery\b0\par\par\uc2 1,039 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 August 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo has introduced an expansive 2022 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  bill that contains a total of $188 billion in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to funds reforms in healthcare, social protection, and infrastructure programs in an attempt to overcome a prolonged pandemic and uneven global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery next year.\par \par \uc2 The president said that the government would need to spend a total of Rp 2,708 trillion ($188 billion) next year, up 0.4 percent from Rp 2,697 trillion this year's outlook. The revenue from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , dividends, royalties, or grants would reach Rp 1,841 trillion next year, increasing 6 percent from this year's outlook of Rp 1.736 trillion.\par \par \uc2 That resulted in Rp 868 trillion in deficits, of 4.85 percent of Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP), narrowing from this year's Rp 962 trillion \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  or 5.8 percent of GDP, Jokowi told the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in a speech after the state address on Monday.\par \par \uc2 "In 2022, we will still be faced with high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Jokowi said.\par \par \uc2 "We also have to be prepared to face other global challenges, such as threats climate change, increased geopolitical volatilities, and uneven global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. Therefore, the 2022 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be anticipatory, responsive, and flexible to respond to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but still reflects optimism and prudence," he said.\par \par \uc2 Next year, the government targeted GDP growth between 5 and 5.5 percent, up from an estimated 3.7 to 4.5 percent this year. Inflation would remain low at 3 percent, compared to this year's 1.8 to 2.5 percent projection.\par \par \uc2 That would allow the 10-year government bond's yield to remain at around 6.82 percent, compared to this year's expected range of 6.34 to 7.24 percent.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia could also expect a stable currency with the rupiah's exchange rate to hover around 14,350 against the US dollar, compared to the expected range of 14,200 to 14,600 this year.\par \par \uc2 The government saw oil prices in 2022 to increase to stay at $63 per barrel, from this year's $55-$65 price range, due to recovery in global demand, increase in oil production, geopolitical instability, and development of alternative energy sources.\par \par \uc2 Due to depleted wells, Indonesia's oil and gas production would struggle to maintain oil productivity at 703,000 barrels per day and gas at 1.04 million barrels of oil equivalent per day.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi said the government would focus on structural reforms to get more outcomes from efficient state \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The 2022 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation will be more focused to support the implementation of structural reforms, especially the acceleration of human resource development, through\par \par \uc2 reform in the fields of health, social protection, and education.\par \par \uc2 "Structural reforms are also directed at improving the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation, through regulatory reform and bureaucracy and sectoral support that encourages growth," Jokowi said.\par \par \uc2 Next year, the government seeks to spend Rp 255 trillion, or 9.4 percent of the total \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for healthcare. Apart from improving the pandemic handling efforts, Jokowi wanted to use the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to overhaul the country's healthcare system, particularly the primary care units, or Puskesmas.\par \par \uc2 The government would also allocate Rp 427.5 trillion social protection \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to help more than 161 million poor and vulnerable populations to meet their basic needs like food, housing, energy, and education.\par \par \uc2 To improve the country's human resources, the government would set aside an education \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 541.7 trillion, Jokowi said. For infrastructure development, on the other hand, the government only allocates Rp 384.8 trillion, focusing on affordable, reliable energy and food infrastructure, as well as information technology and communication infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Flexible Pandemic \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 Next year, the government would allocate Rp 321 trillion for Covid-19 Handling and National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery (PC-PEN) programs, down from Rp 744 trillion this year.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said the government prepared a special clause in the 2020 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  bill that allows the government to shift \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation without the House's approval, taking into account the possibility of the Covid-19 pandemic that could still turn worse next year.\par \par \uc2 "Of course, we know that Covid is an influencing factor and is highly considered in designing the 2022 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Sri Mulyani said during a press conference on Monday.\par \par \uc2 "So, we will also create a 2022 scheme where refocusing or reallocation will be carried out automatically, so it is hoped that it will not cause any disruption if there is a Covid-19 spike again as happened in the delta variant. We hope that doesn't happen, but the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  must prepare for things that are not wanted to happen in 2022," she said.\par \par \uc2 Targets\par \par \uc2 Presiden Jokowi said he hoped the next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  would help the government achieve its development targets, including a reduction of open unemployment to 5.5 to 6.3 percent, compared to 6.3 percent in February this year.\par \par \uc2 He said the government also sought to reduce the poverty rate to between 8.5 and 9.0 percent, from 10.1 percent this year, according to the latest statistics in March. The social protection \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would also help the country narrowing inequality, as measured by the Gini ratio, to the range of 0.376 to 0.378 next year from 0.384 this year.\par \par \uc2 Lastly, Jokowi said he would like to see Indonesia's development index improving to between 73.41 and 73.46 next year, from 71.8 currently.\par \par \uc2 Said Abdullah, the chairman of the House's budgetary body, said the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and targets were "realistic" given the constraints in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year. Still, the Indonesia Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) politician said the government should keep an eye on the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Next year would be the last year the government can run a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  exceeding 3 percent of the GDP threshold \u8212\'20\'14 which temporarily lifted last year to fight the pandemic \u8212\'20\'14 Said said. He hoped the government would be able to finance development programs from other sources than debts.\par \par \uc2 "More creative steps must be taken to optimize contribution from state-owned enterprises and investment," Said said.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020210817eh8h00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
